{"title_page": "Oxalis acetosella", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Common wood sorrel\n|image = Oxalis acetosella LC0190.jpg\n|genus = Oxalis\n|species = acetosella\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]\n}}\n[[Image:Oxalis acetosella 1885 crop.jpg|thumb|left|''Oxalis acetosella'', [[Otto Wilhelm Thom\u00e9]] ''Flora von Deutschland \u00d6sterreich und der Schweiz'' (1885)]]\n\n'''''Oxalis acetosella''''' ('''wood sorrel''' or '''common wood sorrel''') is a [[rhizome|rhizomatous]] [[flowering plant]] in the family ''[[Oxalidaceae]]'', common in most of [[Europe]] and parts of [[Asia]]. The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] ''acetosella'' refers to its sour taste. The common name '''wood sorrel''' is often used for other plants in the genus ''Oxalis''.  In much of its range it is the only member of its [[genus]] and hence simply known as \"the\" '''wood sorrel'''.  While common wood sorrel may be used to differentiate it from most other species of ''Oxalis'', in North America, ''[[Oxalis montana]]'' is also called common wood sorrel. It is also known as ''Alleluia'' because it blossoms between [[Easter]] and [[Pentecost]], when the [[Psalms]] which end with [[Hallelujah]] are sung.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe plant has trifoliate compound [[leaf|leaves]], the leaflets heart-shaped and folded through the middle, that occur in groups of three on petioles up to {{convert|10|cm}} long. It flowers from spring to midsummer with small white [[chasmogamous]] [[flower]]s with pink streaks. Red or violet flowers also occur rarely.<ref name=\"Clapham\">Clapham, A.R., Tutin, T.G. and Warburg E.F. 1968. ''Excursion Flora of the British Isles''.  Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0 521 04656 4}}</ref>{{rp|116}} During the night or when it rains the flowers close and the leaves fold.\n\nAs with other species of wood sorrel, the leaves are sometimes eaten. An [[oxalate]] called \"sal acetosella\" was formerly extracted from the plant, through boiling.\n\n[[Image:Oxalis sp. leaves - 20020616.jpg|thumb|220px|''Oxalis acetosella'' growing at [[Phoenix Park]], [[Dublin]], Ireland.]]\n\n''[[Anemone nemorosa]]'' (wood anemone) is similar. Both have white flowers, are small and are found in woody shady places.  ''Anemone nemorosa'' however has palmately lobed leaves and does not have true petals but large sepals which are petal-like.<ref>Parnell, J. and Curtis, T. 2012. ''Webb's An Irish Flora.'' Cork University Press. {{ISBN|978-185918-4783}}</ref>\n\n==Habitat==\nWoods and shady places in the northern hemisphere.<ref name=\"Clapham\"/>\n\n==Note==\nThe common wood sorrel is sometimes referred to as a [[shamrock]] and given as a gift on [[St. Patrick's Day]]. This is due to its trifoliate [[clover]]-like leaf, and to early references to shamrock being eaten. Despite this, it is generally accepted that the plant described as shamrock is a species of [[clover]], usually white clover (''[[Trifolium repens]]'').\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|author=[[Neltje Blanchan|Blanchan, Neltje]]|title=[[Wild Flowers Worth Knowing]]|year=2005|publisher=[[Project Gutenberg|Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation]]}}\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/oxalida/oxali/oxalace.html Den virtuella floran: ''Oxalis acetosella''] {{in lang|sv}} <!-- which fails to italicize the species name-->\n* [http://www.giftpflanzen.com/oxalis_acetosella.html Giftpflanzen.com &mdash; Waldsauerklee] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.oxalis-acetosella.com oxalis-acetosella.com &mdash; ''Oxalis acetosella''] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q158576}}\n\n[[Category:Oxalis|acetosella]]\n[[Category:Flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Europe]]\n[[Category:Hardwood forest plants]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Europe]]\n[[Category:Groundcovers]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Common wood sorrel\n|image = Oxalis acetosella LC0190.jpg\n|genus = Oxalis\n|species = acetosella\n|authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]\n}}\n[[Image:Oxalis acetosella 1885 crop.jpg|thumb|left|''Oxalis acetosella'', [[Otto Wilhelm Thom\u00e9]] ''Flora von Deutschland \u00d6sterreich und der Schweiz'' (1885)]]\n\n'''''Oxalis acetosella''''' ('''wood sorrel''' or '''common wood sorrel''') is a [[rhizome|rhizomatous]] [[flowering plant]] in the family ''[[Oxalidaceae]]'', common in most of [[Europe]] and parts of [[Asia]]. The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] ''acetosella'' refers to its sour taste. The common name '''wood sorrel''' is often used for other plants in the genus ''Oxalis''.  In much of its range it is the only member of its [[genus]] and hence simply known as \"the\" '''wood sorrel'''.  While common wood sorrel may be used to differentiate it from most other species of ''Oxalis'', in North America, ''[[Oxalis montana]]'' is also called common wood sorrel. It is also known as ''Alleluia'' because it blossoms between [[Easter]] and [[Pentecost]], when the [[Psalms]] which end with [[Hallelujah]] are sung.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe plant has trifoliate compound [[leaf|leaves]], the leaflets heart-shaped and folded through the middle, that occur in groups of three on petioles up to {{convert|10|cm}} long. It flowers from spring to midsummer with small white [[chasmogamous]] [[flower]]s with pink streaks. Red or violet flowers also occur rarely.<ref name=\"Clapham\">Clapham, A.R., Tutin, T.G. and Warburg E.F. 1968. ''Excursion Flora of the British Isles''.  Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0 521 04656 4}}</ref>{{rp|116}} During the night or when it rains the flowers close and the leaves fold.\n\nAs with other species of wood sorrel, the leaves are sometimes eaten. An [[oxalate]] called \"sal acetosella\" was formerly extracted from the plant, through boiling.\n\n[[Image:Oxalis sp. leaves - 20020616.jpg|thumb|220px|''Oxalis acetosella'' growing at [[Phoenix Park]], [[Dublin]], Ireland.]]\n\n''[[Anemone nemorosa]]'' (wood anemone) is similar. Both have white flowers, are small and are found in woody shady places.  ''Anemone nemorosa'' however has palmately lobed leaves and does not have true petals but large sepals which are petal-like.<ref>Parnell, J. and Curtis, T. 2012. ''Webb's An Irish Flora.'' Cork University Press. {{ISBN|978-185918-4783}}</ref>\n\n==Habitat==\nWoods and shady places in the northern hemisphere.<ref name=\"Clapham\"/>\n\n==Note==\nThe common wood sorrel is sometimes referred to as a [[shamrock]] and given as a gift on [[St. Patrick's Day]]. This is due to its trifoliate [[clover]]-like leaf, and to early references to shamrock being eaten. Despite this, it is generally accepted that the plant described as shamrock is a species of [[clover]], usually white clover (''[[Trifolium repens]]'').\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|author=[[Neltje Blanchan|Blanchan, Neltje]]|title=[[Wild Flowers Worth Knowing]]|year=2005|publisher=[[Project Gutenberg|Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation]]}}\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/oxalida/oxali/oxalace.html Den virtuella floran: ''Oxalis acetosella''] {{in lang|sv}} <!-- which fails to italicize the species name-->\n* [http://www.giftpflanzen.com/oxalis_acetosella.html Giftpflanzen.com &mdash; Waldsauerklee] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.oxalis-acetosella.com oxalis-acetosella.com &mdash; ''Oxalis acetosella''] {{in lang|de}}\n{{Commonscat|Oxalis acetosella|position=left}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q158576}}\n\n[[Category:Oxalis|acetosella]]\n[[Category:Flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Europe]]\n[[Category:Hardwood forest plants]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Europe]]\n[[Category:Groundcovers]]\n", "name_user": "Darorcilmir", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxalis_acetosella"}
{"title_page": "Yuzhnaya Anva River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Yuzhnaya Anva\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth             = [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]]\n  | progression       = [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva]]\u2192 {{RVeslyana}}\n  | length            = {{convert|18|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n'''Yuzhnaya Anva''' ({{lang-ru|\u042e\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u043d\u044c\u0432\u0430}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a [[:wikt:left bank|left]] tributary of the [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Veslyana River]]. The river is {{convert|18|km|mi}} long.<ref name=\"\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\">{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180047|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u042e\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u043d\u044c\u0432\u0430}}</ref> The main tributary is the Severnaya Anva River (left).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Yuzhnaya Anva River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]]\n  | progression       = \n  | length            = {{convert|18|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n'''Yuzhnaya Anva''' ({{lang-ru|\u042e\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u043d\u044c\u0432\u0430}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a [[:wikt:left bank|left]] tributary of the [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Veslyana River]]. The river is {{convert|18|km|mi}} long.<ref name=\"\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\">{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180047|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u042e\u0436\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u043d\u044c\u0432\u0430}}</ref> The main tributary is the Severnaya Anva River (left).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuzhnaya_Anva_River"}
{"title_page": "List of attacks related to secondary schools", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of attacks related to secondary schools''' that have occurred around the world. These are attacks that have occurred on school property or related primarily to school issues or events. A narrow definition of the word ''attacks'' is used for this list so as to exclude warfare, robberies, gang violence, public attacks (as in political protests), accidental shootings, and [[suicide]]s and [[murder\u2013suicide]]s by rejected spouses or suitors. Incidents that involved only staff who work at the school have been classified as belonging at [[List of rampage killers|List of workplace killings]]. It also excludes events where no injuries take place, if an attack is foiled.\n\nThe listed attacks include [[shooting]]s, [[stabbing]]s, [[Cutting|slashings]], [[bombing]]s, and [[Battery (crime)|beatings]] administered with [[blunt instrument]]s.\n\n==Secondary school incidents==\n\n===1850s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| November 2, 1853\n| [[Louisville, Kentucky]], United States\n| Matthew Ward\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n| A student, Matthew Ward, went to school and shot and killed Schoolmaster Mr. Butler for excessively punishing his brother the day before. He was acquitted.<ref>April 29, 1854,'' The New York Times''</ref>\n|-\n|July 6, 1858\n|[[Baltimore, Maryland]], United States\n|\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|The 15yr old son of Col. John T. Farlow (Baltimore's Marshal of Police 1867-70), was shot to death during a [[Sunday school|Sabbath School]] gathering. The shooter escaped, but several arrests were made.<ref>''Evening Star,'' Washington D.C., July 06, 1858</ref>\n|}\n\n===1860s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n|January 21, 1860\n|[[Todd County, Kentucky]], United States\n|\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|A son of Col. Elijah Sebree was shot dead by another student.<ref>''The Penny Press.'', Cincinnati, OH, January 21, 1860</ref>\n|-\n|April 2, 1867\n|[[Madison, Florida]], United States\n|Frank Pope\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|Frank Pope, a pupil at the St. John's seminary, shot and killed his teacher Mr. Bristow with a pistol.<ref>''Memphis Daily Appeal'', April 09, 1867</ref>\n|}\n\n===1870s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| February 1, 1872\n|[[Washington, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| Thomas McGiffen\n|\n|align=\"center\"|1\n| At the all-girls Union School, Thomas McGiffen, the 17-year-old son of Col. Norton McGiffin and brother of naval hero [[Philo McGiffin]], shot and seriously wounded the principal, Prof. Wilson, because the professor refused to deliver a note to a young lady for him.<ref>''The Sun,'' New York City, February 02, 1872</ref>\n|-\n|February 20, 1874\n|[[Agency, Montana]], United States\n|Thomas Sguires, 20\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|After being ejected from school for disobedience, Thomas Sguires, 20 years old, returned to the school yard a day or two later, and fatally shot Prof. Hayes three times.<ref>''Nebraska Advertiser'', February 26, 1874</ref>\n|-\n|May 24, 1879\n|[[Lancaster, New York]], United States\n| Frank Shugart\n| \n| align=\"center\"|1\n|Frank Shugart, a [[telegraph operator]], shot and severely injured Mr. Carr, superintendent of the stables at a girls' school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1879/05/26/archives/shot-by-a-telegraph-operator.html|work=The New York Times|title=Shot by a Telegraph Operator|date=May 26, 1879}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===1880s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| January 21, 1882\n| [[Red Bud, Illinois]], United States\n| James E. McBride, 17\n| align=\"center\"|1\n| \n| After striking student James McBride in the face, teacher Robert Bailey was fatally wounded in a scuffle, in which the student stabbed him twice with a knife he was using to sharpen a pencil.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1882/01/22/archives/a-teacher-stabbed-by-a-pupil.html A teacher stabbed by a pupil], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (January 22, 1882)</ref>\n|-\n| April 13, 1882\n| [[Huntsville, Texas]], United States\n| G. W. Gray\n|\n|align=\"center\"| 1\n| G. W. Gray, a student at the [[Sam Houston]] Normal School, shot and wounded another student, M. J. Jordan.  They were arguing over a comic valentine.<ref>''The Milan Exchange''(Milan, Tenn.), April 15, 1882</ref>\n|-\n| August 27, 1886\n| [[Charleston, West Virginia]], United States\n| John Griffith, 15\n|\n| align=\"center\"|1\n| After being reprimanded by his teacher, James Kiser, 15-year-old John Griffith, a student at a school in Jackson County, brought a knife and rocks to school the next morning. A struggle ensued in which student Griffith stabbed Kiser several times.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1886/08/29/archives/stabbed-by-a-pupil.html Stabbed by a pupil], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (August 29, 1886)</ref>\n|-\n| June 29, 1888\n| [[Dalby, Queensland]], Australia\n| Peterson\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n| A 12-year-old student named Peterson stabbed his teacher when he was chastised for chasing another boy with a knife.<ref>[http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/3479157 A school teacher stabbed], ''[[The Brisbane Courier]]'' (June 30, 1888)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1890s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 26, 1893\n|[[Plain Dealing, Louisiana]], United States\n|\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|align=\"center\"|1\n| During an evening school dance at Plain Dealing High School, a fight broke out. Two youths were shot dead, two more were fatally wounded, and the high school's Professor Johnson was shot in the arm.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 73, Number 117, 27 March 1893</ref>\n|-\n| January 26, 1899\n| [[Albany, Missouri]], United States\n| Charles Ayres\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n| When he got whipped by his teacher T. B. Hunter, 13-year-old student Charles Ayres drew a jackknife and slashed the teacher's throat.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1899/01/27/archives/schoolboy-stabs-a-teacher-jackknife-used-near-albany-mo-to-escape.html Schoolboy stabs teacher], ''[[The New York Times]] (January 27, 1899)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1900s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=78width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| September 15, 1900\n| [[Kharkiv]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| Iwanow\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| After failing an exam, [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] student Iwanow shot and killed principal Tschanowitsch with a revolver and also wounded a teacher named Horkiwicz, before surrendering to police.<ref>[http://dza.tessmann.it/tessmannPortal/Zeitungsarchiv/Seite/Zeitung/1/4/16.09.1900/43021/5 Die Rache des Gymnasiasten], ''Meraner Zeitung'' (September 16, 1900)</ref>\n|-\n| April 28, 1902\n| [[Kingston, Ontario]], Canada\n| Eric Sharp, 15\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Beatrice Holland, a 14-year-old student, is shot and killed by a fellow student at the Frontenac School. The shooter, 15-year-old Eric Sharp, fled the scene but later turned himself in to the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=nUouAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tX4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6854,2114367&dq=school+tragedy&hl=en |title=Shot By Schoolmate Frontenac School, Kingston, Scene of a Tragedy. Boy Killed Girl Pupil |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1902-04-29 |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 24, 1903\n| [[Inman, South Carolina]], United States\n| Reuben Pitts\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Edward Foster, a 17-year-old student at Inman High school, was shot and fatally wounded by his teacher Reuben Pitts after he tried to resist punishment. Pitts said the student struck the pistol he drew in self-defense, and it fired. Pitts was acquitted of murder.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/ajc_historic/access/559912722.html?dids=559912722:559912722&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Feb+25%2C+1903&author=&pub=The+Atlanta+Constitution&desc=CAROLINA+YOUTH+SHOT+BY+TEACHER&pqatl=google Carolina youth shot by teacher], ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' (February 25, 1903)</ref><ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/ajc_historic/access/560490212.html?dids=560490212:560490212&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Sep+20%2C+1903&author=&pub=The+Atlanta+Constitution&desc=REUBEN+PITTS+GETS+FREEDOM&pqatl=google Reuben Pitts gets freedom], ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' (September 20, 1903)</ref>\n|-\n|July 21, 1903\n|[[Jackson, Kentucky]], United States\n|\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n|At the Cave Run School, James Barrett and Mack Howard fought a duel with pistols over a card game, killing each other. Another student James Vires, aged 12, suffered a wound while sitting at his desk.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cdnc/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&cl=search&d=LAH19030722.2.14&srpos=1&e=20-07-1903-22-07-1903--en--20-LAH-1--txt-IN-barrett----|work=Los Angeles Herald, Volume XXX, Number 288|title=Deulists Fatally Shot|date=22 July 1903}}</ref>\n|-\n|April 6, 1904\n|[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| Henry Schaze\n|1 dead\n|\n|Two students had been fighting over a girl for the better part of a year. Finally Henry Schaze pushed 16-year-old Paul Jelick to the ground and shot him dead.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 95, Number 129, 7 April 1904</ref>\n|-\n|November 16, 1904\n|[[Riverside, California]], United States\n|\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n|At the Indian School, a gun fight broke out between pupils. Charles Colby was shot in the head, then returned fire, killing Tom Bucanoros and fatally wounding Fred Smith.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 96, Number 170, 17 November 1904</ref>\n|-\n|December 16, 1904\n|[[Magee, Mississippi]], United States\n| E. E. Mangum\n|1 dead\n|1 injured\n|E. E. Mangum was shot through the head and killed by the principal of the high school, Professor J. E. Woodward after the student argued about punishment of his son and the argument became violent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cdnc/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&cl=search&d=SFC19041217.2.76.22&srpos=1&e=15-12-1904-17-12-1904--en--20-SFC-1--txt-IN-mangum----|work=San Francisco Call, Volume 97, Number 17|title=High School Principal Shoots Irate Parent|date=17 December 1904}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 9, 1905\n|[[Colusa, California]], United States\n|William Ingrim\n| \n|2 injured\n|At the request of his childhood friend, Pearl Cruse, Elmer Hildreth a 17-year-old non-student, attended a meeting between Miss Cruse and her teacher which ended in \"a hand to hand\" encounter between teacher and pupil. Hildreth became involved in a physical confrontation with school trustee Ingrim, whom he shot. He was found to have acted in self-defense. Ingrim survived the shooting.<ref>''Colusa Sun Herald'' 15 February 1905</ref>\n|-\n| September 12, 1905\n| [[Athens, Tennessee]], United States\n| Ernest Powers, 15\n| 1 dead\n| \n| 15-year-old student Ernest Powers fatally stabbed his teacher Elbert Wattanbarger when he attempted to whip him for throwing stones.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1905/09/17/archives/surrender-boy-who-slew-teacher.html Surrender Boy Who Slew Teacher], ''The New York Times'' (September 17, 1905)</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1910s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 10, 1910\n| [[Ione, California]], United States\n| Albert Brown<br>Eugene Griffin\n|\n|\n| At the reform school, [[Preston School of Industry]], students Albert Brown and Eugene Griffin tried to escape after stealing a revolver from the school. They shot at Captain William H. White who pursued them. No one was hurt, but the two boys were transferred to the state penitentiary.<ref>''Amador Ledger,'' 11 March 1910</ref>\n|-\n| September 23, 1912\n| [[Sankt P\u00f6lten]], [[Austria]]\n| Rudolf Hlawat\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Rudolf Hlawat, a student at a [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in St. P\u00f6lten, shot at his teacher, Prof. Schmidt, with a revolver. He also shot at the school janitor before shooting himself twice in the head. Hlawat died in hospital, the only casualty.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19120924&seite=2&zoom=2 Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf den Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (September 24, 1912)</ref>\n|-\n| October 9, 1913\n| [[Szeged]], [[Hungary]]\n| Johann Skultety, 14\n| 1 dead\n| \n| After he had been reprimanded by his teacher, Prof. Horvarth, for missing classes, Johann Skultety, a gymnasium student in Szeged, barged into the classroom and fired with a revolver at the teacher, missing him. He committed suicide by shooting himself in the heart.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19131010&seite=3&zoom=2 Ein Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf seinen Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (October 10, 1913)</ref>\n|-\n| April 12, 1919\n| [[Ogden City, Utah]], United States\n| \n| \n|1 injured\n|During a high school assembly, six boys shot off their guns, with permission, thinking they were loaded with blanks. Teacher Miss Verna Davidson was shot in the foot.<ref>''The Ogden Standard,'' April 26, 1919</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1920s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n|February 14, 1920\n|[[Durant, Oklahoma]], United States\n|\n| \n|1 injured\n|At the Durant Normal School, teacher Albert McFarland, was shot and seriously wounded by one of his pupils.<ref>''The Daily Ardmoreite'' (Ardmore, Okla.), February 15, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|March 4, 1920\n|[[Cincinnati, Ohio]], United States\n| Lawrence Angel, 14\n| \n| 1 injured\n|Student, Lawrence Angel, 14 years old, shot his teacher Beatrice Conner through the arm for sending him to the principal's office.<ref>''The Bismarck Tribune'' (Bismarck, N.D.), March 04, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|March 12, 1920\n|[[Newberry, South Carolina]], United States\n|William Scott\n| \n|1 injured\n|William Scott, a student at the Helena Colored School, shot Henry Gray, another student.<ref>''The Herald and News''', (Newberry S.C.), March 12, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|May 1, 1920\n|[[Summerville, Georgia]], United States\n|Alexander Potter, 15\n| \n|\n|At the High School, student Alexander Potter, 15 years old, fired six shots at his teacher, Prof. Ransom, but missed, upset after a severe thrashing. Potter was sentenced to 6 years at a reform school.<ref>The Watchman and Southron.(Sumter, S.C.), May 05, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|November 4, 1920\n|[[Middlesboro, Kentucky]], United States\n| Adolphus Oaks\n| 1 dead\n|\n|Prof. Barnes of Middlesboro high school was fatally shot by Adolphus Oaks, for whipping his sister the week before. Oaks went to jail.<ref>''The Ogden Standard-Examiner'' (Ogden, Utah), November 05, 1920</ref>\n|-\n| May 6, 1925\n| [[Wilno]], Poland\n| Two to three students\n| 5+ dead\n| ~10 injured\n| [[Wilno school massacre]]. A massacre occurred at [[Joachim Lelewel]] high school in [[Wilno]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. At about 11 a.m., during the final exams, at least two eighth-grade students attacked the board of examiners with revolvers and hand grenades, killing at least one teacher, several students and themselves.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nfp&datum=19250507&seite=1&zoom=2 Revolversch\u00fcsse und Bombenw\u00fcrfe gegen Lehrer], ''[[Neue Freie Presse]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A16FF3B5B12738DDDAE0894DD405B858EF1D3 Bomb Kills Three Boy Raiders Who Shoot Up Vilna School], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref>\n|-\n| May 18, 1927\n| [[Bath, Michigan]], United States\n| [[Andrew Kehoe]], 55\n| 45\n| 58\n| [[Bath School disaster]]. School board member [[Andrew Kehoe]] set up a series of explosions in the [[Bath Consolidated School]].  Before blowing up the school, Kehoe murdered his wife and set fire to his farmhouse.  Kehoe detonated his shrapnel-filled vehicle outside the school, committing suicide and wounding others. The bombings constituted the deadliest act of mass murder in any type of school setting in U.S. history.\n|}\n\n===1930s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 5, 1931\n| [[Pristina]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n|\n|\n| 1 injured\n| A student named Ismailovic shot and stabbed his teacher several times at a gymnasium in Pristina after he had been expelled due to low grades. Ismailovic was later arrested at a cemetery when he tried to hang himself.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19310306&seite=5&zoom=2 Die Rache eines durchgefallenen Gymnasiasten], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (March 6, 1931)</ref>\n|-\n| September 14, 1934\n| [[Gill, Massachusetts]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Headmaster Elliott Speer was murdered by a shotgun blast through the window of his study at [[Northfield Mount Hermon School]]. The crime was never solved.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,848774,00.html |title=Education: Berkshire Mystery |publisher=Time.com |date=1937-06-07 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 24, 1937\n| [[Toledo, Ohio]], United States\n| Robert Snyder, 12\n|\n| 2 injured\n| 12-year-old Robert Snyder shot and wounded his principal, June Mapes, in her office at Arlington public school when she declined his request to call a classmate. He later shot and wounded himself but survived.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SO4KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z08DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4212,6557992&dq= Lay shooting to gang tales], ''Prescott Evening Courier'' (September 24, 1937)</ref>\n|-\n| June 24, 1939\n| Tirpan, Bulgaria\n| ..., 15\n| 4 dead\n| \n| A 15-year-old student killed three teachers with a revolver at a school in Tirpan, southern Bulgaria after being expelled. The boy, who had already been expelled from three other schools during the year for bad behaviour, afterwards committed suicide.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19390625&id=xec-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=KU0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=5076,7768567 Boy kills teachers], ''[[The Tuscaloosa News]]'' (June 25, 1939)</ref><ref>[http://www.wbc.poznan.pl/dlibra/plain-content?id=118487 Ucze\u0144 zastrzeli\u0142 nauczycielk\u0119 i pope\u0142ni\u0142 samob\u00f3jstwo], ''[[Or\u0119downik Wrzesi\u0144ski]]'' (July 4, 1939)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1940s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| May 6, 1940\n| [[South Pasadena, California]], United States\n| Verlin Spencer, 38\n| 5 dead\n| 2 injured\n| After being removed as principal of South Pasadena Junior High School, Verlin Spencer shot six school officials, killing five, before attempting to commit suicide by shooting himself in the stomach. He was sentenced to five consecutive life sentences, and was released early on parole in 1970.<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Process%20small/Newspapers/Oswego%20Palladium/Oswego%20Palladium%20May-June%201940%20pdf/Newspaper%20%20Oswego%20Palladium%20May-June%201940%20-%200085.pdf 4 dead, 3 dying from gunfire of ousted educator, ''Oswego Palladium-Times''] (May 7, 1940)</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1940/05/10/archives/5-dead-in-school-killings-teacher-at-pasadena-succumbs-slayer-in.html 5 dead in school killings], ''[[The 