 inside the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/13/americas/brazil-school-shooting/index.html/|title=At least 8 people were killed in a school shooting in Brazil |date=March 13, 2019 |work=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 7, 2019\n| Colorado, United States\n| Devon Erickson, 18; Maya Elizabeth, 16\n| 1 dead\n| 8 injured\n| At the [[STEM School Highlands Ranch]] two suspects, who were students at the school shot eight students and killed one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/08/us/denver-stem-shooting-heroes-run-hide-fight/index.html|title=Again in the age of 'run, hide, fight,' student heroes thwart a school shooter|first=Eliott C.|last= McLaughlin|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/08/us/kendrick-castillo-denver-stem-shooting/index.html|title=This student died trying to stop the Colorado school shooter|author1=Nicole Chavez |author2=Scott McLean|website=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 28, 2019\n| Volsk, Saratov Region, Russia\n| Daniil Pulkin\n| \n| 1 injured\n| In the afternoon of May 28, the teenager came to school with a bag containing an axe and molotov cocktails inside. First, Pulkin attempted to burn the office of his former form mistress. After that, he hit a 6th grader girl in the head with an axe.\n|-\n| August 8, 2019\n| Montgomery, Alabama\n| Isaiah Johnson, 38\n| 0\n| 0\n| 38-year old Isaiah Johnson dropped his son off at Blount Elementary School got into an argument with another father over a traffic dispute then discharged a firearm into the father's vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvtm13.com/article/2-arrested-after-road-rage-shooting-at-alabama-elementary-school/28647302|title=Back-to-school traffic leads to argument, shooting outside Alabama elementary school|first=The Associated|last=Press|date=August 8, 2019|website=WVTM}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apr.org/post/mental-evaluation-sought-school-traffic-shooting-suspect|title=Mental evaluation sought for school traffic shooting suspect|first=Associated|last=Press|website=www.apr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/crime/2019/08/26/isaiah-johnson-charged-escape-after-blount-elementary-shooting/2121409001/|title=Father charged in Blount Elementary shooting re-arrested after escaping treatment facility|first=Melissa|last=Brown|website=The Montgomery Advertiser}}</ref>\n|-\n| August 30, 2019\n| Mobile, Alabama\n| Deangelo Dejuan Parnell, 17\n| 0\n| 10 injured\n| Parnell shot 9 people during a confrontation at a stadium where a high school football game was being played. A tenth person suffered a stroke.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/31/us/mobile-alabama-football-shooting.html|title=At Least 10 Shot at Alabama High School Football Game, Police Say|first=Derrick Bryson|last=Taylor|date=August 31, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 1, 2019\n| [[Kuopio]], Finland\n| Joel Marin, 25\n| 1 dead\n| 10 injured\n| [[Kuopio school stabbing]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019 \n| Santa Clarita, California\n| Nathaniel Berhow, 16\n| 3 dead\n| 3 injured \n| [[Saugus High School shooting]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019\n| [[Blagoveshchensk]], Russia\n| Daniil Zasorin, 19\n| 2 dead\n| 3 injured\n| After being told to leave the classroom twice, Zasorin returned with a pump-action shotgun and opened fire in the room, shooting victims at their desks. He committed suicide after being wounded in the exchange of gunfire with the police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-college-shooting-daniil-zasorin-attack-death-toll-latest-today-a9202526.html|title=Gunman opens fire in deadly Russian college attack after posting bizarre message online|date=14 November 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\nSee also\n\n*[[School bullying]]\n*[[School shooting]]\n*[[List of school-related attacks]]\n*[[List of school shootings in the United States]]\n*[[List of attacks related to primary schools]]\n*[[List of attacks related to post-secondary schools]]\n*[[List of rampage killers: School massacres]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n<ref name=note_a>Including death or injury of attacker(s), when applicable.</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181140/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence00-01.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2000\u20132001], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181216/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence02-03.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2002\u20132003], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181239/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence04-05.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2004\u20132005], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181347/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence06-07.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2006\u20132007], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181441/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence07-08.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2007\u20132008], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181632/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence08-09.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2008\u20132009], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181945/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence09-10.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2009\u20132010], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:School-Related Attacks}}\n[[Category:Attacks on schools|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of schools|*]]\n[[Category:Crime-related lists]]\n[[Category:Secondary education-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of school-related attacks|secondary]]\n", "name_user": "BorderRegions", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1940s:Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_attacks_related_to_secondary_schools"}
{"title_page": "Gambling in Japan", "text_new": "Most forms of '''gambling in Japan''' are generally banned by the [[Criminal Code of Japan|Criminal Code]] chapter 23;<ref>{{in lang|en}} [http://www.cas.go.jp/jp/seisaku/hourei/data/PC.pdf Criminal Code of Japan] PDF</ref> however, there are several exceptions, including betting on [[horse racing]] and certain [[motor sports]].<ref name=\"sumo supremo\" />\n\nPublic sports, [[lottery]], and toto (football pools) are held under special laws in order to increase the income of national and local governments, as well as to offer a form of entertainment.\n\nSince 2018, casino operators have been bidding for three legal licenses to operate an integrated casino resort in Japan, including in [[Osaka]], [[Tokyo]], and [[Yokohama]]. The Japanese government established the Casino Administration Committee in 2020 to supervise and manage Japan's resort operators.\n\nA number of fictional franchises focus on gambling in Japan.\n\n==Public sports==\n''K\u014dei ky\u014dgi'' (\u516c\u55b6\u7af6\u6280, public sports) are public races that can be gambled on legally. There are four types: [[horse racing]], [[Keirin#Keirin in Japan|bicycle racing]], [[Ky\u014dtei|powerboat racing]], and [[Auto Race (Japanese sport)|asphalt speedway]] [[motorcycle speedway|motorcycle racing]]. They are allowed by special laws and are regulated by local governments or governmental corporations.\n\nThe prize pool for gamblers on these races are about 75-80% of total sales. Betting tickets are available at numerous circuits and ticket booths within many cities.\n\n==Lottery==\n[[File:Takarakuji Ikebukuro 2011.jpg|thumb|Small street shop, in [[Ikebukuro]], selling takarakuji tickets.]]\nTakarakuji (\u5b9d\u304f\u3058), i.e., lotteries, are held by [[Prefectures of Japan|prefectures]] or [[City designated by government ordinance|large cities]] on a regular basis all throughout the calendar year.\n\nThere are three main types of lotteries: unique number lotteries, selected number lotteries, and scratch cards. Each lottery ticket is sold at 100 to 500 yen, and the top cash prizes are usually 100 million yen or more.\n\nThe takarakuji law stipulates that the entire prize pool for any given lottery is to be less than 50% of total sales, with the rest going to local government organizations and charities. \n\nTakarakuji tickets are available at takarakuji booth and stores in many cities, with some outlets becoming particularly popular.<ref>[https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2009/11/30/business/takarakuji-whats-chance-got-to-do-with-it/#.Xk18iC2ZPOQ japantimes.com]</ref> Tickets for selected number lotteries can be also bought at some [[Automated teller machine|ATM]]s.\n\n==Pachinko==\n{{main article|Pachinko}}\n[[Pachinko]] is a [[pinball]]-like [[slot machine]] game. It is officially not considered gambling because Japanese laws regard pachinko as an exception to the criminal code on gambling for historical, monetary, and cultural reasons. Pachinko parlours can be found all over Japan, and they are operated by private companies. As of 2011, there are about 12,480 pachinko parlors in Japan.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031822/http://www.majiroxnews.com/2011/04/21/gov-sparks-pachinko-bashing/: Gov. sparks pachinko bashing]</ref> In 2018, Japan spent $200 billion on pachinko each year. Also, \"nearly half of all leisure time in Japan\" was spent in pachinko parlours.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-pachinko-gambling-japan-2018-7 businessinsider.com]</ref>\n\nIn pachinko, when a player's ball makes it into a special hole to activate the slot machine and a jackpot is made, they are rewarded with more balls. Players can then exchange the balls for prizes of different value at a booth in the parlour. Money cannot be awarded at pachinko parlors as this would be in violation of the criminal code. However, players almost always exchange pachinko balls for special tokens, usually slips of gold encased in plastic, and then \"sell\" them at a neighboring shop for cash. Usually such shops are also owned by the parlor operators, but as long as the winners do not receive cash in the parlour, the law is not broken.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120202214818/http://blog.thejapanesetutor.com/playing-pachinko-how-illegal-gambling-is-legal-in-japan-2010-09 Playing Pachinko: How Illegal Gambling Is Legal in Japan]</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2011, [[Shintaro Ishihara]], the previous Tokyo Governor, spoke against the pachinko parlours, arguing that the popular game together with vending machines were wasting electricity, at up about 1000&nbsp;[[kWh|kilowatts per hour]].{{clarify|reason=1000 kWh per what unit of time?|date=August 2016}} He said that following the consequences the earthquake of March 11, 2011, the government asked people to reduce energy consumption, but asking wasn't enough and the government order was not enacted.<ref name=\"https://www.expatbets.com/japan/top-poker-players-from-japan/\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.expatbets.com/japan/top-poker-players-from-japan/|title=Top Gambling players from Japan|access-date=2013-05-09}}</ref> In 2016, the Parliament voted to approve the said law that will eventually alter the gambling industry in Japan.<ref name=\"https://www.expatbets.com/japan/top-poker-players-from-japan/\"/><ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2011/04/11/tokyo-governor-takes-aim-at-vending-machines-pachinko/ Tokyo Governor Takes Aim at Vending Machines, Pachinko]</ref>\n\n==Illegal gambling==\n[[Yakuza]] are known to operate illegal casinos in Japan. In addition to traditional casino games, [[Mahjong]] can be played for money and many mahjong parlors have ties with the Yakuza to assist collecting debt from players who default.\n\nAnother illegal gambling opportunity is offered by mobile gambling sites. At these sites, Japanese gamblers can play [[rock-paper-scissors]] and win cash prizes. In 2010, the owner of one of these sites was arrested and confessed to earning over $1 million. The players purchased betting tickets for \u00a5315. They could win \u00a51,000 if they won three times in a row while \u00a510,000 was the prize for those who won five times in a row.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://factsanddetails.com/japan.php?itemid=793&catid=21&subcatid=144#10 |title=Gambling in Japan: Gambling in Japan: Bicycles, Boats and Horse Racing |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202161713/http://factsanddetails.com/japan.php?itemid=793&catid=21&subcatid=144#10 |archive-date=2011-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Casinos==\n===Efforts to legalize===\nThere were movements within the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP) government to open [[casino]]s to boost [[tourism in Japan]].<ref>[[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|LDP]] [http://www.jimin.jp/jimin/seisaku/2006/seisaku-006.html discussion about casinos in 2006] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109115230/http://www.jimin.jp/jimin/seisaku/2006/seisaku-006.html |date=2008-01-09 }}</ref>  Operating casinos remains illegal in Japan, and recent [[sports betting]] on [[baseball]] by [[sumo]] wrestlers has caused a scandal.<ref name=\"sumo supremo\">{{cite news  \n| url=  https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i7x6-jG-ZKv2x6ABoo2axM-VsGzw\n| title=  Japan's sumo supremo replaced\n| publisher=  AFP\n| date=  Aug 12, 2010\n| accessdate= 5 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, former mayor Ishihara proposed building casinos in [[Odaiba]], but despite the high public interest, the idea wasn't entirely approved. One of the arguments against the developments was that the Japanese being not used to gambling would be too prone to addiction.<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20000116a3.html Viva Odaiba! Ishihara dreams of casinos in the bay]</ref> Another possibility for the development of the casino industry in Japan is the creation of floating casinos. The idea of boat gambling has also been actively supported by Ishihara.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.japantraveler.com/issues/0005/racism.html |title=Racism in Japan: Racism as a Business Defence |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103144157/http://www.japantraveler.com/issues/0005/racism.html |archive-date=2013-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCasino legislation in Japan picked up fresh momentum with lawmakers submitting the Integrated Resort (IR) Enabling Act to the Diet in 2015.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/30/japan-casino-idUSL2N0WW0C520150330 reuters.com]</ref>\n\n===Legalization and bidding===\nIn July 2018, Japanese lawmakers approved a bill that officially allows casinos in the country. Three casinos in the form of integrated resorts (IRs) will be established in different locations. The IRs will come with restrictions and Japanese locals will only be able to visit the casinos three times per week, or ten times a month. Japanese visitors will also be charged a 6,000 yen entrance fee to help discourage addiction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20180720/p2g/00m/0fp/133000c|title=Japan's Diet approves opening of casino resorts despite opposition|date=July 20, 2018|website=The Mainichi|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOsaka was the first to launch the \u201cRequest For Proposal\u201d (RFP) process in 2019,<ref>[https://www.casino.org/news/osaka-begins-taking-applications-for-integrated-resort-proposals/ casino.org]</ref> and the five companies who applied for an Osaka integrated casino resort license are [[Las Vegas Sands]], [[Wynn Resorts]], [[MGM Resorts]], [[Melco Resorts & Entertainment|Melco Resorts]], and [[Genting Singapore]].<ref>[https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/the-race-for-a-japan-casino-license-is-now-mgm-resorts-to-lose-2019-11-10 nasdaq.com]</ref> Names of two gambling operators were not revealed as they had requested anonymity.<ref>[https://www.ggrasia.com/names-of-five-casino-firms-in-osaka-rfc-phase-revealed/ ggrasia.com]</ref> In February 2020 only MGM Resorts had submitted a bid in Osaka, with no bids put in by competing companies [[Galaxy Entertainment]] and Genting Singapore.<ref>[https://www.casino.org/news/mgm-resorts-is-the-lone-remaining-bidder-for-an-osaka-license/ casino.org]</ref> MGM was awarded the contract. Las Vegas Sands, Melco Resorts and Entertainment and Wynn Resorts all said they were instead focusing on [[Yokohama]] and [[Tokyo]] and the bidding processes there, for the remaining two licenses.<ref>[https://casinobeats.com/2020/02/17/osaka-closes-on-ir-partner-following-drop-outs/ casinobeats.com]</ref>\n\n===Casino Administration Committee===\nThe Japanese government established the Casino Administration Committee on January 7th, 2020. Intended to supervise and manage Japan's IR operators, it operates as an external department to the cabinet. The chairman is Michio Katamura. It will grant casino licenses and also be able to revoke them, and investigate operators and related officers.<ref>[https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/01/08/japan-formally-establishes-casino-administration-committee/ asgam.com]</ref>\n\n==Media depictions==\nGambling is the central theme of many Japanese fictional works, including manga, anime, film, and literature. Examples of gambling franchises include ''[[Kakegurui|Kakegurui (Compulsive Gambler)]]'', ''[[Kaiji (manga)|Gambling Apocalypse: Kaiji]]'', ''[[Usogui]]'', ''[[Akagi (manga)|Akagi]]'', ''[[Legendary Gambler Tetsuya]]'', ''[[Liar Game]]'', ''[[Mahjong Hish\u014d-den: Naki no Ry\u016b]]'', ''[[One Outs]]'', ''[[Rio: Rainbow Gate!]]'', and ''[[Tobaku Ha\u014dden Zero]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sports betting]]\n*[[Bookmaker]]\n*[[Yakuza]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gambling by country}}\n{{Japan topics}}\n\n[[Category:Gambling in Japan]]\n[[Category:Economy of Japan]]\n[[Category:Politics of Japan]]\n", "text_old": "Most forms of '''gambling in Japan''' are generally banned by the [[Criminal Code of Japan|Criminal Code]] chapter 23;<ref>{{in lang|en}} [http://www.cas.go.jp/jp/seisaku/hourei/data/PC.pdf Criminal Code of Japan] PDF</ref> however, there are several exceptions, including betting on [[horse racing]] and certain [[motor sports]].<ref name=\"sumo supremo\" />\n\nPublic sports, [[lottery]], and toto (football pools) are held under special laws in order to increase the income of national and local governments, as well as to offer a form of entertainment.\n\nSince 2018, casino operators have been bidding for three legal licenses to operate an integrated casino resort in Japan, including in [[Osaka]], [[Tokyo]], and [[Yokohama]]. The Japanese government established the Casino Administration Committee in 2020 to supervise and manage Japan's resort operators.\n\nA number of fictional franchises focus on gambling in Japan.\n\n==Public sports==\n''K\u014dei ky\u014dgi'' (\u516c\u55b6\u7af6\u6280, public sports) are public races that people in Japan can gamble on legally. There are four different types of ''k\u014dei ky\u014dgi'': [[horse racing]], [[Keirin#Keirin in Japan|bicycle racing]], [[Ky\u014dtei|powerboat racing]], and [[Auto Race (Japanese sport)|asphalt speedway]] [[motorcycle speedway|motorcycle racing]]. They are allowed by special laws and are regulated by local governments or governmental corporations.\n\nThe prize pool for the gamblers of these races are about 75-80% of total sales. Betting tickets are available at countless circuits and ticket booths within many cities, such as [[Tokyo]], [[Osaka]], [[Yokohama]], and [[Nagoya]].\n\n==Lottery==\n[[File:Takarakuji Ikebukuro 2011.jpg|thumb|Small street shop, in [[Ikebukuro]], selling takarakuji tickets.]]\nTakarakuji (\u5b9d\u304f\u3058), i.e., lotteries, are held by [[Prefectures of Japan|prefectures]] or [[City designated by government ordinance|large cities]] on a regular basis all throughout the calendar year.\n\nThere are three main types of lotteries: unique number lotteries, selected number lotteries, and scratch cards. Each lottery ticket is sold at 100 to 500 yen, and the top cash prizes are usually 100 million yen or more.\n\nThe takarakuji law stipulates that the entire prize pool for any given lottery is to be less than 50% of total sales, with the rest going to local government organizations and charities. \n\nTakarakuji tickets are available at takarakuji booth and stores in many cities, with some outlets becoming particularly popular.<ref>[https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2009/11/30/business/takarakuji-whats-chance-got-to-do-with-it/#.Xk18iC2ZPOQ japantimes.com]</ref> Tickets for selected number lotteries can be also bought at some [[Automated teller machine|ATM]]s.\n\n==Pachinko==\n{{main article|Pachinko}}\n[[Pachinko]] is a [[pinball]]-like [[slot machine]] game. It is officially not considered gambling because Japanese laws regard pachinko as an exception to the criminal code on gambling for historical, monetary, and cultural reasons. Pachinko parlours can be found all over Japan, and they are operated by private companies. As of 2011, there are about 12,480 pachinko parlors in Japan.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031822/http://www.majiroxnews.com/2011/04/21/gov-sparks-pachinko-bashing/: Gov. sparks pachinko bashing]</ref> In 2018, Japan spent $200 billion on pachinko each year. Also, \"nearly half of all leisure time in Japan\" was spent in pachinko parlours.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-pachinko-gambling-japan-2018-7 businessinsider.com]</ref>\n\nIn pachinko, when a player's ball makes it into a special hole to activate the slot machine and a jackpot is made, they are rewarded with more balls. Players can then exchange the balls for prizes of different value at a booth in the parlour. Money cannot be awarded at pachinko parlors as this would be in violation of the criminal code. However, players almost always exchange pachinko balls for special tokens, usually slips of gold encased in plastic, and then \"sell\" them at a neighboring shop for cash. Usually such shops are also owned by the parlor operators, but as long as the winners do not receive cash in the parlour, the law is not broken.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120202214818/http://blog.thejapanesetutor.com/playing-pachinko-how-illegal-gambling-is-legal-in-japan-2010-09 Playing Pachinko: How Illegal Gambling Is Legal in Japan]</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2011, [[Shintaro Ishihara]], the previous Tokyo Governor, spoke against the pachinko parlours, arguing that the popular game together with vending machines were wasting electricity, at up about 1000&nbsp;[[kWh|kilowatts per hour]].{{clarify|reason=1000 kWh per what unit of time?|date=August 2016}} He said that following the consequences the earthquake of March 11, 2011, the government asked people to reduce energy consumption, but asking wasn't enough and the government order was not enacted.<ref name=\"https://www.expatbets.com/japan/top-poker-players-from-japan/\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.expatbets.com/japan/top-poker-players-from-japan/|title=Top Gambling players from Japan|access-date=2013-05-09}}</ref> In 2016, the Parliament voted to approve the said law that will eventually alter the gambling industry in Japan.<ref name=\"https://www.expatbets.com/japan/top-poker-players-from-japan/\"/><ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2011/04/11/tokyo-governor-takes-aim-at-vending-machines-pachinko/ Tokyo Governor Takes Aim at Vending Machines, Pachinko]</ref>\n\n==Illegal gambling==\n[[Yakuza]] are known to operate illegal casinos in Japan. In addition to traditional casino games, [[Mahjong]] can be played for money and many mahjong parlors have ties with the Yakuza to assist collecting debt from players who default.\n\nAnother illegal gambling opportunity is offered by mobile gambling sites. At these sites, Japanese gamblers can play [[rock-paper-scissors]] and win cash prizes. In 2010, the owner of one of these sites was arrested and confessed to earning over $1 million. The players purchased betting tickets for \u00a5315. They could win \u00a51,000 if they won three times in a row while \u00a510,000 was the prize for those who won five times in a row.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://factsanddetails.com/japan.php?itemid=793&catid=21&subcatid=144#10 |title=Gambling in Japan: Gambling in Japan: Bicycles, Boats and Horse Racing |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202161713/http://factsanddetails.com/japan.php?itemid=793&catid=21&subcatid=144#10 |archive-date=2011-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Casinos==\n===Efforts to legalize===\nThere were movements within the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP) government to open [[casino]]s to boost [[tourism in Japan]].<ref>[[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|LDP]] [http://www.jimin.jp/jimin/seisaku/2006/seisaku-006.html discussion about casinos in 2006] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109115230/http://www.jimin.jp/jimin/seisaku/2006/seisaku-006.html |date=2008-01-09 }}</ref>  Operating casinos remains illegal in Japan, and recent [[sports betting]] on [[baseball]] by [[sumo]] wrestlers has caused a scandal.<ref name=\"sumo supremo\">{{cite news  \n| url=  https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i7x6-jG-ZKv2x6ABoo2axM-VsGzw\n| title=  Japan's sumo supremo replaced\n| publisher=  AFP\n| date=  Aug 12, 2010\n| accessdate= 5 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, former mayor Ishihara proposed building casinos in [[Odaiba]], but despite the high public interest, the idea wasn't entirely approved. One of the arguments against the developments was that the Japanese being not used to gambling would be too prone to addiction.<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20000116a3.html Viva Odaiba! Ishihara dreams of casinos in the bay]</ref> Another possibility for the development of the casino industry in Japan is the creation of floating casinos. The idea of boat gambling has also been actively supported by Ishihara.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.japantraveler.com/issues/0005/racism.html |title=Racism in Japan: Racism as a Business Defence |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103144157/http://www.japantraveler.com/issues/0005/racism.html |archive-date=2013-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCasino legislation in Japan picked up fresh momentum with lawmakers submitting the Integrated Resort (IR) Enabling Act to the Diet in 2015.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/30/japan-casino-idUSL2N0WW0C520150330 reuters.com]</ref>\n\n===Legalization and bidding===\nIn July 2018, Japanese lawmakers approved a bill that officially allows casinos in the country. Three casinos in the form of integrated resorts (IRs) will be established in different locations. The IRs will come with restrictions and Japanese locals will only be able to visit the casinos three times per week, or ten times a month. Japanese visitors will also be charged a 6,000 yen entrance fee to help discourage addiction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20180720/p2g/00m/0fp/133000c|title=Japan's Diet approves opening of casino resorts despite opposition|date=July 20, 2018|website=The Mainichi|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOsaka was the first to launch the \u201cRequest For Proposal\u201d (RFP) process in 2019,<ref>[https://www.casino.org/news/osaka-begins-taking-applications-for-integrated-resort-proposals/ casino.org]</ref> and the five companies who applied for an Osaka integrated casino resort license are [[Las Vegas Sands]], [[Wynn Resorts]], [[MGM Resorts]], [[Melco Resorts & Entertainment|Melco Resorts]], and [[Genting Singapore]].<ref>[https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/the-race-for-a-japan-casino-license-is-now-mgm-resorts-to-lose-2019-11-10 nasdaq.com]</ref> Names of two gambling operators were not revealed as they had requested anonymity.<ref>[https://www.ggrasia.com/names-of-five-casino-firms-in-osaka-rfc-phase-revealed/ ggrasia.com]</ref> In February 2020 only MGM Resorts had submitted a bid in Osaka, with no bids put in by competing companies [[Galaxy Entertainment]] and Genting Singapore.<ref>[https://www.casino.org/news/mgm-resorts-is-the-lone-remaining-bidder-for-an-osaka-license/ casino.org]</ref> MGM was awarded the contract. Las Vegas Sands, Melco Resorts and Entertainment and Wynn Resorts all said they were instead focusing on [[Yokohama]] and [[Tokyo]] and the bidding processes there, for the remaining two licenses.<ref>[https://casinobeats.com/2020/02/17/osaka-closes-on-ir-partner-following-drop-outs/ casinobeats.com]</ref>\n\n===Casino Administration Committee===\nThe Japanese government established the Casino Administration Committee on January 7th, 2020. Intended to supervise and manage Japan's IR operators, it operates as an external department to the cabinet. The chairman is Michio Katamura. It will grant casino licenses and also be able to revoke them, and investigate operators and related officers.<ref>[https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/01/08/japan-formally-establishes-casino-administration-committee/ asgam.com]</ref>\n\n==Media depictions==\nGambling is the central theme of many Japanese fictional works, including manga, anime, film, and literature. Examples of gambling franchises include ''[[Kakegurui|Kakegurui (Compulsive Gambler)]]'', ''[[Kaiji (manga)|Gambling Apocalypse: Kaiji]]'', ''[[Usogui]]'', ''[[Akagi (manga)|Akagi]]'', ''[[Legendary Gambler Tetsuya]]'', ''[[Liar Game]]'', ''[[Mahjong Hish\u014d-den: Naki no Ry\u016b]]'', ''[[One Outs]]'', ''[[Rio: Rainbow Gate!]]'', and ''[[Tobaku Ha\u014dden Zero]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sports betting]]\n*[[Bookmaker]]\n*[[Yakuza]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gambling by country}}\n{{Japan topics}}\n\n[[Category:Gambling in Japan]]\n[[Category:Economy of Japan]]\n[[Category:Politics of Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic sports:More direct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gambling_in_Japan"}
{"title_page": "Last Week Tonight with John Oliver", "text_new": "{{short description|American late-night talk show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Last Week Tonight {{nowrap|with John Oliver}}\n| show_name_2        = Last Week Tonight\n| image              = Last Week Tonight.svg\n| image_alt          = Black and red text on a white background reading \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\".\n| caption            =\n| genre              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Comedy]]\n* [[News satire]]\n* [[Political satire]]\n* [[Talk show]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[John Oliver]]\n| writer             = <!-- Per infobox template rules, writer(s) should not be included if series has 5+ writers -->\n| director           = {{plainlist|\n* Joe Perota\n* Christopher Werner\n* Jim Hoskinson\n* Paul Pennolino\n* Bruce Leddy\n}}\n| presenter          = John Oliver\n| starring           =\n| narrated           = [[David Kaye (voice actor)|David Kaye]]\n| opentheme          = \"Go\" by [[Valley Lodge (band)|Valley Lodge]]<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=476822910494310400|date=June 11, 2014|title=By the way, our theme song \"Go\" is performed by the excellent rock band @ValleyLodge!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Hill|title=Valley Lodge's \"Go\" Is the Theme Song for \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\" on HBO|url=http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|publisher=DaveHillOnline.com|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=April 2, 2016|author-link=Dave Hill (comedian)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401105027/http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 7\n| num_episodes       = 187\n| list_episodes      = List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes\n| executive_producer = {{plainlist|\n* John Oliver\n* [[Tim Carvell]]\n* Liz Stanton\n* James Taylor\n* [[Jon Thoday]]\n}}\n| location           = [[CBS Broadcast Center]]<br />New York, New York\n| runtime            = 30\u201340 minutes<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=927269314025140225|date=November 5, 2017|title=You got an extra hour of sleep this morning, so you should be well-rested for tonight's 40-minute episode that starts at 11:15.}}</ref>\n| company            = {{plainlist|\n* Avalon Television\n* Partially Important Productions\n}}\n| distributor        = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network            = [[HBO]]\n| picture_format     = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format       = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2014|4|27}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| website            = http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver\n}}\n'''''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver''''' (often abridged as '''''Last Week Tonight''''') is an American [[late-night talk show|late-night talk]] and [[news satire]] television program hosted by comedian [[John Oliver]].<ref name=\"order\">{{cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |date=February 12, 2014 |title=HBO Sets Name & Date For John Oliver Debut |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |url-status=live |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214111313/http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |archivedate=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> The half-hour-long show premiered on Sunday, April 27, 2014, on [[HBO]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|title=John Oliver's HBO Series Gets Name, April Premiere|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|accessdate=March 10, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324102357/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|archive-date=March 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Last Week Tonight'' shares some similarities with [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[The Daily Show]]'' (where Oliver was previously [[List of The Daily Show correspondents|featured as a correspondent]] and fill-in host), as it takes a satirical look at news, politics and current events, but on a weekly basis.<ref name=\"order\"/>\n\nOliver has stated that he has \"full [[artistic freedom|creative freedom]], including free rein to [[Criticisms of corporations|criticize corporations]]\". His initial contract with HBO was for two years with an option for extension.<ref name=\"freedom\">{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|title=John Oliver on the Luxurious 'Freedom' of HBO, His Complicated Relationship With NYC|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 19, 2014|date=April 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418232827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|archive-date=April 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, HBO announced that the show had been renewed for three additional seasons of 30 episodes each, keeping the show on the air through 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |title=John Oliver Extends HBO Contract Through 2020 |last=Koblin |first=John |work=The New York Times |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=September 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912182739/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |archive-date=September 12, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show's seventh season, the last season promised by the 2017 renewal announcement, premiered on February 16, 2020.<ref name=\"S6\">{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Gets Season 6 Premiere Date On HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |accessdate=January 2, 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 2, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102235844/https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |archive-date=January 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nOliver described his preparations for the show to an interviewer for ''[[The Atlantic#The Wire|The Wire]]'': \"... I basically have to watch everything. The only thing I kind of watch for pleasure is [[Fareed Zakaria GPS|Fareed Zakaria's show]] on Sundays ... That and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' I watch for pleasure, or maybe ''[[Frontline (American TV program)|Frontline]]'' ... I have a TV on in my office all the time and I'll generally flick around on that from [[CNN]], [[Fox News|Fox]], [[MSNBC]], [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], [[Al Jazeera America|Al Jazeera]] ... I'm watching with a certain thing in mind and that is how to see a story told badly.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |author= Zuckerman, Esther |date= May 1, 2014 |title= John Oliver: What I Read |work= The Wire |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504083727/http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nHe said to another interviewer that he is concerned about dealing with [[news values|old news]]:\n\n<blockquote>If something happens on a Monday, realistically all the meat is going to be picked off that bone by the time it gets to us&nbsp;\u2014 there's probably barely a point in doing it ... I think we'll be attracted to some extent by stories that are off the grid ... Our show may end up skewing more international in terms of stories.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better |title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Changing journalism for the better |last=Hoxie |first=Angie |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218055110/http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better/ |archive-date=February 18, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[Tim Carvell]], executive producer of ''Last Week Tonight'', explained in an interview how the cast and crew deal with a half hour of Oliver speaking without any [[Television advertisement|commercial]] breaks.<ref name=\"usnews\">{{cite web |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |author= Sneed, Tierney |date= April 22, 2014 |title= Why ''Last Week Tonight'' Will Not Just Be ''The Daily Show'' on Sundays |work= [[U.S. News & World Report]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504081746/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Structural considerations are leading to changes in the content in the show that will inherently make it different from ''The Daily Show'' ... We realized early on, you don't necessarily want to hear anybody talk to you for a half an hour straight&nbsp;\u2013 even John, who is very charming&nbsp;\u2013 so we are constructing these little, produced comedy elements that will serve the function of commercial breaks throughout the show, which will let us get out of the studio, get us away from John's voice and break the show up a bit.}}\n\nCarvell also revealed that HBO gave them freedom in choosing guests for the show, advising them not to feel obligated to feature celebrities.<ref name=\"usnews\" /> When asked by an interviewer about \"[[correspondent]]s\" such as those featured on ''The Daily Show'', Oliver replied, \"we're not going to be a parody news show, so no people pretending to be journalists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|last=Furlong|first=Maggie|title='Last Week Tonight,' Two Days Later: John Oliver on His First Show, Dream Guests, and Old White Racists|website=Yahoo!|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619185957/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the fifth episode of season 7, Oliver stated that the studio and the show's offices were shut down after employees tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and that the show would go on temporary hiatus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/films-tv-delayed-coronavirus-canceled-1203532033/|title=All the Shows and Movies Shut Down or Delayed Because of Coronavirus|publisher=Variety|date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The show returned on March&nbsp;29, filmed from Oliver's home, to cover the coronavirus and the response to it.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/john-oliver-coronavirus-last-week-tonight-march-29.html</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2015}}\nThe format is similar to ''[[The Daily Show]]'', with Oliver sitting at a desk in front of a backdrop of a skyline containing buildings from around the world, often relating to the current topic. Unlike ''The Daily Show'', Oliver tends to explore one concept in depth but retains the appearance of commercial breaks to intercut larger topics with smaller segments that are not necessarily related to the topic at hand. The show is taped in front of a [[studio audience]], and HBO offers a limited number of free tickets to attend each week's ''Last Week Tonight'' taping. As of March 15, 2020 the show is being filmed with no live audience at an unspecified studio location due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\nThe show's theme starts off every episode containing images relating to it or the world at large with satirical captions written in [[dog Latin]]. Each episode covers a small handful of shorter segments, and then one main segment. While the short segments almost always relate to recent news, the episode's main segment usually covers in length and detail a political issue, even if that issue did not have news media attention during the preceding week. On occasion, the short segments are omitted and the main segment takes up the entirety of the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|last=Framke|first=Caroline|title=John Oliver on making Last Week Tonight and why he won't focus on the 2016 election|website=Vox|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=March 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320052802/http://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|archive-date=March 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver injects humor into his presentation, including satirical [[analogies]], and allusions to popular culture and celebrities. The show includes a panel in the upper-left corner that frequently displays a photo or graphic for that accompanies subject at hand, which aids in the humor. A full-screen graphic will show and play a video clip (such as excerpts from news show or documentaries) when Oliver is citing it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|title=Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' is The Next Generation of Late Night|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|website=IndieWire|language=en|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904015651/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|archive-date=September 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He often coins [[hashtag|hashtags]] related to his segment for use in [[social media]], some of which go [[Viral phenomenon|viral]].<ref name=Emertainment>{{cite web|url=http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|last=Solomon|first=Emily|title=How John Oliver Gets Social Media Right While the Rest of Traditional Media Fails|work=Emertainment Monthly|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404222905/http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|archive-date=April 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA recurring element of the show is Oliver's use of mascots. The mascots used in the show include Jeff the Diseased Lung in a Cowboy Hat, Hoots the NSA Owl, Taryn the Tinder Chicken, and the Last Week Tonight puppets.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ranker.com/list/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-mascots/ranker-tv | title=All the Mascot Costumes from Last Week Tonight, Ranked}}</ref> Oliver told Vulture in February 2019, \"I mean, the truth of the mascots is that we have a gigantic room filled with spectacular mascot costumes now. [Executive producer] Tim Carvell and I \u2014 I think we\u2019ve always seen the show as our attempt to make The Muppet Show and failing to do so. But occasionally, just occasionally, you get the kind of Muppet Show adoration in the ludicrous mascots.\"<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-hbo-interview-mascots.html</ref>\n\nThe typical structure of the show is to open with a recap of a few of the week's news stories, segue into a video compilation, and then move on to Oliver's main segment. Some of the episodes will follow up the main segment with another video compilation or news story. Oliver's speech is broken up with video compilations of recent news clips, or recurring segments, into which Oliver segues with the slogan, \"And now, this.\" Oliver has also ended some segments with mock trailers for fictional TV shows or commercials that satirize the subject of his speech.\n\n=== Celebrity guests===\nThe show frequently features one or more celebrity guests in its segments to help Oliver better get his point on the week's topic across. Guests have featured in many different capacities including giving monologues directly to camera, being interviewed by Oliver, playing musical numbers, participating in comedic skits with or without Oliver, or starring in fictitious parody [[Public service announcement|PSAs]]. On the show, guests are sometimes seen in the Last Week Tonight studio itself doing their part during the show's main taping, while at other times they are seen in video clips that were pre-recorded at a different location and later included in the show. Oliver often interviews personalities who were directly involved in or impacted by the issues being discussed in the show to get their first-hand experiences and viewpoints on the issue. Some of the famous personalities Oliver has interviewed include [[Edward Snowden]], the [[14th Dalai Lama|14th]] [[Dalai Lama]], [[Anita Hill|Professor Anita Hill]] and [[Monica Lewinsky]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n{{:List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n\n==YouTube channel==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a [[YouTube]] channel where videos are intermittently (depending on series) added after a show has aired.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |title=Last Week Tonight channel |access-date=March 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313183030/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Most of the videos are of the main segment from each episode. Some extended clips are also available on the show's YouTube channel, as are \"Web Exclusives\" that are produced solely for the channel, such as a July 2016 video in which Oliver responded to negative comments left on the channel itself.<ref name=Emertainment/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Framke |first1=Caroline |title=John Oliver ends 2016 by confronting Last Week Tonight's role in the liberal echo chamber |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |website=Vox |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=November 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163235/https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rhodan |first1=Maya |title=Watch John Oliver Read Mean 'Fan Mail' from YouTube |url=http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |website=Time |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501084644/http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |archive-date=May 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe show's production has also created content specifically for fan use. For the March 19, 2017, episode, which reported on Bolivia's growing coalition of workers clad in zebra suits to educate civilians about traffic laws, the show's production recorded 23 minutes of a person in a zebra costume dancing and gesticulating before a green screen so that viewers could edit it into other videos for humorous effect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=John Oliver Slams Trump's Budget, Lightens Mood with Dancing Zebras |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608152244/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |archive-date=June 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A similar video called \"Real Animals, Fake Paws\" for use in reenacting [[U.S. Supreme Court]] cases was released after the October 19, 2014, episode where dogs were used instead of justices to make listening to oral court cases more amusing to the general public and to increase interest in the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|title=Real Animals, Fake Paws Footage: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|last=LastWeekTonight|date=October 19, 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube|access-date=June 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620155905/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|archive-date=June 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2015, the channel had attained over a million subscribers.<ref name=Emertainment/> That number had risen to 3.6 million by July 2016,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Durkin |first1=J.D. |title=Oliver Responds to Harsh YouTube Comments in Newest Last Week Tonight Segment |url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |website=Mediaite |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163915/https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and over 5 million by May 2017. {{As of|2020|April|df=}}, the channel had over 7.8 million subscribers and more than 2.4 billion views.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about \"Last Week Tonight\" videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304225649/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about |date=March 4, 2017 }}. YouTube. Retrieved April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Social media ==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a Facebook page with over 2.6 million likes, a Twitter account with over 2.9 million followers, and an Instagram account with more than 450,000 followers {{As of|2019|July|lc=y|df=}}.\n\nOliver often makes use of joke [[hashtags]] to facilitate the [[viral spread]] of his videos on [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]], as with the hashtag #NotMyChristian, which he used in 2014 to complain about the casting of actor [[Jamie Dornan]] in the feature film adaptation of ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''. The hashtag became a recurring punchline on the show, mentioned in both serious stories and casual segues.<ref name=\"Emertainment\" />\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:John Oliver 2014.jpg|thumb|250x250px|John Oliver, host of ''Last Week Tonight'']]\nOliver's debut show garnered 1.11 million viewers. The number of viewers online, through websites such as YouTube showing extended clips of different segments, have steadily climbed into multiple millions. The show's YouTube channel also features Web Exclusives which are occasionally posted when the main show is taking a week off. Across the TV airings, [[Digital video recorder|DVR]], [[Video on demand|on-demand]] and [[HBO Go]], ''Last Week Tonight'' averaged 4.1 million weekly viewers in its first season.<ref>{{cite news |last= O'Connell |first= Michael |title= John Oliver's Talk Show Ratings Edging Out HBO Colleague Bill Maher |work= The Hollywood Reporter |date= September 9, 2014 |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |accessdate= December 23, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013001/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |archive-date= December 17, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n''Last Week Tonight'' has received widespread critical acclaim. Matthew Jacobs of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' named Oliver's program as 2014's best television show, writing \"the year's most surprising contribution to television is a show that bucked conventional formats, left us buzzing and paved the way for a burgeoning dynasty. ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' is 2014's crowning achievement.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Jacobs |first= Matthew |title= Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Was 2014's Best Show |work= The Huffington Post |date= December 8, 2014 |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |accessdate= December 9, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141209032042/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |archive-date= December 9, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' compared Oliver's program with ''The Daily Show'' several times in his review of Oliver's debut:\n\n<blockquote>Another scathing, stick-it-to-'em critique of American [[mass media]] and politics shellacked in satire and delivered by a funny if almost off-puttingly incredulous man with a British accent ... Exactly like ''The Daily Show'', the goal is to make elected and appointed officials, as well as just about any corporate enterprise, look foolish and inept while slyly culling together television news clips that make the media look equally inept at covering such evident truths.<ref>{{cite news |last= Stuever |first= Hank |title= John Oliver's 'Last Week Tonight' on HBO sticks to a familiar formula |work= The Washington Post |date= April 28, 2014 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150508221812/http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |archive-date= May 8, 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[James Poniewozik]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly compared ''Last Week'' with ''The Daily Show'', but also wrote that the \"full half-hour gives Oliver the room to do more,\" and praised Oliver's \"sharper tone and his globalist, English-outsider perspective,\" as well as his \"genuine passion over his subjects.\" Poniewozik wrote that Oliver's debut was \"a funny, confident start.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |author= Poniewozik, James |date= April 28, 2014 |title= REVIEW: Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |work= Time |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503214147/http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review began by ringing the same changes: \"The fear with ''Last Week Tonight'' is that it's ''The Daily Show'' except once a week&nbsp;\u2014 a staggered timeline that would rob the basic news-punning format of its intrinsic topical punch ... The first episode of his HBO series didn't stray far from the [[Jon Stewart|[Jon] Stewart]] mothership, stylistically ...\" However, the reviewer, Darren Franich, liked that Oliver has \"a half-hour of television that is simultaneously tighter and more ambitious, that the extra production time leads to sharper gags but also the ability to present more context\" and thought that the debut had \"plenty of funny throwaway lines.\" Franich appreciated Oliver's coverage of [[2014 Indian general election|the 2014 Indian election]], which the American press was largely ignoring,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |last= Ayres |first= Alyssa |date= May 1, 2014 |title= Thanks, John Oliver! Why India Isn't a Big Focus for U.S. Television |work= [[Forbes]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504055011/http://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> and, like Poniewozik, praised Oliver's \"passion.\" Franich concluded that ''Last Week Tonight'' \"suggested the sharpest possible version of its inspiration\" and that it \"should feel like an experiment\" but \"felt almost fully formed.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |last= Franich |first= Darren |date= April 28, 2014 |title= 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' review: The Weekly Show |work= Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503045808/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nDavid Haglund of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' was ambivalent, writing that the show is \"obviously a work in progress\" and that one segment \"felt like misplaced overkill,\" but also that it is \"good use of a weekly show, and it was funny to boot.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |last= Haglund |first= David |date= April 2014 |title= Last Week Tonight: Like The Daily Show, With Unbleeped Swears! |work= Slate |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504203605/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> [[Gawker]]'s Jordan Sargent claimed ''Last Week Tonight'' was \"the new ''Daily Show'',\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |author=Sargent, Jordan |date=May 6, 2014 |title=John Oliver's Last Week Tonight is the New Daily Show |publisher=Gawker |accessdate=May 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507030451/http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |archivedate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref> while simultaneously criticizing the ''Daily Show'' for abandoning those \"who have moved on from caring about [[Fox News|Fox [News]]] and [[Republican Party of the United States|Republicans]].\"\n\nA number of commentators from mainstream media outlets, including ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|title=John Oliver's Complicated Fun Connects for HBO|date=November 16, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Carr|first=David|newspaper=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501135440/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|archive-date=May 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Huffington Post'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814125641/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archivedate=August 14, 2015|title=John Oliver Is Doing Some Really Good Investigative Journalism|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|title=Unfortunately, John Oliver, You Are a Journalist|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|work=Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725193947/http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|archive-date=July 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|title=With journalism in quiver, John Oliver transcends his schtick|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614075700/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|archive-date=June 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> have described Oliver's style of reporting as journalism or even investigative journalism. Oliver himself disagrees, stating that \"it's not journalism, it's comedy\u2014it's comedy first, and it's comedy second.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|title='Last Week Tonight' Does Real Journalism, No Matter What John Oliver Says|last=Suebsaeng|first=Asawin|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602195007/http://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|archive-date=June 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n{{:List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n\n==Reaction and influence==\nA [[Net Neutrality (Last Week Tonight)#\"Net Neutrality\"|June 2014 segment]] about [[net neutrality in the United States]] was thought to spur over 45,000 comments on the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s electronic filing page about a net neutrality proposal that, if implemented, would have priority \"lanes\" for certain internet traffic. The FCC also received an extra 300,000 comments in an email inbox designated specifically for the proposal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|title=John Oliver Helps Rally 45,000 Net Neutrality Comments To FCC|last=Hu|first=Elise|work=NPR|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624041323/http://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|archive-date=June 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was thought that Oliver's segment had a major role in the FCC's ultimate reversal of stance on that proposal,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|title=Net neutrality's stunning reversal of fortune: Is it John Oliver's doing?|last=Bruinius|first=Harry|date=February 26, 2015|work=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=September 15, 2017|issn=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922102025/https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> with the FCC instead implementing net-neutrality rules that prohibited priority \"lanes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|title=What the Net Neutrality Rules Say|last=Sommer|first=Jeff|date=March 12, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313080607/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|archive-date=March 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A sequel in 2017 inspired over 150,000 comments on a subsequent proposal to scrap the new net neutrality rules.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|title=John Oliver may have helped spur 150,000 comments to FCC on Net neutrality|last=Snider|first=Mike|date=May 10, 2017|work=USA TODAY|access-date=September 22, 2017|last2=Weise|first2=Elizabeth|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922101510/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA segment on the then [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Tony Abbott]] received widespread attention in Australia across the mainstream media and was trending on [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|last= Bond|first= Nick|date= June 3, 2014|title= Tony Abbott lambasted on US TV show Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|publisher= [[News Corp Australia]]|accessdate= June 5, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170922002508/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|archive-date= September 22, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140603190359/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archivedate= June 3, 2014 |author= Ma Evelyn Castino Quilas |date= June 3, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott Mocked in U.S. News Program, Aussies Cringe on Twitter |work= International Business Times |accessdate= June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |author= Nick Toscano |date= June 2, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott roasted by John Oliver on HBO show Last Week Tonight |work= [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate= June 5, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180227040314/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |archive-date= February 27, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a document obtained by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', the military government of [[Thailand]] listed Oliver as \"[[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|undermining the royal institution]]\" for calling Crown Prince [[Vajiralongkorn]] a \"buffoon\" and an \"idiot.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|title=Thailand's Military Government Thinks John Oliver Is a Threat to Its Monarchy|last=Marshall|first=Andrew|publisher=Vice|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163841/https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|last=Hodal|first=Kate|title=Thai junta unamused by comedian John Oliver's royal jibes|work=The Guardian|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163837/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show also made international headlines following Oliver's interview with [[Edward Snowden]], which included a graphic, in-depth conversation about the amount of power the [[United States government]] has at its disposal in terms of intelligence, both domestic and foreign. Oliver also confronted Snowden about the lack of knowledge of the American people about his work and why they may be hesitant to analyze it for themselves rather than accept preconceived notions of him being a [[whistleblower]]. Notably, he tried to help Snowden in creating public awareness for the fundamentality of the surveillance problem in putting forward the question \"Can they see my dick?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|title=John Oliver lands Edward Snowden interview from Russia|publisher=CNNMoney|date=April 6, 2015|first=Brian|last=Stelter|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618211744/http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|archive-date=June 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|title=John Oliver presses Edward Snowden on whether he read all leaked NSA material|last=Yuhas|first=Alan|work=The Guardian|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163305/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a segment about [[public defender]]s and how some offices are extremely underfunded, the New Orleans Public Defense office's crowdfunding efforts to improve their conditions were featured. In the days following the episode's broadcast, thousands of dollars were donated to the office by the show's fans, helping them raise their goal four days after the show aired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opdla.causevox.com/ |title=Orleans Public Defenders crowd-funding |publisher=causevox.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917061217/http://opdla.causevox.com/ |archive-date=September 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor a segment in the October 18, 2015, broadcast, Oliver put on a comically grand demonstration with Canadian actor [[Mike Myers]] to urge Canadian voters to vote against [[Stephen Harper]] in the next day's [[2015 Canadian federal election|Canadian federal election]]. As part of this gesture, Oliver displayed $5000 in cash in anticipation of being charged for the crime of being a foreigner attempting to induce Canadian citizens to change their vote as per section 331 of the [[Canada Elections Act]]. However, the agency responsible for overseeing federal elections in Canada, [[Elections Canada]], explained the next day that prosecution of Oliver will not be necessary since inducement in the act is defined as offering something material to voters. Per Elections Canada, Oliver has not tried to influence Canadian electorate, since the money shown was only for the anticipated fine, but merely expressed his opinion as a bystander, which is lawful.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Peter|title=Why John Oliver won't go to jail for flouting Canadian election law|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|accessdate=November 17, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=October 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118044508/http://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|archive-date=November 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the June 17, 2018 episode, Oliver spoke at length about [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], in part criticizing his [[Censorship in China|censorship]] of Chinese media, his dictatorship<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|title=Media Censorship in China|work=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330080256/https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and consolidation of power.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|title=Why now? The rationale behind Xi Jinping's power consolidation|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040136/http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Both \"John Oliver\" and \"Last Week Tonight\" were blocked from Chinese social media platform [[Sina Weibo]] immediately following the segment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|title=Chinese social media censors John Oliver|date=June 21, 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622134355/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[HBO]] website and content from the network were also blocked,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|title=China blocks HBO after John Oliver mockery of Xi Jinping|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185611/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> although Last Week Tonight had already been excluded from [[HBO (Asia)|HBO Asia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|title=China Blocks HBO Website After John Oliver's Jokes About Xi Jinping|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625130936/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe promotion for Season 3 highlighted four derogatory quotes either the show or Oliver himself received: \"Comedian fool\" (former [[FIFA]] vice-president [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], responding to a segment on the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]]), \"Makes people dumb\" (an article ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote about the show), \"Very boring\" ([[Donald Trump]]'s assessment of the show), and \"More unpleasant than a diuretic\" (what [[President of Ecuador]] [[Rafael Correa]] said \"gringo talk shows\" were like, after being featured in a segment).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|title=When Does 'Last Week Tonight' Season 3 Premiere? John Oliver's Hit Show Is About To Jazz Up Your Winter|last=Tognotti|first=Chris|date=January 20, 2016|website=Bustle|accessdate=April 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402032053/http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== The John Oliver Effect ===\n{{Main|John Oliver#Influence and the \"John Oliver effect\"|l1 = John Oliver (Influence)}}\nOn several occasions, show segments on major societal issues, such as the \"Chickens\" or \"Bail\" segments, were soon followed by real-world change and action on said issues by the public, policymakers and/or other institutions. Several media outlets, noticing this pattern, suggested that attention from the show had instigated these changes, going so far as to dub the phenomenon the \"John Oliver Effect\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3674807/john-oliver-net-neutrality-civil-forfeiture-miss-america/|title=How the 'John Oliver Effect' Is Having a Real-Life Impact|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/29/john-oliver-impact/|title=The John Oliver Effect|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> One of the most commonly cited examples of this is Oliver's first Net Neutrality segment which allegedly led to more than 45,000 comments being sent to the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]], crashing the website set up to receive comments in the process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/03/john-oliver-fcc-website-net-neutrality|title=John Oliver's cheeky net neutrality plea crashes FCC website|last=Holpuch|first=Amanda|date=2014-06-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOliver himself does not believe the effect to be real and has openly ridiculed the idea on the show, even calling the term \"completely meaningless\".{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Tobacco===\n{{Main|Tobacco (Last Week Tonight)}}\n\"Tobacco\" is a segment about the tobacco industry, which aired on February 15, 2015, as part of the second episode of the second season. During the eighteen-minute segment, Oliver discusses tobacco industry trends and practices. He also introduces Jeff the Diseased Lung, a mascot he created for the American global cigarette and tobacco company [[Philip Morris International]], the makers of [[Marlboro (cigarette)|Marlboro]] brand of cigarettes. The anthropomorphic diseased lung, who smokes and coughs, has been compared to Joe Camel and the [[Marlboro Man]]. Oliver and his team promoted the cartoon character by sending shirts with Jeff's image to [[Togo]] and displaying billboards in [[Uruguay]], and by encouraging use of the hashtag #JeffWeCan, which trended on Twitter following the broadcast.\n\nThe segment received widespread media coverage, with several outlets praising Oliver's ability to launch successful marketing campaigns and change perceptions about smoking through the creation of the mascot. The mascot later made an appearance at a protest organized by the \"Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids\" in New York City in May 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|last=Olson|first=Samantha|title=John Oliver's 'Jeff The Diseased Lung' Hits Times Square For Anti-Smoking Awareness Flash Mob|date=May 6, 2015|work=Medical Daily|access-date=September 3, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915181858/http://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|archive-date=September 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|title=Youth advocates head to New York City to #StopMarlboro - Kick Butts Day|last=Olmstead|first=Erica|website=Kick Butts Day|date=May 22, 2015|access-date=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163701/https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPhilip Morris International issued a response to the segment, stating that it included \"many mischaracterizations\" of the company.<ref name=Parker>{{cite news|last=Parker|first=Ryan|title=John Oliver targets cigarettes on 'Last Week Tonight'; Philip Morris reacts|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|accessdate=November 24, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122195954/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|archive-date=November 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies ===\nIn the Mandatory Minimums segment that aired on July 25, 2015, John Oliver talked about the controversial history of presidential pardoning, claiming that Abraham Lincoln once pardoned a man convicted of bestiality because he was intoxicated at the time; the man in question being John Wilkes Booth. He then confessed the statement was not true and for the first time mentioned a book compiling his favorite history lies.\n\nA couple of weeks later, he published a web-exclusive video  based on that reference, expanding the content for a book called \"Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies\", to be released in the following spring. At the end of the mini-segment, however, he confesses again that the entire book was also a lie.\n\nIn what seems a continuation of the lie saga, the book surprisingly appeared on Amazon UK in October 2018.\n\nThe book description reads as follow: <blockquote>There is absolutely nothing more fun than lying confidently about history. Lying is incredibly fun. In fact, the only thing that feels better than lying to someone is lying to someone, then regaining their trust, and then lying to them again. This book, for example, was promised to be released in April 2016. But that was a lie. The plan was always October 2018. Because, you know, now is a time in history when lying openly gets you elected to office. </blockquote><blockquote>In this book, you will find plenty of plausible but completely unverifiable nonsense. Almost like watching Fox News but with a better sense of humour. Hopefully, it will teach you much about nothing other than the true joy of lying to people. Honestly, there has never been a better moment in history to be a liar. We have reached a point where truths have become lies and lies are now the truth. So learn from the greatest and get inspired by the best lies in history. </blockquote><blockquote>*NB: Most profits from this book are going to finance railway infrastructure under the English Channel. Contains strong language.<ref>{{Cite book|title=STRANGER THAN TRUTH.|last=PAUL.|first=OSPREY, FEY. DORIAN|date=2018|publisher=BLURB|isbn=978-0464820208|location=[S.l.]|oclc=1057754076}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption===\n{{Main|Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption}}\nIn August 2015, after delivering his \"Televangelists\" segment, Oliver hired a professional tax lawyer to set up a church called [[Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption]] as a legal entity. He did this partly as a way to demonstrate how \"disturbingly easy\" it is, in terms of paperwork, to set up a [[Tax exemption|tax-exempt]] religious organization as viewed by the [[Internal Revenue Service]]. As Oliver explained, the requirements needed to be defined as a \"church\" are quite broad. Since regulatory guidelines require an established location for a church, Oliver chose his studio location in New York City as its official location,<ref name=\"Mediaite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |last=Wilstein |first=Matt |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver One-Ups Colbert Super PAC by Creating His Own Tax-Exempt Church |work=Mediaite |quote=\"... This is real,\" John Oliver repeatedly told his Last Week Tonight audience last night after announcing the creation of his new megachurch, Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825011710/http://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |archive-date=August 25, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> although he registered the [[nonprofit organization]] in the state of [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |last=Pellot |first=Brian |date=August 18, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title='Megareverend' John Oliver trolls televangelists with new tax-exempt church |agency=[[Religion News Service]] |quote=\"... Oliver registered his church as a nonprofit corporation in Texas, named his New York studio as its \"established place of worship,\"...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819025650/http://www.religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |archive-date=August 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver's \"megachurch\" had a [[Toll-free telephone number|toll-free phone number]] which allowed callers to donate to the church, and said that any money collected would be redistributed to the charitable relief organization [[Doctors Without Borders]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |first=Nate |last=Scott |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver takes on televangelism on 'Last Week Tonight' |work=[[USA Today]] |quote=... You can donate to the church, too. (Though eventually, all the donations will be moved to Doctors Without Borders.) ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822104843/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |archive-date=August 22, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Pedestrian>{{cite web |url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |last=Bracken |first=Claire |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver launches his very own anti-Evangelist church |work=Pedestrian News |quote=\"... John Oliver ran a segment on \"church's who exploit people's faith for monetary gain\" and explored the ease at which these can be created in America ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904194105/https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |archive-date=September 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver announced the formation of his church on the episode of the show that aired on August 16, 2015.<ref name=\"TimeMag\">{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |first=Melissa |last=Locker |title=John Oliver Becomes a Televangelist and Finally Starts His Own Church |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |work=Time |quote=... The satirical aim of Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption will be to collect copious, tax-exempt donations ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824174155/http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |archive-date=August 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMatt Wilstein, writing for ''[[Mediaite]]'', saw Oliver's stunt as being along the same lines as comedian [[Stephen Colbert]]'s setting up of a [[501(c)(4)]] organization\u2014[[Colbert Super PAC]]\u2014as a way to \"test the absurd limits of the Supreme Court's [[Citizens United v. FEC|Citizens United decision]]\"; Oliver's megachurch, in contrast, is a way to test whether the IRS might view his \"megachurch\" as a tax-exempt organization.<ref name=\"Mediaite\"/> Steve Thorngate, writing in ''[[The Christian Century]]'', suggested that the question of the religious exemption from taxation was more difficult and nuanced than Oliver portrayed, and not a simple matter of government regulation, describing Oliver's pivot to IRS policy as \"unhelpful.\" However, Thorngate agreed that Oliver's exposure and criticism of \"manipulative sleazeballs\" who \"fleece the faithful\" is \"spot-on.\"<ref name=\"ChristianCentury\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |first=Steve |last=Thorngate |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Why is John Oliver's televangelism segment about the IRS? |work=The Christian Century |quote=\"... Oliver's scornful outrage: televangelists who fleece the faithful ... The question of religious tax exemption generally is more complicated. ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820000830/http://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |archive-date=August 20, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Leonardo Blair, writing for ''[[Christian Post]]'', described Oliver's segment as a \"brutal takedown\" of televangelists and churches which preach \"the [[prosperity theology|prosperity gospel]],\" a message that dupes people into thinking that cash donations will solve medical or financial problems, while in fact the donations go to the personal aggrandizement of televangelists who buy expensive jets or large mansions.<ref name=\"ChristianPost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |first=Blair |last=Leonardo |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Comedian John Oliver Lampoons Televangelists on 'Last Week Tonight' Show; Opens Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption Church |work=[[The Christian Post]] |quote=... From Creflo Dollar to Kenneth Copeland, late night comedian John Oliver delivered a brutal takedown. ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823142157/http://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |archive-date=August 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA week later, on the following episode, Oliver devoted a short segment to the donations the church had received, which included money from around the world. Oliver said he had received \"thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars\" from donors. Displayed were several US Post Office containers full of mail. Oliver told viewers that the more money they sent in, the more \"blessings\" would be returned to them, adding that \"that is still something I'm \u2014 amazingly \u2014 legally allowed to say.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title = John Oliver Televangelist Church Received \"Thousands of Dollars,\" Seeds and Beef Jerky|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|website = The Hollywood Reporter|date = August 24, 2015|accessdate = August 25, 2015|quote = ... We have received thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars ...|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150826221454/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|archive-date = August 26, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOliver announced that the Church would be shutting down during his show on September 13, 2015. All monetary donations have been forwarded to Doctors Without Borders.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | title=Closed. Praise Be Unto You | date=September 13, 2015 | accessdate=September 13, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827212918/http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | archive-date=August 27, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\n{{Main|Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump}}\n[[Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|\"Donald Trump\"]] is a segment discussing American businessman Donald Trump. It aired on February 28, 2016, as part of the third episode of the third season. During the 22-minute segment, Oliver discusses [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]] and his long career in business. He also reveals that the Trump family name was changed at one point from the ancestral name 'Drumpf'. Although the changing of names was once a common [[Anglicisation of names|practice]] among many non-English immigrants to the United States, the segment popularized the term \"Donald Drumpf\" and started a campaign urging viewers to \"Make Donald Drumpf Again,\" a play on Trump's own campaign slogan, \"[[Make America Great Again]].\" It is the most popular segment the show has ever done. The segment garnered more than 85 million views on Facebook and YouTube combined which, an HBO spokesman has said, \"is a record for any piece of HBO content.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|title=Even John Oliver enjoys a Drumpf bump|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=March 30, 2016|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331201056/http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|archive-date=March 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]] and following [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inauguration]], Oliver made [[Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump|additional segments regarding Trump]].\n\n===Debt buyers===\n\"Debt Buyers\" is a segment discussing the business and questionable practice of [[debt buyers]]. It aired on June 5, 2016, as part of the fourteenth episode of the third season. Oliver announced he had purchased nearly $15 million in medical debt that belonged to 9,000 debtors. He did this through a company he had created, called \"Central Asset Recovery Professionals Inc.\" (CARP), which he described as being \"for [[Carp|the bottom-feeding fish]].\" Oliver stated that it was \"pretty clear by now [that] debt buying is a grimy business, and badly needs more oversight\" and went to point out that starting such a business was \"disturbingly easy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |first=Kelly |last=Lawler |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15 million of debt |website=USA Today |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606180535/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It cost him $50 to register the business in [[Mississippi]], while it cost less than $60,000 to purchase almost $15 million in [[bad debt]], medical debt from Texas. Oliver forgave the debt in its entirety, and claimed that it was the largest single giveaway in the American television history, eclipsing that of [[General Motors]] on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in 2004 where it gifted cars to Winfrey's studio audience, worth an estimated $8 million in total.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | first=J. Weston | last=Phippen | title=John Oliver's $15 Million Debt Giveaway | website=The Atlantic | date=June 6, 2016 | accessdate=June 6, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160607105724/http://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | archive-date=June 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''Slate'', Jordan Weissmann disputed the $15 million figure: \"[Oliver] says CARP paid around $60,000 ... for its paper, which was 'out-of-statute'\u2014meaning the debts were so old that creditors technically couldn't even sue over them anymore. That suggests the seller thought the debts were worth no more than, well, $60,000.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |title=Sorry, but John Oliver Did Not Really Just Give Away $15 Million |last=Weissmann |first=Jordan |date=June 6, 2016 |newspaper=Slate |issn=1091-2339 |access-date=June 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606221649/http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The episode was highlighted in the academic journal ''Religions''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krantz |first=David |title=Shmita Revolution: The Reclamation and Reinvention of the Sabbatical Year |work=Religions |date=August 8, 2016 |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920052704/http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |archive-date=September 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show partnered with RIP Medical Debt, Inc. to abolish the debt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kasperkevic |first1=Jana |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15m worth of medical debt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=June 6, 2016 |quote=Instead of collecting the debt, however, Last Week Tonight partnered with RIP Medical Debt charity and decided to forgive that debt. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140428/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|title=The Miracle of Debt Forgiveness on HBO's Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|last=Goff|first=Robert|website=RIP Medical Debt, Inc.|date=June 5, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115132834/https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|archive-date=November 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Coal mining and Bob Murray ===\nOn June 18, 2017, ''Last Week Tonight''{{'}}s main segment was about coal mining and [[Robert E. Murray|Bob Murray]]. In his segment, Oliver talked about how the safety condition inside the coal mines specifically the 2007 [[Crandall Canyon Mine]] collapse, which killed six miners, in which Oliver criticized Murray for claiming the collapse was caused by an [[earthquake]], despite all evidence demonstrating otherwise.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|title=John Oliver Is In Legal Trouble For His Rant About A Coal CEO|last=Suneson|first=Grant|work=Newsy|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623041444/http://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|archive-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The show ended with a costumed [[squirrel]] named \"Mr. Nutterbutter\" presenting Murray with a voided check for \"3 acorns and 18 cents\" in response to Murray's company presenting its employees with low sums of money as bonuses, and how the employees retaliate by voiding the checks, and in reference to a claim that stated that Murray supposedly got the idea to start his company from a talking squirrel.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Coal: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO) |series=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=June 18, 2017 |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |network=HBO |last=Oliver |first=John (host) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623002244/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |archivedate=June 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 22, Bob Murray presented a [[lawsuit]] against Oliver, HBO, and [[Time Warner]] for defamation. HBO believes ''Last Week Tonight'' has done nothing wrong, with a [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] lawyer describing the lawsuit as \"frivolous.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In February 2018, a West Virginia judge stated that he plans to dismiss the lawsuit filed by Murray as unfounded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oppenheim|first1=Maya|title=Coal tycoon's defamation lawsuit against John Oliver dismissed by judge|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=The Independent|date=February 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225060807/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|archive-date=February 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Murray's appeal to the West Virginia Supreme Court was delayed due to impeachment of the judges, Murray offered to drop the charges and HBO accepted.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|title=John Oliver takes on muzzling lawsuits \u2013 and the man who sued his show|last=Horton|first=Adrian|date=November 11, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On November 10, 2019, Oliver discussed the case in a segment about [[SLAPP|SLAPP suits]], revealing that the suit cost HBO $200,000 in legal costs and tripled the show's libel insurance fees. Oliver acknowledged that, despite the segment being vetted, the content would likely lead to another lawsuit, and that he would stand behind his team if it were to happen.<ref name=\":1\" /> The segment was ended with a five-minute, [[Times Square]]-set [[musical number]] featuring crude and ludicrous fictional anecdotes about Murray; the musical is titled \"Eat Shit, Bob.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===''A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo''===\n{{Main|A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo}}\nOn March 18, 2018, Oliver announced the publication of a children's book, ''[[A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo]]'', which parodies a book that [[Mike Pence]]'s family wrote about their family rabbit, [[Marlon Bundo's: A Day in the Life of the Vice President|Marlon Bundo]]. Oliver used his book as a platform to criticize Pence's positions on LGBT issues, as it featured a rabbit in a same-sex relationship.<ref name=\"Daily Beast Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=March 19, 2018 |title=John Oliver Trolls Vice President Mike Pence With Gay Children's Book of His Pet Bunny |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |work=Daily Beast |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319104738/https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The book became the number-one book and e-book on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] the next day, and the top-selling audiobook on [[Audible (store)|Audible]].<ref name=\"Politico Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Nelson |first=Louis |date=March 19, 2018 |title=Comey's memoir tops Amazon's best-sellers list |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |work=Politico |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319140528/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/03/john-oliver-marlon-bundo-book-mike-pence-troll|title=John Oliver's Gay-Bunny Book Is Outselling the Mike Pence Book It's Trolling|first=Hillary|last=Busis|website=Vanity Fair|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Russell Crowe's jockstrap===\n{{main|Russell Crowe's jockstrap}}\n[[Russell Crowe's jockstrap]] became a notable piece of memorabilia when it was purchased by the ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' and then donated to a Blockbuster Video shop. The jockstrap reappeared in a skit in the final episode of the 2018 season of the show.\n\n===Robocalls===\nThe March 10, 2019, episode dealt primarily with [[robocalls]], and how the problem had mushroomed in recent years since being increasingly deregulated under [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC Chairman]] [[Ajit Pai]]. To prove the point of how easy it was for any company to begin flooding anyone with robocalls, Oliver had one of his IT techs develop a system in which all of the FCC chairs would, at regular intervals on their personal phone numbers, receive a robocall followed immediately by [[bagpipe]] music. Oliver freely admitted his astonishment at just how easy this was to accomplish; the IT technician tasked with setting the system up told him they needed only 15 minutes to complete the project, doing so on a minimal budget. And per the very FCC regulations currently in place, Oliver quickly scrolled a section of fine print on screen at a random time during the segment, in which his office address was randomly embedded, and each FCC chair was required to send him an official letter to that address, notifying him in writing that they wished to have him cease all robocalls forthwith. Oliver was also flabbergasted at discovering that while tens of millions of dollars in fines were levied against companies for violating robocall regulations, only a few thousand dollars have ever been collected, effectively giving the companies free rein to continue robocalling unabated.\n\n===''Guinness World Records''===\nThe main story of the August 11, 2019 episode was [[Turkmenistan]] and its autocratic leader [[Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow]]. The last portion of the segment centered around Berdimuhamedow's obsession with ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', with the Turkmen capital of [[Ashgabat]] being home to the most buildings with white marble cladding, the largest indoor [[Ferris wheel]], and the largest statue of a horse's head, among others. Oliver found that ''Guinness World Records'' received sums of money ranging from US$12,000 to US$500,000 from companies and authoritarian nations to set records for publicity. He ended the show with a 600 square foot [[marble cake]] adorned with a picture of Berdimuhamedow falling from a horse; he had requested a Guinness adjudicator to certify it as the world's largest marble cake, a record previously set by [[Betty Crocker]] in Saudi Arabia in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|title=A gift 'fresh from the heart' in Saudi Arabia|website=General Mills|language=en|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=August 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815165112/https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness refused, stating that because their brand was \"aligned with kids and families\", they would not send an adjudicator; Oliver mockingly commented that he didn't \"run a brutal enough dictatorship to meet Guinness World Records' high ethical standards\". Oliver claimed that Guinness offered to certify it after the fact only if he signed an agreement not to criticize their practices on the show, which Oliver dismissed as \"ridiculous\".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E |title=Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=August 11, 2019 |author=HBO |access-date=August 15, 2019 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815170404/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|title=John Oliver Bakes Very Large Cake to Annoy Turkmenistan|website=Time|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814150445/https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|archive-date=August 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness called Oliver's allegations \"false and unfair\", claiming that they did not send an adjudicator because they felt the cake was specifically for the purpose of mocking a record holder, stating it was their policy \"not to partake in any activities which may belittle their achievements or subject them to ridicule\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|title=Guinness World Records on Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|date=August 12, 2019|website=Guinness World Records|language=en-GB|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813023105/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Narendra Modi===\n\nJohn Oliver extensively satirized Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in a broadcast which went online on February 23, 2020 calling him a temporary symbol of hate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qVIXUhZ2AWs |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Last Week Tonight |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was during a visit of US President [[Donald Trump]] to India, and in an [[Namaste Trump|organized rally]] which unexpectedly coincided with [[North East Delhi riots|large-scale violence in Delhi]], the country's capital. In this episode, Oliver likened Modi's [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP party's]] political beliefs to [[Adolf Hitler|Adolf Hitler's]], by noting that this party's founders, in 1925, had admired Hitler for his methods to ensure \u201cthe purity of the race\u201d \u2013 \u201cwhich is just not a chill thing to admire Hitler - and that, there is one and only one thing that it\u2019s OK to admire Hitler for, and it\u2019s the fact that he killed Hitler.\" <ref name=\"TempHate\">{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Adrian|title=John Oliver explains Trump's support of Modi, India's 'temporary symbol of hate'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=Guardian|date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229180408/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver also lampooned Trump's choice of words to describe Modi as \"the father of India\", suggesting that there is a [[Mahatma Gandhi|certain Gandhi]] that already holds that exact title.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/> The brunt of his attacks, however, were aimed at Modi's \"increasingly controversial reputation and [[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|widespread protests against his government's citizenship measures]].\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>In his attempt to explain the political climate in India under BJP which condones [[Violence against Muslims in India|widespread violence against Muslims]], Oliver mentions how Modi's party-appointed head of [[Uttar Pradesh]], the largest BJP-ruled state of India, said at a recent rally: \u201cIf they kill one Hindu then we will also kill 100 of them (Muslims).\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>He further adds that Modi's party has also edited religious pluralism out of history textbooks, and introduced primary school textbooks teaching Indian supremacy, and that the image is \"nauseating\" and that for perhaps the first time in Modi's whole career, his actions are creating a massive and sustained backlash.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>Oliver concludes this segment by saying that when Trump says Modi is bringing India together, \u201cwith any luck, the thing that unites them may actually end up being their complete disgust over what he is trying to do\u201d, since India, home of the \u201csymbol of love\u201d [[Taj Mahal]], \u201cfrankly deserves much more than this temporary symbol of hate\u201d.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>\n\n[[Disney+ Hotstar|Hotstar]], an Indian streaming service who holds rights to HBO programming in the country, refused to stream the episode, leading to criticism by local viewers (including Hotstar's apps being [[Review bombing|review bombed]] with 1-star reviews).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-1-star-reviews-modi-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-censorship-backlash-2185798|title=Hotstar Gets 1-Star Reviews for Pro-Government Censorship of John Oliver|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Oliver addressed the censorship in the March 8, 2020 episode, also noting that since the acquisition of Hotstar by [[The Walt Disney Company]] (which occurred as part of its [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-southeast-asia-expansion-disney-bob-iger-star-india-2081496|title=Disney Plans Southeast Asia Expansion for Hotstar|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Hotstar had begun to censor jokes regarding Disney characters from the program, such as his \"factually-accurate\" claim that [[Donald Duck]] had a [[corkscrew penis]].<ref name=\"thr-lwthotstar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-slams-disney-owned-hotstar-removing-jokes-disney-1283146|title=John Oliver Slams Disney-Owned Streamer for Censoring 'Last Week Tonight' Jokes About Disney|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\n''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' episode clips can be seen internationally on [[YouTube]]. It is broadcast on [[Pay television|premium]] channel [[HBO Canada]] that is [[simulcast]] with HBO in the U.S.; around the same time it is shown on the international [[HBO (international)|HBO]] channels. It airs in Australia on [[The Comedy Channel]] hours after the U.S. airing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|title=Airdate: Last Week Tonight|last=Knox|first=David|date=April 11, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2014|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200503/http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|archive-date=June 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and airs in New Zealand on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver coming to SoHo|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=Dan News|accessdate=August 13, 2015|archivedate=August 13, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813114138/http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/}}</ref> In the United Kingdom and Ireland, it is broadcast on Mondays on [[Sky Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sky.com/watch/title/series/b7a772c4-8fdb-4e28-be16-66141b9b34d6/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Sky |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In Belgium, it is broadcast on Thursdays by the [[Telenet (Belgium)|Telenet]] cable-only channel [[Prime (Flanders)|PRIME Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver S2|publisher=Telenet/PRIME|accessdate=February 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150221095413/http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|archivedate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> It airs in South Africa on [[M-Net]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|publisher=channel24.co.za|title=M-Net adds exciting new late night talk show to its schedule|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2015|last=Ferreira|first=Thinus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930202818/http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and in Portugal on [[RTP3]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferreira|first1=David|trans-title=|title=Conhe\u00e7a a programa\u00e7\u00e3o da nova RTP3 (com v\u00eddeo)|url=http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|language=Portuguese|accessdate=September 29, 2015|publisher=A Televis\u00e3o|date=September 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930130307/http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In India, the show is streamed on Hotstar Premium.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Series Full Episodes, Watch Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Show Online | access-date=November 18, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164539/https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | archive-date=November 18, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Comedy|Television}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=3530232|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{tv.com show|last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Facebook|LastWeekTonight}}\n* {{YouTube|u=LastWeekTonight|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Last Week Tonight}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Awards for ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'']]\n|list=\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Talk Show}}\n{{Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Talk Series}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in News and Information}}\n{{Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy-Variety Talk Series}}\n}}\n{{Late night television in the United States}}\n{{HBONetwork Shows}}\n\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver| ]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American late-night television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American late-night television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:American news parodies]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:HBO original programming]]\n[[Category:Political satirical television series]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Censored television series]]\n[[Category:Works banned in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American late-night talk show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Last Week Tonight {{nowrap|with John Oliver}}\n| show_name_2        = Last Week Tonight\n| image              = Last Week Tonight.svg\n| image_alt          = Black and red text on a white background reading \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\".\n| caption            =\n| genre              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Comedy]]\n* [[News satire]]\n* [[Political satire]]\n* [[Talk show]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[John Oliver]]\n| writer             = <!-- Per infobox template rules, writer(s) should not be included if series has 5+ writers -->\n| director           = {{plainlist|\n* Joe Perota\n* Christopher Werner\n* Jim Hoskinson\n* Paul Pennolino\n* Bruce Leddy\n}}\n| presenter          = John Oliver\n| starring           =\n| narrated           = [[David Kaye (voice actor)|David Kaye]]\n| opentheme          = \"Go\" by [[Valley Lodge (band)|Valley Lodge]]<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=476822910494310400|date=June 11, 2014|title=By the way, our theme song \"Go\" is performed by the excellent rock band @ValleyLodge!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Hill|title=Valley Lodge's \"Go\" Is the Theme Song for \"Last Week Tonight with John Oliver\" on HBO|url=http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|publisher=DaveHillOnline.com|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=April 2, 2016|author-link=Dave Hill (comedian)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401105027/http://davehillonline.com/blog/2014/04/valley-lodges-go-is-the-theme-song-for-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-on-hbo/|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 7\n| num_episodes       = 187\n| list_episodes      = List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes\n| executive_producer = {{plainlist|\n* John Oliver\n* [[Tim Carvell]]\n* Liz Stanton\n* James Taylor\n* [[Jon Thoday]]\n}}\n| location           = [[CBS Broadcast Center]]<br />New York, New York\n| runtime            = 30\u201340 minutes<ref>{{cite tweet|user=LastWeekTonight|number=927269314025140225|date=November 5, 2017|title=You got an extra hour of sleep this morning, so you should be well-rested for tonight's 40-minute episode that starts at 11:15.}}</ref>\n| company            = {{plainlist|\n* Avalon Television\n* Partially Important Productions\n}}\n| distributor        = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network            = [[HBO]]\n| picture_format     = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format       = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2014|4|27}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| website            = http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver\n}}\n'''''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver''''' (often abridged as '''''Last Week Tonight''''') is an American [[late-night talk show|late-night talk]] and [[news satire]] television program hosted by comedian [[John Oliver]].<ref name=\"order\">{{cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |date=February 12, 2014 |title=HBO Sets Name & Date For John Oliver Debut |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |url-status=live |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214111313/http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |archivedate=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> The half-hour-long show premiered on Sunday, April 27, 2014, on [[HBO]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|title=John Oliver's HBO Series Gets Name, April Premiere|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|accessdate=March 10, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324102357/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|archive-date=March 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Last Week Tonight'' shares some similarities with [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[The Daily Show]]'' (where Oliver was previously [[List of The Daily Show correspondents|featured as a correspondent]] and fill-in host), as it takes a satirical look at news, politics and current events, but on a weekly basis.<ref name=\"order\"/>\n\nOliver has stated that he has \"full [[artistic freedom|creative freedom]], including free rein to [[Criticisms of corporations|criticize corporations]]\". His initial contract with HBO was for two years with an option for extension.<ref name=\"freedom\">{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|title=John Oliver on the Luxurious 'Freedom' of HBO, His Complicated Relationship With NYC|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 19, 2014|date=April 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418232827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|archive-date=April 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, HBO announced that the show had been renewed for three additional seasons of 30 episodes each, keeping the show on the air through 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |title=John Oliver Extends HBO Contract Through 2020 |last=Koblin |first=John |work=The New York Times |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=September 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912182739/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |archive-date=September 12, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show's seventh season, the last season promised by the 2017 renewal announcement, premiered on February 16, 2020.<ref name=\"S6\">{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Gets Season 6 Premiere Date On HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |accessdate=January 2, 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 2, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102235844/https://deadline.com/2019/01/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-season-6-premiere-date-hbo-1202528068/ |archive-date=January 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nOliver described his preparations for the show to an interviewer for ''[[The Atlantic#The Wire|The Wire]]'': \"... I basically have to watch everything. The only thing I kind of watch for pleasure is [[Fareed Zakaria GPS|Fareed Zakaria's show]] on Sundays ... That and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' I watch for pleasure, or maybe ''[[Frontline (American TV program)|Frontline]]'' ... I have a TV on in my office all the time and I'll generally flick around on that from [[CNN]], [[Fox News|Fox]], [[MSNBC]], [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], [[Al Jazeera America|Al Jazeera]] ... I'm watching with a certain thing in mind and that is how to see a story told badly.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |author= Zuckerman, Esther |date= May 1, 2014 |title= John Oliver: What I Read |work= The Wire |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504083727/http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nHe said to another interviewer that he is concerned about dealing with [[news values|old news]]:\n\n<blockquote>If something happens on a Monday, realistically all the meat is going to be picked off that bone by the time it gets to us&nbsp;\u2014 there's probably barely a point in doing it ... I think we'll be attracted to some extent by stories that are off the grid ... Our show may end up skewing more international in terms of stories.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better |title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Changing journalism for the better |last=Hoxie |first=Angie |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218055110/http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better/ |archive-date=February 18, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[Tim Carvell]], executive producer of ''Last Week Tonight'', explained in an interview how the cast and crew deal with a half hour of Oliver speaking without any [[Television advertisement|commercial]] breaks.<ref name=\"usnews\">{{cite web |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |author= Sneed, Tierney |date= April 22, 2014 |title= Why ''Last Week Tonight'' Will Not Just Be ''The Daily Show'' on Sundays |work= [[U.S. News & World Report]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504081746/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Structural considerations are leading to changes in the content in the show that will inherently make it different from ''The Daily Show'' ... We realized early on, you don't necessarily want to hear anybody talk to you for a half an hour straight&nbsp;\u2013 even John, who is very charming&nbsp;\u2013 so we are constructing these little, produced comedy elements that will serve the function of commercial breaks throughout the show, which will let us get out of the studio, get us away from John's voice and break the show up a bit.}}\n\nCarvell also revealed that HBO gave them freedom in choosing guests for the show, advising them not to feel obligated to feature celebrities.<ref name=\"usnews\" /> When asked by an interviewer about \"[[correspondent]]s\" such as those featured on ''The Daily Show'', Oliver replied, \"we're not going to be a parody news show, so no people pretending to be journalists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|last=Furlong|first=Maggie|title='Last Week Tonight,' Two Days Later: John Oliver on His First Show, Dream Guests, and Old White Racists|website=Yahoo!|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619185957/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the fifth episode of season 7, Oliver stated that the studio and the show's offices were shut down after employees tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and that the show would go on temporary hiatus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/films-tv-delayed-coronavirus-canceled-1203532033/|title=All the Shows and Movies Shut Down or Delayed Because of Coronavirus|publisher=Variety|date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The show returned on March&nbsp;29, filmed from Oliver's home, to cover the coronavirus and the response to it.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/john-oliver-coronavirus-last-week-tonight-march-29.html</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2015}}\nThe format is similar to ''[[The Daily Show]]'', with Oliver sitting at a desk in front of a backdrop of a skyline containing buildings from around the world, often relating to the current topic. Unlike ''The Daily Show'', Oliver tends to explore one concept in depth but retains the appearance of commercial breaks to intercut larger topics with smaller segments that are not necessarily related to the topic at hand. The show is taped in front of a [[studio audience]], and HBO offers a limited number of free tickets to attend each week's ''Last Week Tonight'' taping.\n\nThe show's theme starts off every episode containing images relating to it or the world at large with satirical captions written in [[dog Latin]]. Each episode covers a small handful of shorter segments, and then one main segment. While the short segments almost always relate to recent news, the episode's main segment usually covers in length and detail a political issue, even if that issue did not have news media attention during the preceding week. On occasion, the short segments are omitted and the main segment takes up the entirety of the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|last=Framke|first=Caroline|title=John Oliver on making Last Week Tonight and why he won't focus on the 2016 election|website=Vox|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=March 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320052802/http://www.vox.com/2016/2/14/10989154/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-3|archive-date=March 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver injects humor into his presentation, including satirical [[analogies]], and allusions to popular culture and celebrities. The show includes a panel in the upper-left corner that frequently displays a photo or graphic for that accompanies subject at hand, which aids in the humor. A full-screen graphic will show and play a video clip (such as excerpts from news show or documentaries) when Oliver is citing it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|title=Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' is The Next Generation of Late Night|last=Miller|first=Liz Shannon|website=IndieWire|language=en|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904015651/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/07/why-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-is-the-next-generation-of-late-night-23696/|archive-date=September 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He often coins [[hashtag|hashtags]] related to his segment for use in [[social media]], some of which go [[Viral phenomenon|viral]].<ref name=Emertainment>{{cite web|url=http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|last=Solomon|first=Emily|title=How John Oliver Gets Social Media Right While the Rest of Traditional Media Fails|work=Emertainment Monthly|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404222905/http://emertainmentmonthly.com/index.php/how-john-oliver-gets-social-media-right-while-the-rest-of-traditional-media-fails/|archive-date=April 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA recurring element of the show is Oliver's use of mascots. The mascots used in the show include Jeff the Diseased Lung in a Cowboy Hat, Hoots the NSA Owl, Taryn the Tinder Chicken, and the Last Week Tonight puppets.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ranker.com/list/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-mascots/ranker-tv | title=All the Mascot Costumes from Last Week Tonight, Ranked}}</ref> Oliver told Vulture in February 2019, \"I mean, the truth of the mascots is that we have a gigantic room filled with spectacular mascot costumes now. [Executive producer] Tim Carvell and I \u2014 I think we\u2019ve always seen the show as our attempt to make The Muppet Show and failing to do so. But occasionally, just occasionally, you get the kind of Muppet Show adoration in the ludicrous mascots.\"<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-hbo-interview-mascots.html</ref>\n\nThe typical structure of the show is to open with a recap of a few of the week's news stories, segue into a video compilation, and then move on to Oliver's main segment. Some of the episodes will follow up the main segment with another video compilation or news story. Oliver's speech is broken up with video compilations of recent news clips, or recurring segments, into which Oliver segues with the slogan, \"And now, this.\" Oliver has also ended some segments with mock trailers for fictional TV shows or commercials that satirize the subject of his speech.\n\n=== Celebrity guests===\nThe show frequently features one or more celebrity guests in its segments to help Oliver better get his point on the week's topic across. Guests have featured in many different capacities including giving monologues directly to camera, being interviewed by Oliver, playing musical numbers, participating in comedic skits with or without Oliver, or starring in fictitious parody [[Public service announcement|PSAs]]. On the show, guests are sometimes seen in the Last Week Tonight studio itself doing their part during the show's main taping, while at other times they are seen in video clips that were pre-recorded at a different location and later included in the show. Oliver often interviews personalities who were directly involved in or impacted by the issues being discussed in the show to get their first-hand experiences and viewpoints on the issue. Some of the famous personalities Oliver has interviewed include [[Edward Snowden]], the [[14th Dalai Lama|14th]] [[Dalai Lama]], [[Anita Hill|Professor Anita Hill]] and [[Monica Lewinsky]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n{{:List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes}}\n\n==YouTube channel==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a [[YouTube]] channel where videos are intermittently (depending on series) added after a show has aired.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |title=Last Week Tonight channel |access-date=March 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313183030/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Most of the videos are of the main segment from each episode. Some extended clips are also available on the show's YouTube channel, as are \"Web Exclusives\" that are produced solely for the channel, such as a July 2016 video in which Oliver responded to negative comments left on the channel itself.<ref name=Emertainment/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Framke |first1=Caroline |title=John Oliver ends 2016 by confronting Last Week Tonight's role in the liberal echo chamber |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |website=Vox |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=November 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163235/https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/11/20/13678748/john-oliver-election-2016 |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rhodan |first1=Maya |title=Watch John Oliver Read Mean 'Fan Mail' from YouTube |url=http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |website=Time |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501084644/http://time.com/4401025/watch-john-oliver-read-mean-fan-mail-from-youtube/ |archive-date=May 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe show's production has also created content specifically for fan use. For the March 19, 2017, episode, which reported on Bolivia's growing coalition of workers clad in zebra suits to educate civilians about traffic laws, the show's production recorded 23 minutes of a person in a zebra costume dancing and gesticulating before a green screen so that viewers could edit it into other videos for humorous effect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=John Oliver Slams Trump's Budget, Lightens Mood with Dancing Zebras |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608152244/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/john-oliver-donald-trump-budget-proposal-dancing-zebras |archive-date=June 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A similar video called \"Real Animals, Fake Paws\" for use in reenacting [[U.S. Supreme Court]] cases was released after the October 19, 2014, episode where dogs were used instead of justices to make listening to oral court cases more amusing to the general public and to increase interest in the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|title=Real Animals, Fake Paws Footage: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|last=LastWeekTonight|date=October 19, 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube|access-date=June 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620155905/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tug71xZL7yc|archive-date=June 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2015, the channel had attained over a million subscribers.<ref name=Emertainment/> That number had risen to 3.6 million by July 2016,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Durkin |first1=J.D. |title=Oliver Responds to Harsh YouTube Comments in Newest Last Week Tonight Segment |url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |website=Mediaite |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |date=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163915/https://www.mediaite.com/online/oliver-responds-to-harsh-youtube-comments-in-newest-last-week-tonight-segment/ |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and over 5 million by May 2017. {{As of|2020|April|df=}}, the channel had over 7.8 million subscribers and more than 2.4 billion views.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about \"Last Week Tonight\" videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304225649/https://www.youtube.com/user/LastWeekTonight/about |date=March 4, 2017 }}. YouTube. Retrieved April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Social media ==\n''Last Week Tonight'' has a Facebook page with over 2.6 million likes, a Twitter account with over 2.9 million followers, and an Instagram account with more than 450,000 followers {{As of|2019|July|lc=y|df=}}.\n\nOliver often makes use of joke [[hashtags]] to facilitate the [[viral spread]] of his videos on [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]], as with the hashtag #NotMyChristian, which he used in 2014 to complain about the casting of actor [[Jamie Dornan]] in the feature film adaptation of ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''. The hashtag became a recurring punchline on the show, mentioned in both serious stories and casual segues.<ref name=\"Emertainment\" />\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:John Oliver 2014.jpg|thumb|250x250px|John Oliver, host of ''Last Week Tonight'']]\nOliver's debut show garnered 1.11 million viewers. The number of viewers online, through websites such as YouTube showing extended clips of different segments, have steadily climbed into multiple millions. The show's YouTube channel also features Web Exclusives which are occasionally posted when the main show is taking a week off. Across the TV airings, [[Digital video recorder|DVR]], [[Video on demand|on-demand]] and [[HBO Go]], ''Last Week Tonight'' averaged 4.1 million weekly viewers in its first season.<ref>{{cite news |last= O'Connell |first= Michael |title= John Oliver's Talk Show Ratings Edging Out HBO Colleague Bill Maher |work= The Hollywood Reporter |date= September 9, 2014 |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |accessdate= December 23, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013001/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-olivers-talk-show-ratings-735187 |archive-date= December 17, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n''Last Week Tonight'' has received widespread critical acclaim. Matthew Jacobs of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' named Oliver's program as 2014's best television show, writing \"the year's most surprising contribution to television is a show that bucked conventional formats, left us buzzing and paved the way for a burgeoning dynasty. ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' is 2014's crowning achievement.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Jacobs |first= Matthew |title= Why 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Was 2014's Best Show |work= The Huffington Post |date= December 8, 2014 |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |accessdate= December 9, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141209032042/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/08/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-best-show-2014_n_6284074.html |archive-date= December 9, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' compared Oliver's program with ''The Daily Show'' several times in his review of Oliver's debut:\n\n<blockquote>Another scathing, stick-it-to-'em critique of American [[mass media]] and politics shellacked in satire and delivered by a funny if almost off-puttingly incredulous man with a British accent ... Exactly like ''The Daily Show'', the goal is to make elected and appointed officials, as well as just about any corporate enterprise, look foolish and inept while slyly culling together television news clips that make the media look equally inept at covering such evident truths.<ref>{{cite news |last= Stuever |first= Hank |title= John Oliver's 'Last Week Tonight' on HBO sticks to a familiar formula |work= The Washington Post |date= April 28, 2014 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150508221812/http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style/wp/2014/04/28/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-on-hbo-sticks-to-a-familiar-formula/ |archive-date= May 8, 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[James Poniewozik]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly compared ''Last Week'' with ''The Daily Show'', but also wrote that the \"full half-hour gives Oliver the room to do more,\" and praised Oliver's \"sharper tone and his globalist, English-outsider perspective,\" as well as his \"genuine passion over his subjects.\" Poniewozik wrote that Oliver's debut was \"a funny, confident start.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |author= Poniewozik, James |date= April 28, 2014 |title= REVIEW: Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |work= Time |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503214147/http://time.com/79133/john-oliver-review-last-week/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' review began by ringing the same changes: \"The fear with ''Last Week Tonight'' is that it's ''The Daily Show'' except once a week&nbsp;\u2014 a staggered timeline that would rob the basic news-punning format of its intrinsic topical punch ... The first episode of his HBO series didn't stray far from the [[Jon Stewart|[Jon] Stewart]] mothership, stylistically ...\" However, the reviewer, Darren Franich, liked that Oliver has \"a half-hour of television that is simultaneously tighter and more ambitious, that the extra production time leads to sharper gags but also the ability to present more context\" and thought that the debut had \"plenty of funny throwaway lines.\" Franich appreciated Oliver's coverage of [[2014 Indian general election|the 2014 Indian election]], which the American press was largely ignoring,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |last= Ayres |first= Alyssa |date= May 1, 2014 |title= Thanks, John Oliver! Why India Isn't a Big Focus for U.S. Television |work= [[Forbes]] |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504055011/http://www.forbes.com/sites/alyssaayres/2014/05/01/thanks-john-oliver-why-india-isnt-a-big-focus-for-u-s-television/ |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> and, like Poniewozik, praised Oliver's \"passion.\" Franich concluded that ''Last Week Tonight'' \"suggested the sharpest possible version of its inspiration\" and that it \"should feel like an experiment\" but \"felt almost fully formed.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |last= Franich |first= Darren |date= April 28, 2014 |title= 'Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' review: The Weekly Show |work= Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503045808/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/04/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-review/ |archive-date= May 3, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nDavid Haglund of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' was ambivalent, writing that the show is \"obviously a work in progress\" and that one segment \"felt like misplaced overkill,\" but also that it is \"good use of a weekly show, and it was funny to boot.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |last= Haglund |first= David |date= April 2014 |title= Last Week Tonight: Like The Daily Show, With Unbleeped Swears! |work= Slate |accessdate= May 4, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140504203605/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2014/04/the_premiere_of_john_oliver_s_hbo_show_last_week_tonight_reviewed.html |archive-date= May 4, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref> [[Gawker]]'s Jordan Sargent claimed ''Last Week Tonight'' was \"the new ''Daily Show'',\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |author=Sargent, Jordan |date=May 6, 2014 |title=John Oliver's Last Week Tonight is the New Daily Show |publisher=Gawker |accessdate=May 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507030451/http://defamer.gawker.com/john-olivers-last-week-tonight-is-the-new-daily-show-1572116205/all |archivedate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref> while simultaneously criticizing the ''Daily Show'' for abandoning those \"who have moved on from caring about [[Fox News|Fox [News]]] and [[Republican Party of the United States|Republicans]].\"\n\nA number of commentators from mainstream media outlets, including ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|title=John Oliver's Complicated Fun Connects for HBO|date=November 16, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Carr|first=David|newspaper=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501135440/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html|archive-date=May 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Huffington Post'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814125641/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/26/john-oliver-journalism_n_5888184.html |archivedate=August 14, 2015|title=John Oliver Is Doing Some Really Good Investigative Journalism|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|title=Unfortunately, John Oliver, You Are a Journalist|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=November 17, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|work=Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725193947/http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|archive-date=July 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|title=With journalism in quiver, John Oliver transcends his schtick|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|last=Bauder|first=David|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614075700/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/with-journalism-in-quiver-john-oliver-transcends-his-schtick-1.1760408|archive-date=June 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> have described Oliver's style of reporting as journalism or even investigative journalism. Oliver himself disagrees, stating that \"it's not journalism, it's comedy\u2014it's comedy first, and it's comedy second.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|title='Last Week Tonight' Does Real Journalism, No Matter What John Oliver Says|last=Suebsaeng|first=Asawin|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602195007/http://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|archive-date=June 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n{{:List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n\n==Reaction and influence==\nA [[Net Neutrality (Last Week Tonight)#\"Net Neutrality\"|June 2014 segment]] about [[net neutrality in the United States]] was thought to spur over 45,000 comments on the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s electronic filing page about a net neutrality proposal that, if implemented, would have priority \"lanes\" for certain internet traffic. The FCC also received an extra 300,000 comments in an email inbox designated specifically for the proposal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|title=John Oliver Helps Rally 45,000 Net Neutrality Comments To FCC|last=Hu|first=Elise|work=NPR|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=September 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624041323/http://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2014/06/03/318458496/john-oliver-helps-rally-45-000-net-neutrality-comments-to-fcc|archive-date=June 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was thought that Oliver's segment had a major role in the FCC's ultimate reversal of stance on that proposal,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|title=Net neutrality's stunning reversal of fortune: Is it John Oliver's doing?|last=Bruinius|first=Harry|date=February 26, 2015|work=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=September 15, 2017|issn=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922102025/https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2015/0226/Net-neutrality-s-stunning-reversal-of-fortune-Is-it-John-Oliver-s-doing|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> with the FCC instead implementing net-neutrality rules that prohibited priority \"lanes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|title=What the Net Neutrality Rules Say|last=Sommer|first=Jeff|date=March 12, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313080607/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/03/12/technology/net-neutrality-rules-explained.html|archive-date=March 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A sequel in 2017 inspired over 150,000 comments on a subsequent proposal to scrap the new net neutrality rules.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|title=John Oliver may have helped spur 150,000 comments to FCC on Net neutrality|last=Snider|first=Mike|date=May 10, 2017|work=USA TODAY|access-date=September 22, 2017|last2=Weise|first2=Elizabeth|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922101510/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/05/09/john-oliver-may-have-helped-spur-150000-comments-fcc-net-neutrality/101480100/|archive-date=September 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA segment on the then [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Tony Abbott]] received widespread attention in Australia across the mainstream media and was trending on [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|last= Bond|first= Nick|date= June 3, 2014|title= Tony Abbott lambasted on US TV show Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|publisher= [[News Corp Australia]]|accessdate= June 5, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170922002508/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-lambasted-on-us-tv-show-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/news-story/cb0df94da804403072b59016dadf12b8|archive-date= September 22, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140603190359/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/554572/20140603/tony-abbot-last-week-tonight-john-oliver.htm#.U4-z_CgkRTY |archivedate= June 3, 2014 |author= Ma Evelyn Castino Quilas |date= June 3, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott Mocked in U.S. News Program, Aussies Cringe on Twitter |work= International Business Times |accessdate= June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |author= Nick Toscano |date= June 2, 2014 |title= Tony Abbott roasted by John Oliver on HBO show Last Week Tonight |work= [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate= June 5, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180227040314/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-roasted-by-john-oliver-on-hbo-show-last-week-tonight-20140602-zrvl1.html |archive-date= February 27, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a document obtained by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', the military government of [[Thailand]] listed Oliver as \"[[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|undermining the royal institution]]\" for calling Crown Prince [[Vajiralongkorn]] a \"buffoon\" and an \"idiot.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|title=Thailand's Military Government Thinks John Oliver Is a Threat to Its Monarchy|last=Marshall|first=Andrew|publisher=Vice|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163841/https://news.vice.com/article/thailands-military-government-thinks-john-oliver-is-a-threat-to-its-monarchy|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|last=Hodal|first=Kate|title=Thai junta unamused by comedian John Oliver's royal jibes|work=The Guardian|date=July 29, 2014|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163837/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/29/thai-junta-comedian-john-oliver-royal-jibes|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show also made international headlines following Oliver's interview with [[Edward Snowden]], which included a graphic, in-depth conversation about the amount of power the [[United States government]] has at its disposal in terms of intelligence, both domestic and foreign. Oliver also confronted Snowden about the lack of knowledge of the American people about his work and why they may be hesitant to analyze it for themselves rather than accept preconceived notions of him being a [[whistleblower]]. Notably, he tried to help Snowden in creating public awareness for the fundamentality of the surveillance problem in putting forward the question \"Can they see my dick?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|title=John Oliver lands Edward Snowden interview from Russia|publisher=CNNMoney|date=April 6, 2015|first=Brian|last=Stelter|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618211744/http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/06/media/edward-snowden-john-oliver-interview/index.html|archive-date=June 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|title=John Oliver presses Edward Snowden on whether he read all leaked NSA material|last=Yuhas|first=Alan|work=The Guardian|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163305/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-nsa-leaked-documents|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a segment about [[public defender]]s and how some offices are extremely underfunded, the New Orleans Public Defense office's crowdfunding efforts to improve their conditions were featured. In the days following the episode's broadcast, thousands of dollars were donated to the office by the show's fans, helping them raise their goal four days after the show aired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opdla.causevox.com/ |title=Orleans Public Defenders crowd-funding |publisher=causevox.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917061217/http://opdla.causevox.com/ |archive-date=September 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor a segment in the October 18, 2015, broadcast, Oliver put on a comically grand demonstration with Canadian actor [[Mike Myers]] to urge Canadian voters to vote against [[Stephen Harper]] in the next day's [[2015 Canadian federal election|Canadian federal election]]. As part of this gesture, Oliver displayed $5000 in cash in anticipation of being charged for the crime of being a foreigner attempting to induce Canadian citizens to change their vote as per section 331 of the [[Canada Elections Act]]. However, the agency responsible for overseeing federal elections in Canada, [[Elections Canada]], explained the next day that prosecution of Oliver will not be necessary since inducement in the act is defined as offering something material to voters. Per Elections Canada, Oliver has not tried to influence Canadian electorate, since the money shown was only for the anticipated fine, but merely expressed his opinion as a bystander, which is lawful.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Peter|title=Why John Oliver won't go to jail for flouting Canadian election law|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|accessdate=November 17, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=October 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118044508/http://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/2015/10/19/john-oliver-flouts-canadian-election-law-to-blast-harper.html|archive-date=November 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the June 17, 2018 episode, Oliver spoke at length about [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], in part criticizing his [[Censorship in China|censorship]] of Chinese media, his dictatorship<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|title=Media Censorship in China|work=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330080256/https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/media-censorship-china|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and consolidation of power.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|title=Why now? The rationale behind Xi Jinping's power consolidation|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040136/http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/2135962/why-now-rationale-behind-xi-jinpings-power-consolidation|archive-date=June 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Both \"John Oliver\" and \"Last Week Tonight\" were blocked from Chinese social media platform [[Sina Weibo]] immediately following the segment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|title=Chinese social media censors John Oliver|date=June 21, 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622134355/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-44557528|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[HBO]] website and content from the network were also blocked,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|title=China blocks HBO after John Oliver mockery of Xi Jinping|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185611/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2152323/china-blocks-hbo-after-john-oliver-parody-xi-jinping|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> although Last Week Tonight had already been excluded from [[HBO (Asia)|HBO Asia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|title=China Blocks HBO Website After John Oliver's Jokes About Xi Jinping|access-date=June 25, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625130936/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-hbo-john-oliver-xi-jinping.html|archive-date=June 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe promotion for Season 3 highlighted four derogatory quotes either the show or Oliver himself received: \"Comedian fool\" (former [[FIFA]] vice-president [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], responding to a segment on the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]]), \"Makes people dumb\" (an article ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote about the show), \"Very boring\" ([[Donald Trump]]'s assessment of the show), and \"More unpleasant than a diuretic\" (what [[President of Ecuador]] [[Rafael Correa]] said \"gringo talk shows\" were like, after being featured in a segment).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|title=When Does 'Last Week Tonight' Season 3 Premiere? John Oliver's Hit Show Is About To Jazz Up Your Winter|last=Tognotti|first=Chris|date=January 20, 2016|website=Bustle|accessdate=April 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402032053/http://www.bustle.com/articles/136882-when-does-last-week-tonight-season-3-premiere-john-olivers-hit-show-is-about-to-jazz|archive-date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== The John Oliver Effect ===\n{{Main|John Oliver#Influence and the \"John Oliver effect\"|l1 = John Oliver (Influence)}}\nOn several occasions, show segments on major societal issues, such as the \"Chickens\" or \"Bail\" segments, were soon followed by real-world change and action on said issues by the public, policymakers and/or other institutions. Several media outlets, noticing this pattern, suggested that attention from the show had instigated these changes, going so far as to dub the phenomenon the \"John Oliver Effect\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3674807/john-oliver-net-neutrality-civil-forfeiture-miss-america/|title=How the 'John Oliver Effect' Is Having a Real-Life Impact|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/29/john-oliver-impact/|title=The John Oliver Effect|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> One of the most commonly cited examples of this is Oliver's first Net Neutrality segment which allegedly led to more than 45,000 comments being sent to the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]], crashing the website set up to receive comments in the process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/03/john-oliver-fcc-website-net-neutrality|title=John Oliver's cheeky net neutrality plea crashes FCC website|last=Holpuch|first=Amanda|date=2014-06-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOliver himself does not believe the effect to be real and has openly ridiculed the idea on the show, even calling the term \"completely meaningless\".{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Tobacco===\n{{Main|Tobacco (Last Week Tonight)}}\n\"Tobacco\" is a segment about the tobacco industry, which aired on February 15, 2015, as part of the second episode of the second season. During the eighteen-minute segment, Oliver discusses tobacco industry trends and practices. He also introduces Jeff the Diseased Lung, a mascot he created for the American global cigarette and tobacco company [[Philip Morris International]], the makers of [[Marlboro (cigarette)|Marlboro]] brand of cigarettes. The anthropomorphic diseased lung, who smokes and coughs, has been compared to Joe Camel and the [[Marlboro Man]]. Oliver and his team promoted the cartoon character by sending shirts with Jeff's image to [[Togo]] and displaying billboards in [[Uruguay]], and by encouraging use of the hashtag #JeffWeCan, which trended on Twitter following the broadcast.\n\nThe segment received widespread media coverage, with several outlets praising Oliver's ability to launch successful marketing campaigns and change perceptions about smoking through the creation of the mascot. The mascot later made an appearance at a protest organized by the \"Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids\" in New York City in May 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|last=Olson|first=Samantha|title=John Oliver's 'Jeff The Diseased Lung' Hits Times Square For Anti-Smoking Awareness Flash Mob|date=May 6, 2015|work=Medical Daily|access-date=September 3, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915181858/http://www.medicaldaily.com/john-olivers-jeff-diseased-lung-hits-times-square-anti-smoking-awareness-flash-mob-332252|archive-date=September 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|title=Youth advocates head to New York City to #StopMarlboro - Kick Butts Day|last=Olmstead|first=Erica|website=Kick Butts Day|date=May 22, 2015|access-date=September 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619163701/https://www.kickbuttsday.org/index.php/updates/detail/2015_05_22_nyc|archive-date=June 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPhilip Morris International issued a response to the segment, stating that it included \"many mischaracterizations\" of the company.<ref name=Parker>{{cite news|last=Parker|first=Ryan|title=John Oliver targets cigarettes on 'Last Week Tonight'; Philip Morris reacts|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|accessdate=November 24, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122195954/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-philip-morris-john-oliver-20150216-story.html|archive-date=November 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies ===\nIn the Mandatory Minimums segment that aired on July 25, 2015, John Oliver talked about the controversial history of presidential pardoning, claiming that Abraham Lincoln once pardoned a man convicted of bestiality because he was intoxicated at the time; the man in question being John Wilkes Booth. He then confessed the statement was not true and for the first time mentioned a book compiling his favorite history lies.\n\nA couple of weeks later, he published a web-exclusive video  based on that reference, expanding the content for a book called \"Stranger Than Truth: John Oliver's 101 Favorite History Lies\", to be released in the following spring. At the end of the mini-segment, however, he confesses again that the entire book was also a lie.\n\nIn what seems a continuation of the lie saga, the book surprisingly appeared on Amazon UK in October 2018.\n\nThe book description reads as follow: <blockquote>There is absolutely nothing more fun than lying confidently about history. Lying is incredibly fun. In fact, the only thing that feels better than lying to someone is lying to someone, then regaining their trust, and then lying to them again. This book, for example, was promised to be released in April 2016. But that was a lie. The plan was always October 2018. Because, you know, now is a time in history when lying openly gets you elected to office. </blockquote><blockquote>In this book, you will find plenty of plausible but completely unverifiable nonsense. Almost like watching Fox News but with a better sense of humour. Hopefully, it will teach you much about nothing other than the true joy of lying to people. Honestly, there has never been a better moment in history to be a liar. We have reached a point where truths have become lies and lies are now the truth. So learn from the greatest and get inspired by the best lies in history. </blockquote><blockquote>*NB: Most profits from this book are going to finance railway infrastructure under the English Channel. Contains strong language.<ref>{{Cite book|title=STRANGER THAN TRUTH.|last=PAUL.|first=OSPREY, FEY. DORIAN|date=2018|publisher=BLURB|isbn=978-0464820208|location=[S.l.]|oclc=1057754076}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption===\n{{Main|Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption}}\nIn August 2015, after delivering his \"Televangelists\" segment, Oliver hired a professional tax lawyer to set up a church called [[Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption]] as a legal entity. He did this partly as a way to demonstrate how \"disturbingly easy\" it is, in terms of paperwork, to set up a [[Tax exemption|tax-exempt]] religious organization as viewed by the [[Internal Revenue Service]]. As Oliver explained, the requirements needed to be defined as a \"church\" are quite broad. Since regulatory guidelines require an established location for a church, Oliver chose his studio location in New York City as its official location,<ref name=\"Mediaite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |last=Wilstein |first=Matt |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver One-Ups Colbert Super PAC by Creating His Own Tax-Exempt Church |work=Mediaite |quote=\"... This is real,\" John Oliver repeatedly told his Last Week Tonight audience last night after announcing the creation of his new megachurch, Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825011710/http://www.mediaite.com/tv/john-oliver-one-ups-colbert-super-pac-by-creating-his-own-tax-exempt-church/ |archive-date=August 25, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> although he registered the [[nonprofit organization]] in the state of [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |last=Pellot |first=Brian |date=August 18, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title='Megareverend' John Oliver trolls televangelists with new tax-exempt church |agency=[[Religion News Service]] |quote=\"... Oliver registered his church as a nonprofit corporation in Texas, named his New York studio as its \"established place of worship,\"...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150819025650/http://www.religionnews.com/2015/08/18/john-oliver-hbo-last-week-tonight-televangelists-church-irs-creflo-dollar-tilton-copeland/ |archive-date=August 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver's \"megachurch\" had a [[Toll-free telephone number|toll-free phone number]] which allowed callers to donate to the church, and said that any money collected would be redistributed to the charitable relief organization [[Doctors Without Borders]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |first=Nate |last=Scott |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver takes on televangelism on 'Last Week Tonight' |work=[[USA Today]] |quote=... You can donate to the church, too. (Though eventually, all the donations will be moved to Doctors Without Borders.) ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822104843/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/john-oliver-takes-on-televangelism-on-last-week-tonight |archive-date=August 22, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Pedestrian>{{cite web |url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |last=Bracken |first=Claire |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=John Oliver launches his very own anti-Evangelist church |work=Pedestrian News |quote=\"... John Oliver ran a segment on \"church's who exploit people's faith for monetary gain\" and explored the ease at which these can be created in America ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904194105/https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/john-oliver-launches-his-very-own-anti-evangelist-church/ |archive-date=September 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver announced the formation of his church on the episode of the show that aired on August 16, 2015.<ref name=\"TimeMag\">{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |first=Melissa |last=Locker |title=John Oliver Becomes a Televangelist and Finally Starts His Own Church |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |work=Time |quote=... The satirical aim of Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption will be to collect copious, tax-exempt donations ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824174155/http://time.com/3999933/john-oliver-televangelist-church-alst-week-tonight/ |archive-date=August 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMatt Wilstein, writing for ''[[Mediaite]]'', saw Oliver's stunt as being along the same lines as comedian [[Stephen Colbert]]'s setting up of a [[501(c)(4)]] organization\u2014[[Colbert Super PAC]]\u2014as a way to \"test the absurd limits of the Supreme Court's [[Citizens United v. FEC|Citizens United decision]]\"; Oliver's megachurch, in contrast, is a way to test whether the IRS might view his \"megachurch\" as a tax-exempt organization.<ref name=\"Mediaite\"/> Steve Thorngate, writing in ''[[The Christian Century]]'', suggested that the question of the religious exemption from taxation was more difficult and nuanced than Oliver portrayed, and not a simple matter of government regulation, describing Oliver's pivot to IRS policy as \"unhelpful.\" However, Thorngate agreed that Oliver's exposure and criticism of \"manipulative sleazeballs\" who \"fleece the faithful\" is \"spot-on.\"<ref name=\"ChristianCentury\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |first=Steve |last=Thorngate |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Why is John Oliver's televangelism segment about the IRS? |work=The Christian Century |quote=\"... Oliver's scornful outrage: televangelists who fleece the faithful ... The question of religious tax exemption generally is more complicated. ...\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820000830/http://www.christiancentury.org/blogs/archive/2015-08/why-john-olivers-televangelism-segment-about-irs |archive-date=August 20, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Leonardo Blair, writing for ''[[Christian Post]]'', described Oliver's segment as a \"brutal takedown\" of televangelists and churches which preach \"the [[prosperity theology|prosperity gospel]],\" a message that dupes people into thinking that cash donations will solve medical or financial problems, while in fact the donations go to the personal aggrandizement of televangelists who buy expensive jets or large mansions.<ref name=\"ChristianPost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |first=Blair |last=Leonardo |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |title=Comedian John Oliver Lampoons Televangelists on 'Last Week Tonight' Show; Opens Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption Church |work=[[The Christian Post]] |quote=... From Creflo Dollar to Kenneth Copeland, late night comedian John Oliver delivered a brutal takedown. ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823142157/http://www.christianpost.com/news/comedian-john-oliver-lampoons-televangelists-on-last-week-tonight-show-opens-our-lady-of-perpetual-exemption-church-143003/ |archive-date=August 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA week later, on the following episode, Oliver devoted a short segment to the donations the church had received, which included money from around the world. Oliver said he had received \"thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars\" from donors. Displayed were several US Post Office containers full of mail. Oliver told viewers that the more money they sent in, the more \"blessings\" would be returned to them, adding that \"that is still something I'm \u2014 amazingly \u2014 legally allowed to say.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title = John Oliver Televangelist Church Received \"Thousands of Dollars,\" Seeds and Beef Jerky|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|website = The Hollywood Reporter|date = August 24, 2015|accessdate = August 25, 2015|quote = ... We have received thousands of envelopes with thousands of dollars ...|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150826221454/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-televangelist-church-received-817058|archive-date = August 26, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOliver announced that the Church would be shutting down during his show on September 13, 2015. All monetary donations have been forwarded to Doctors Without Borders.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | title=Closed. Praise Be Unto You | date=September 13, 2015 | accessdate=September 13, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827212918/http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/ | archive-date=August 27, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\n{{Main|Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump}}\n[[Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|\"Donald Trump\"]] is a segment discussing American businessman Donald Trump. It aired on February 28, 2016, as part of the third episode of the third season. During the 22-minute segment, Oliver discusses [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]] and his long career in business. He also reveals that the Trump family name was changed at one point from the ancestral name 'Drumpf'. Although the changing of names was once a common [[Anglicisation of names|practice]] among many non-English immigrants to the United States, the segment popularized the term \"Donald Drumpf\" and started a campaign urging viewers to \"Make Donald Drumpf Again,\" a play on Trump's own campaign slogan, \"[[Make America Great Again]].\" It is the most popular segment the show has ever done. The segment garnered more than 85 million views on Facebook and YouTube combined which, an HBO spokesman has said, \"is a record for any piece of HBO content.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|title=Even John Oliver enjoys a Drumpf bump|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=March 30, 2016|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331201056/http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|archive-date=March 31, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Throughout the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]] and following [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inauguration]], Oliver made [[Last Week Tonight segments about Donald Trump|additional segments regarding Trump]].\n\n===Debt buyers===\n\"Debt Buyers\" is a segment discussing the business and questionable practice of [[debt buyers]]. It aired on June 5, 2016, as part of the fourteenth episode of the third season. Oliver announced he had purchased nearly $15 million in medical debt that belonged to 9,000 debtors. He did this through a company he had created, called \"Central Asset Recovery Professionals Inc.\" (CARP), which he described as being \"for [[Carp|the bottom-feeding fish]].\" Oliver stated that it was \"pretty clear by now [that] debt buying is a grimy business, and badly needs more oversight\" and went to point out that starting such a business was \"disturbingly easy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |first=Kelly |last=Lawler |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15 million of debt |website=USA Today |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=June 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606180535/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2016/06/06/john-oliver-buys-and-forgives-15-million-of-debt-last-week-tonight/85488616/ |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It cost him $50 to register the business in [[Mississippi]], while it cost less than $60,000 to purchase almost $15 million in [[bad debt]], medical debt from Texas. Oliver forgave the debt in its entirety, and claimed that it was the largest single giveaway in the American television history, eclipsing that of [[General Motors]] on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in 2004 where it gifted cars to Winfrey's studio audience, worth an estimated $8 million in total.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | first=J. Weston | last=Phippen | title=John Oliver's $15 Million Debt Giveaway | website=The Atlantic | date=June 6, 2016 | accessdate=June 6, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160607105724/http://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2016/06/john-oliver-debt/485834/ | archive-date=June 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''Slate'', Jordan Weissmann disputed the $15 million figure: \"[Oliver] says CARP paid around $60,000 ... for its paper, which was 'out-of-statute'\u2014meaning the debts were so old that creditors technically couldn't even sue over them anymore. That suggests the seller thought the debts were worth no more than, well, $60,000.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |title=Sorry, but John Oliver Did Not Really Just Give Away $15 Million |last=Weissmann |first=Jordan |date=June 6, 2016 |newspaper=Slate |issn=1091-2339 |access-date=June 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160606221649/http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/06/john_oliver_did_not_really_give_away_15_million_on_his_show.html |archive-date=June 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The episode was highlighted in the academic journal ''Religions''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krantz |first=David |title=Shmita Revolution: The Reclamation and Reinvention of the Sabbatical Year |work=Religions |date=August 8, 2016 |url=http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920052704/http://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/8/100 |archive-date=September 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The show partnered with RIP Medical Debt, Inc. to abolish the debt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kasperkevic |first1=Jana |title=John Oliver buys and forgives $15m worth of medical debt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |accessdate=June 19, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=June 6, 2016 |quote=Instead of collecting the debt, however, Last Week Tonight partnered with RIP Medical Debt charity and decided to forgive that debt. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140428/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/06/john-oliver-medical-debt-forgiveness-last-week-tonight |archive-date=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|title=The Miracle of Debt Forgiveness on HBO's Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|last=Goff|first=Robert|website=RIP Medical Debt, Inc.|date=June 5, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115132834/https://www.ripmedicaldebt.org/the-miracle-of-debt-forgiveness-on-hbos-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver/|archive-date=November 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Coal mining and Bob Murray ===\nOn June 18, 2017, ''Last Week Tonight''{{'}}s main segment was about coal mining and [[Robert E. Murray|Bob Murray]]. In his segment, Oliver talked about how the safety condition inside the coal mines specifically the 2007 [[Crandall Canyon Mine]] collapse, which killed six miners, in which Oliver criticized Murray for claiming the collapse was caused by an [[earthquake]], despite all evidence demonstrating otherwise.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|title=John Oliver Is In Legal Trouble For His Rant About A Coal CEO|last=Suneson|first=Grant|work=Newsy|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623041444/http://www.newsy.com/stories/coal-ceo-sues-john-oliver-and-his-show-for-defamation/|archive-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The show ended with a costumed [[squirrel]] named \"Mr. Nutterbutter\" presenting Murray with a voided check for \"3 acorns and 18 cents\" in response to Murray's company presenting its employees with low sums of money as bonuses, and how the employees retaliate by voiding the checks, and in reference to a claim that stated that Murray supposedly got the idea to start his company from a talking squirrel.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Coal: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO) |series=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=June 18, 2017 |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |network=HBO |last=Oliver |first=John (host) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623002244/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aw6RsUhw1Q8 |archivedate=June 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 22, Bob Murray presented a [[lawsuit]] against Oliver, HBO, and [[Time Warner]] for defamation. HBO believes ''Last Week Tonight'' has done nothing wrong, with a [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] lawyer describing the lawsuit as \"frivolous.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In February 2018, a West Virginia judge stated that he plans to dismiss the lawsuit filed by Murray as unfounded.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oppenheim|first1=Maya|title=Coal tycoon's defamation lawsuit against John Oliver dismissed by judge|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=The Independent|date=February 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225060807/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/john-oliver-bob-murray-defamation-lawsuit-dismissed-judge-murray-energy-corp-a8226846.html|archive-date=February 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Murray's appeal to the West Virginia Supreme Court was delayed due to impeachment of the judges, Murray offered to drop the charges and HBO accepted.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/11/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-lawsuits-murray-energy|title=John Oliver takes on muzzling lawsuits \u2013 and the man who sued his show|last=Horton|first=Adrian|date=November 11, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On November 10, 2019, Oliver discussed the case in a segment about [[SLAPP|SLAPP suits]], revealing that the suit cost HBO $200,000 in legal costs and tripled the show's libel insurance fees. Oliver acknowledged that, despite the segment being vetted, the content would likely lead to another lawsuit, and that he would stand behind his team if it were to happen.<ref name=\":1\" /> The segment was ended with a five-minute, [[Times Square]]-set [[musical number]] featuring crude and ludicrous fictional anecdotes about Murray; the musical is titled \"Eat Shit, Bob.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===''A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo''===\n{{Main|A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo}}\nOn March 18, 2018, Oliver announced the publication of a children's book, ''[[A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo]]'', which parodies a book that [[Mike Pence]]'s family wrote about their family rabbit, [[Marlon Bundo's: A Day in the Life of the Vice President|Marlon Bundo]]. Oliver used his book as a platform to criticize Pence's positions on LGBT issues, as it featured a rabbit in a same-sex relationship.<ref name=\"Daily Beast Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=March 19, 2018 |title=John Oliver Trolls Vice President Mike Pence With Gay Children's Book of His Pet Bunny |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |work=Daily Beast |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319104738/https://www.thedailybeast.com/john-oliver-trolls-vice-president-mike-pence-with-gay-childrens-book-of-his-pet-bunny |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The book became the number-one book and e-book on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] the next day, and the top-selling audiobook on [[Audible (store)|Audible]].<ref name=\"Politico Bundo\">{{cite news |last=Nelson |first=Louis |date=March 19, 2018 |title=Comey's memoir tops Amazon's best-sellers list |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |work=Politico |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319140528/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/19/james-comey-memoir-sales-470281 |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/03/john-oliver-marlon-bundo-book-mike-pence-troll|title=John Oliver's Gay-Bunny Book Is Outselling the Mike Pence Book It's Trolling|first=Hillary|last=Busis|website=Vanity Fair|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Russell Crowe's jockstrap===\n{{main|Russell Crowe's jockstrap}}\n[[Russell Crowe's jockstrap]] became a notable piece of memorabilia when it was purchased by the ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' and then donated to a Blockbuster Video shop. The jockstrap reappeared in a skit in the final episode of the 2018 season of the show.\n\n===Robocalls===\nThe March 10, 2019, episode dealt primarily with [[robocalls]], and how the problem had mushroomed in recent years since being increasingly deregulated under [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC Chairman]] [[Ajit Pai]]. To prove the point of how easy it was for any company to begin flooding anyone with robocalls, Oliver had one of his IT techs develop a system in which all of the FCC chairs would, at regular intervals on their personal phone numbers, receive a robocall followed immediately by [[bagpipe]] music. Oliver freely admitted his astonishment at just how easy this was to accomplish; the IT technician tasked with setting the system up told him they needed only 15 minutes to complete the project, doing so on a minimal budget. And per the very FCC regulations currently in place, Oliver quickly scrolled a section of fine print on screen at a random time during the segment, in which his office address was randomly embedded, and each FCC chair was required to send him an official letter to that address, notifying him in writing that they wished to have him cease all robocalls forthwith. Oliver was also flabbergasted at discovering that while tens of millions of dollars in fines were levied against companies for violating robocall regulations, only a few thousand dollars have ever been collected, effectively giving the companies free rein to continue robocalling unabated.\n\n===''Guinness World Records''===\nThe main story of the August 11, 2019 episode was [[Turkmenistan]] and its autocratic leader [[Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow]]. The last portion of the segment centered around Berdimuhamedow's obsession with ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', with the Turkmen capital of [[Ashgabat]] being home to the most buildings with white marble cladding, the largest indoor [[Ferris wheel]], and the largest statue of a horse's head, among others. Oliver found that ''Guinness World Records'' received sums of money ranging from US$12,000 to US$500,000 from companies and authoritarian nations to set records for publicity. He ended the show with a 600 square foot [[marble cake]] adorned with a picture of Berdimuhamedow falling from a horse; he had requested a Guinness adjudicator to certify it as the world's largest marble cake, a record previously set by [[Betty Crocker]] in Saudi Arabia in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|title=A gift 'fresh from the heart' in Saudi Arabia|website=General Mills|language=en|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=August 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815165112/https://blog.generalmills.com/2017/09/a-gift-fresh-from-the-heart-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness refused, stating that because their brand was \"aligned with kids and families\", they would not send an adjudicator; Oliver mockingly commented that he didn't \"run a brutal enough dictatorship to meet Guinness World Records' high ethical standards\". Oliver claimed that Guinness offered to certify it after the fact only if he signed an agreement not to criticize their practices on the show, which Oliver dismissed as \"ridiculous\".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E |title=Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver |date=August 11, 2019 |author=HBO |access-date=August 15, 2019 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815170404/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9QYu8LtH2E&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|title=John Oliver Bakes Very Large Cake to Annoy Turkmenistan|website=Time|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814150445/https://time.com/5648682/john-oliver-turkmenistan-cake/|archive-date=August 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Guinness called Oliver's allegations \"false and unfair\", claiming that they did not send an adjudicator because they felt the cake was specifically for the purpose of mocking a record holder, stating it was their policy \"not to partake in any activities which may belittle their achievements or subject them to ridicule\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|title=Guinness World Records on Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|date=August 12, 2019|website=Guinness World Records|language=en-GB|access-date=August 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813023105/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/8/guinness-world-records-on-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-586398/|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Narendra Modi===\n\nJohn Oliver extensively satirized Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in a broadcast which went online on February 23, 2020 calling him a temporary symbol of hate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qVIXUhZ2AWs |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Last Week Tonight |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was during a visit of US President [[Donald Trump]] to India, and in an [[Namaste Trump|organized rally]] which unexpectedly coincided with [[North East Delhi riots|large-scale violence in Delhi]], the country's capital. In this episode, Oliver likened Modi's [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP party's]] political beliefs to [[Adolf Hitler|Adolf Hitler's]], by noting that this party's founders, in 1925, had admired Hitler for his methods to ensure \u201cthe purity of the race\u201d \u2013 \u201cwhich is just not a chill thing to admire Hitler - and that, there is one and only one thing that it\u2019s OK to admire Hitler for, and it\u2019s the fact that he killed Hitler.\" <ref name=\"TempHate\">{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Adrian|title=John Oliver explains Trump's support of Modi, India's 'temporary symbol of hate'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|accessdate=February 26, 2018|work=Guardian|date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229180408/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/feb/24/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-recap-trump-modi-india|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver also lampooned Trump's choice of words to describe Modi as \"the father of India\", suggesting that there is a [[Mahatma Gandhi|certain Gandhi]] that already holds that exact title.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/> The brunt of his attacks, however, were aimed at Modi's \"increasingly controversial reputation and [[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|widespread protests against his government's citizenship measures]].\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>In his attempt to explain the political climate in India under BJP which condones [[Violence against Muslims in India|widespread violence against Muslims]], Oliver mentions how Modi's party-appointed head of [[Uttar Pradesh]], the largest BJP-ruled state of India, said at a recent rally: \u201cIf they kill one Hindu then we will also kill 100 of them (Muslims).\"<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>He further adds that Modi's party has also edited religious pluralism out of history textbooks, and introduced primary school textbooks teaching Indian supremacy, and that the image is \"nauseating\" and that for perhaps the first time in Modi's whole career, his actions are creating a massive and sustained backlash.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>Oliver concludes this segment by saying that when Trump says Modi is bringing India together, \u201cwith any luck, the thing that unites them may actually end up being their complete disgust over what he is trying to do\u201d, since India, home of the \u201csymbol of love\u201d [[Taj Mahal]], \u201cfrankly deserves much more than this temporary symbol of hate\u201d.<ref name=\"TempHate\"/>\n\n[[Disney+ Hotstar|Hotstar]], an Indian streaming service who holds rights to HBO programming in the country, refused to stream the episode, leading to criticism by local viewers (including Hotstar's apps being [[Review bombing|review bombed]] with 1-star reviews).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-1-star-reviews-modi-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-censorship-backlash-2185798|title=Hotstar Gets 1-Star Reviews for Pro-Government Censorship of John Oliver|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Oliver addressed the censorship in the March 8, 2020 episode, also noting that since the acquisition of Hotstar by [[The Walt Disney Company]] (which occurred as part of its [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/hotstar-southeast-asia-expansion-disney-bob-iger-star-india-2081496|title=Disney Plans Southeast Asia Expansion for Hotstar|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Hotstar had begun to censor jokes regarding Disney characters from the program, such as his \"factually-accurate\" claim that [[Donald Duck]] had a [[corkscrew penis]].<ref name=\"thr-lwthotstar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-oliver-slams-disney-owned-hotstar-removing-jokes-disney-1283146|title=John Oliver Slams Disney-Owned Streamer for Censoring 'Last Week Tonight' Jokes About Disney|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\n''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'' episode clips can be seen internationally on [[YouTube]]. It is broadcast on [[Pay television|premium]] channel [[HBO Canada]] that is [[simulcast]] with HBO in the U.S.; around the same time it is shown on the international [[HBO (international)|HBO]] channels. It airs in Australia on [[The Comedy Channel]] hours after the U.S. airing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|title=Airdate: Last Week Tonight|last=Knox|first=David|date=April 11, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2014|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200503/http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/airdate-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver.html|archive-date=June 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and airs in New Zealand on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver coming to SoHo|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=Dan News|accessdate=August 13, 2015|archivedate=August 13, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813114138/http://dannews.co.nz/2015/01/28/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-coming-to-soho/}}</ref> In the United Kingdom and Ireland, it is broadcast on Mondays on [[Sky Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sky.com/watch/title/series/b7a772c4-8fdb-4e28-be16-66141b9b34d6/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver |publisher=Sky |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In Belgium, it is broadcast on Thursdays by the [[Telenet (Belgium)|Telenet]] cable-only channel [[Prime (Flanders)|PRIME Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver S2|publisher=Telenet/PRIME|accessdate=February 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150221095413/http://www.prime.be/series/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-2|archivedate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> It airs in South Africa on [[M-Net]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|publisher=channel24.co.za|title=M-Net adds exciting new late night talk show to its schedule|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=September 9, 2015|last=Ferreira|first=Thinus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930202818/http://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/M-Net-adds-exciting-new-late-night-talk-show-to-its-schedule-20140430|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and in Portugal on [[RTP3]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferreira|first1=David|trans-title=|title=Conhe\u00e7a a programa\u00e7\u00e3o da nova RTP3 (com v\u00eddeo)|url=http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|language=Portuguese|accessdate=September 29, 2015|publisher=A Televis\u00e3o|date=September 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930130307/http://www.atelevisao.com/cabo/conheca-a-programacao-da-nova-rtp3/|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In India, the show is streamed on Hotstar Premium.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Series Full Episodes, Watch Last Week Tonight with John Oliver TV Show Online | access-date=November 18, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164539/https://www.hotstar.com/tv/last-week-tonight/s-585 | archive-date=November 18, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Comedy|Television}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hbo.com/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=3530232|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{tv.com show|last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Facebook|LastWeekTonight}}\n* {{YouTube|u=LastWeekTonight|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Last Week Tonight}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of awards and nominations received by Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Awards for ''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver'']]\n|list=\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Talk Show}}\n{{Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Talk Series}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in News and Information}}\n{{Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy-Variety Talk Series}}\n}}\n{{Late night television in the United States}}\n{{HBONetwork Shows}}\n\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver| ]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American late-night television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American late-night television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American political comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:American news parodies]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:HBO original programming]]\n[[Category:Political satirical television series]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Censored television series]]\n[[Category:Works banned in China]]\n", "name_user": "KyleStAubyn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated the format of the show due to social distancing guidelines", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Last_Week_Tonight_with_John_Oliver"}
{"title_page": "Paul Masvidal", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Paul Masvidal\n| image            = Paul Masvidal 2020.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Photo by [http://darrinnoble.com/ Darrin Noble]\n| image_size       = 250\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Paul Albert Masvidal\n| alias            = \n| birth_place      = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1971|1|20}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Miami, Florida]], United States\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals\n* keyboards\n* [[guitar synthesizer]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Progressive rock]]}}\n* [[heavy metal music|metal]]\n* [[ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[experimental music|experimental]]\n* [[acoustic music|acoustic]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* Songwriter\n* Artist\n}}\n| years_active     = 1987\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* [[Season of Mist]]\n* [[SPV GmbH|SPV]]\n* [[Warner Music]]\n* [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]\n* Portal\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]]\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]]\n* Onward With Love\n* Masvidal\n}}\n| website          = http://masvidalien.com/\n}}\n\n'''Paul Albert Masvidal''' (born 20 January 1971) is an American guitarist, songwriter and producer. He is the guitarist, singer, and a founding member of the progressive rock band, [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]. He has remained a continual member for nearly three decades and has developed numerous other projects including [[\u00c6on Spoke]], Onward with Love, and recent his solo work. Masvidal was ranked in ''[[Loudwire]]''<nowiki/>'s 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists Of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/top-hard-rock-metal-guitarists-of-all-time/|title=The 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists of All Time|last=Staff|first=Loudwire|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and 50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/best-metal-songwriters/|title=50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time|last=DiVita|first=Joe|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nPaul Masvidal was born in San Juan, Puerto Rico to Cuban-American civic and business leader Raul Masvidal. Masvidal's early years were spent in the Miami area where he studied classical guitar with [[Carlos Molina (guitarist)|Carlos Molina]], and in college, with jazz musician, Dave Weissbrot who inspired his love of jazz, [[Steinberger|Steinberger guitars]], and introduced him to [[Buddhist philosophy]]. Masvidal developed an interest in mysticism and esoteric topics from a young age, becoming an initiate to [[Kriya Yoga]] in his late teens and eventually a practitioner of [[Buddhist meditation]] by his late 20s. Masvidal met drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in 1984 at [[Gulliver Schools|Gulliver Academy]] In Miami, where the duo began making music the day they met, eventually forming the pre-Cynic groups, Crypha and Seaweed. Masvidal's eclectic musical tastes ranging from classical to rock, jazz, fusion, and metal along with a innate passion for mysticism came to inform much of his work with Cynic and other projects. Masvidal wrote in detail about early life experiences in his Mett\u0101 Mind Journal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metalsucks.net/2010/04/07/metta-mind-journal-with-cynics-paul-masvidal-the-bird-outside-my-window/|title=METTA MIND JOURNAL WITH CYNIC'S PAUL MASVIDAL: \"THE BIRD OUTSIDE MY WINDOW\"|date=2010-04-07|website=MetalSucks|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> series, which he published on the music blog [[MetalSucks]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nMasvidal co-founded Cynic with drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in the late 80\u2019s, having released four demos from 1988-1991 that circulated in the underground tape trading community. Masvidal developed a reputation in the South Florida music scene for his musicianship and attention began to grow quickly around the band. In 1989, while still in high school, Masvidal toured Mexico as a replacement guitarist for the band [[Death (metal band)|Death]], but declined an invitation to permanently join the band in order to remain committed to Cynic. This had many journalists curious at the time, since Death were emerging as an influential and popular act, but Masvidal persevered with Cynic. However, Masvidal returned to the Death fold replacing guitarist [[James Murphy (guitarist)|James Murphy]] for tour dates on the international ''[[Spiritual Healing (album)|Spiritual Healing]]'' tour in 1990. In 1991, Masvidal and fellow Cynic member Reinert were recruited by Death to record the \"groundbreaking\" ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]''. In 2017, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine placed the album as the 70th greatest metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/|title=The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time|last=Christe|first=Christopher R. Weingarten,Tom Beaujour,Hank Shteamer,Kim Kelly,Steve Smith,Brittany Spanos,Suzy Exposito,Richard Bienstock,Kory Grow,Dan Epstein,J D. Considine,Andy Greene,Rob Sheffield,Adrien Begrand,Ian|last2=Weingarten|first2=Christopher R.|date=2017-06-21|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15|last3=Beaujour|first3=Tom|last4=Shteamer|first4=Hank|last5=Kelly|first5=Kim|last6=Smith|first6=Steve|last7=Spanos|first7=Brittany|last8=Exposito|first8=Suzy|last9=Bienstock|first9=Richard}}</ref>. Masvidal toured extensively for ''Human'', in addition to appearing in the [[music video]] for ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7j8vUbMmOwM \"Lack of Comprehension\"]'', which debuted on MTV's [[Headbangers Ball]]. After fulfilling their obligations with Death, both Masvidal and Reinert returned to Cynic in 1992. In 2013, Masvidal joined forces with other original members of the Death ''Human'' line up and toured worldwide in honor of [[Chuck Schuldiner]]'s legacy with the group DTA (Death to All).\n[[File:Cynic, Focus (1993).jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Focus'' (1993)]]\n1993 saw the release of the \u201cprogressive landmark\u201d album, ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' on [[Roadrunner Records]]. ''Focus'' was listed in Rock Hard magazine's book as one of ''The 500 Greatest Rock & Metal Albums of All Time''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rensen|first=Michael|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/best-of-rock-metal-die-500-starksten-scheiben-aller-zeiten/oclc/62273803|title=Best of Rock & Metal: die 500 st\u00e4rksten Scheiben aller Zeiten|last2=Heine|first2=Uwe|last3=Stratmann|first3=Holger|last4=Villalonga|first4=Marc|date=2005|publisher=Heel|isbn=978-3-89880-517-9|location=K\u00f6nigswinter|language=German|oclc=62273803}}</ref>. ''[[Loudwire]]'' writer Graham Hartmann named Focus the ninth best debut metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/cynic-focus-best-debut-metal-albums/|title=No. 9: Cynic, 'Focus' \u2013 Best Debut Metal Albums|last=Hartmann|first=Graham|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. Roadrunner released a reissue of Focus in 2004 as a special collector's edition due to high demand. Cynic took a 12 year hiatus in 1995 after recording \"''The Portal Tapes\"'' demos. Masvidal moved to Los Angeles in the fall of 1996, upon being offered a full scholarship at [[Musicians Institute]], where he also began work as a session musician and composer for network TV and film. \n\n[[File:Aeon Spoke Band.jpg|thumb|152x152px|[[\u00c6on Spoke]]|alt=]]During Cynic's hiatus, Masvidal founded [[\u00c6on Spoke]], whose ethereal indie rock was heralded as \"beautiful, exquisite [and] destined for greatness\" by Janice Long, BBC Radio. In 2004, the band received airplay on BBC Radio 2 and XFM for the single \"Silence\". The following year, the track \"Emmanuel\" appeared in the indie breakout film ''[[What the Bleep Do We Know!?]]'' \u00c6on Spoke songs have also appeared on the Warner Bros. television series ''[[Smallville]]'', ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' and the motion picture ''[[Cry Wolf (2005 film)|Cry Wolf]]''. \u00a0Their self-titled debut LP was released in 2007 on SPV Records.\n\n\n[[File:Cynic, Traced In Air (2008).jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Traced In Air'' (2008)]]\nCynic reunited in 2008 to record ''[[Traced in Air|Traced In Air]]'', their comeback opus. In his review<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/arts/music/01choi.html|title=New CDs|date=2008-11-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, ''New York Times'' music critic Ben Ratliff wrote that Cynic \"should be understood not so much alongside any metal bands but along with the radical harmonic progressives in the last 45 years of pop and jazz: composers like Milton Nascimento, the Beach Boys or Pat Metheny.\" [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] described it as \"A Modern Classic.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/a-modern-classic-cynics-e_b_190622|title=A Modern Classic: Cynic's Traced in Air , A Reunion Album As Good As the Classic Debut|last=Remington|first=Alex|last2=ContributorBlogger|date=2009-05-24|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 and 2011 Cynic released two conceptual records: ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010), featuring re-interpretations of several ''Traced in Air'' tracks, and ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011). ''Rolling Stone'' music critic Hank Shteamer raved in his review<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16034-carbon-based-anatomy-ep/|title=Cynic: Carbon-Based Anatomy EP|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> of ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'': \"The title track is a perfectly paced stunner...Cynic sounds fully liberated, not just from their metal past but from any aesthetic concern other than assembling a great song.\" The album's opening track ''\"Amidst The Coals\"'' features artist, [[Amy Correia]] singing an adaptation of an Amazonian [[Icaro]], inspired by Masvidal's work with the South American entheogenic brew, [[Ayahuasca]]. \u00a0  <gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Cynic, Re-Traced (2010).jpg|Cynic, ''Re-Traced'' (2010)\nFile:Cynic, Carbon-Based Anatomy (2011).jpg|Cynic, ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'' (2011)\n</gallery>\n[[File:Cynic, Kindly Bent to Free Us (2014).jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Kindly Bent to Free Us'' (2014)]]\nCynic's third full-length album, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'', released in 2014, was hailed by [[Malcolm Dome|Malcome Dome]] of ''[[Prog (magazine)|Prog]]'' magazine as \"an album that transcends all the limitations of genre and era... There are few albums which can claim such a remarkable hold.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/cynic-kindly-bent-to-free-us|title=Cynic: Kindly Bent To Free Us|last=February 2014|first=Malcolm Dome 11|website=Prog Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The album rose to No. 4 on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Heatseekers chart in February 2014 and was No. 1 on CMJ's Loud Rock Chart the following month.\n<nowiki/><blockquote>\"Kindly Bent to Free Us [is] an album that, while most definitely in the realm of prog rock, has the kind of open, unpretentious air that makes Rush such an easy-to-love band.\" - [[AllMusic.com|allmusic.com]]</blockquote><blockquote>\"The alchemy of front man Paul Masvidal (vocals, guitars & keyboards) combined with rhythmaniac Sean Reinert (drums) and the technically divine Sean Malone (bass), make Cynic one of the finest Prog Rock bands to have ever of landed on Planet Earth\" - [https://burningfist.co.uk burningfist.co.uk]</blockquote>[[File:Onward with Love.jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Onward with Love, 2015]]In 2015, Masvidal ventured into the performing-arts world with masked duo Onward with Love (OwL), a musical collaboration with acclaimed singer-songwriter [[Amy Correia]]. The pair's singular points of view make for an intriguing synthesis of Eastern-influenced philosophy, symbolist poetry, American blues, jazz and experimental rock. OwL has performed in concert venues, hospices and art galleries around greater Los Angeles. In 2015, OwL unveiled a video for the song ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHrg6W6gddY \"Kali In My Arms\"]'', which was featured in the HBO TV series and film, ''[[Looking (TV series)|Looking]]''. The duo officially released the song [https://distrokid.com/hyperfollow/onwardwithlove/kali-in-my-arms digitally] in 2019 have plans to release a full-length record by 2021.\n\nIn 2016, Masvidal, along with collaborator [[Amy Correia]], composed the musical score for the award-winning feature film ''[[The Tiger Hunter]]'', featuring lead actor [[Danny Pudi]]. The film was released in over 60 cities nationwide,won the grand jury prize for narrative feature at the Los Angeles Asian Pacific Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/los-angeles-asian-pacific-film-festival-the-tiger-hunter-hooligan-sparrow-win-1201768412/|title=\u2018Tiger Hunter\u2019 and \u2018Hooligan Sparrow\u2019 Win Big at L.A. Asian Pacific Film Festival|last=Cavassuto|first=Maria|last2=Cavassuto|first2=Maria|date=2016-05-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and garnered effusively positive reviews from The New York Times, Los Angeles Times, and more. In 2017, Correia and Masvidal scored the main title to CW Networks, game show \"Save To Win\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pilotonline.com/business/article_2428e2c3-f385-5b17-805a-58e61daa7316.html|title=Family Dollar launches &quot;Save to Win&quot; game show on The CW|last=Pierceall|first=Kimberly|website=pilotonline.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Creators Scott Weiner and Paul Reaney described the song as \"acid jazz meets 70's game show.\" Most recently the duo composed end title song for the feature film [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lKzGNIk4XBI&fbclid=IwAR2nbrqJe9IjfUrakvWKP7oR6KQIJyRg711IfBCckEqKdKsffbYMBsMmDkU ''The Deported''] which made the official selection at the prestigious New York Latin Film Festival and the [[Beverly Hills Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beverlyhillsfilmfestival.com/2019-official-selection-fri/|title=2019 Official Selection Fri {{!}} Beverly Hills Film Festival {{!}} Official Site|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.  \n\nMasvidal also writes and performs music for television and motion pictures. His credits include main title (composer credit) on an Emmy nominated NBC teen series show ''[[Operation Junkyard]]'', short films ''The Yellow Umbrella'', ''A Bride in Black'', assistant to [[Ben Vaughn]] and session musician for Carsey Warner network sitcoms ''[[That '70s Show]]'' and ''[[3rd Rock from the Sun]]''. In 2013 Masvidal founded composing collective [http://stillmotionmusic.com/ Still Motion Music] which scored music for numerous TV series on H2, National Geographic, Bravo, ABC and PBS. Masvidal also has a library songs regularly performed on network and cable television. Music writer Jeff Wagner, in his book ''[[Mean Deviation (book)|Mean Deviation]]:'' Four Decades of Progressive Heavy Metal, stated that \"any viewer of ''3rd Rock from the Sun'', ''That '70s Show'', ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'', ''[[Queer as Folk (2000 TV series)|Queer as Folk]]'', and any number of random television programs has probably stumbled across Cynic's core members without even knowing it.\" In 2015, Masvidal produced a children's album for actor [[Jim Carrey]] titled ''How Roland Rolls''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howrolandrolls.com/the-ep/|title=The EP {{!}} How Roland Rolls|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\n[[File:Cynic Humanoid.jpg|thumb|150x150px|Cynic - Humanoid (Single)|alt=]]In January 2018, Cynic released a digital single, titled ''\"Humanoid\"''. The song featured new drummer, Matt Lynch with longtime bassist and collaborator, [[Sean Malone]]. \"Humanoid\" marked the first new music from the progressive pioneers since the band's 2014 album ''Kindly Bent to Free Us''. The artwork features a detail from the painting \"Ayahuasca Dream\" by [[Robert Venosa]], Cynic's longtime collaborator and celebrated artist who passed away in 2011. <blockquote>\"Venosa and Masvidal recognized each other as fellow artists in the pursuit of authentic, spirit-based artistic expression in sound and imagery.\" - \u00a0[https://www.martinahoffmann.com/ Martina Hoffman], painter and Venosa's wife, from the book ...''And Justice for Art, Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers'' by Ramon Martos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://andjusticeforart.bigcartel.com/product/and-justice-for-art-stories-about-heavy-metal-album-covers-volume-2|title=...And Justice For Art: Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers|last=Art|first=And Justice For|website=And Justice For Art|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 2019 and 2020 Masvidal ventured into releasing work as a solo artist under the name 'Masvidal' releasing three conceptual albums titled ''Mythical Human Vessel.'' The artwork for the three albums was designed by visual artists Igraine Grey and Jonatan Martinez aka [https://cargocollective.com/greymar/about Greymar]. <gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:MYTHICAL Album.jpg|MYTHICAL\nFile:HUMAN Album by Masvidal.jpg|HUMAN\nFile:VESSEL Album by Masvidal.jpg|VESSEL\n</gallery>Produced by three-time [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] winner Warren Riker (Lauryn Hill, Fugees, Santana). Drawing on influences from musicians [[John Lennon]], [[Brian Eno]], [[Chet Baker]], Russill Paul and [https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/artist/Elliott Elliott Smith] to visual artists - [[Mark Rothko]], [[Cai Guo-Qiang]], [[Hilma af Klint|Hilma af Klimt]], the songs embrace concise forms and catchy melodies in spite of their often painful subject matters of loss, depression, and heartache. In Masvidal's view, \"pain is not something to be feared but embraced as inevitable and, ultimately, a doorway.\" ''Billboard'' described the work\u00a0''Mythical Human Vessel'', finds Masvidal at his most vulnerable, often with just a guitar and vocals, while experimenting with brain entrainment, a series of pulsing sounds that are said to lead to enhanced neural perception and memory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8513968/paul-masvidal-interview-brain-experiment|title=Paul Masvidal's Solo Project Doubles as a Brain Entrainment Experiment|date=2019-05-31|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOther press related to MHV: Human<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8532688/paul-masvidal-interview-human-track-by-track-rundown|title=Paul Masvidal 'Human' Track-by-Track: Cynic Frontman Explains New EP|date=2019-10-10|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> / Vessel<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9324719/paul-masvidal-releases-final-installment-of-mythical-human-vessel-trilogy?fbclid=IwAR3AhHwixQ7LGFZjUtZ1hWW9-ErQ3yH2rH8LZ-k6OsLBmgOGJLyAy0MUqqs|title=Paul Masvidal&#39;s &#39;Mythical Human Vessel&#39; Finale|date=2020-03-06|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nBen Ratliff of the ''New York Times'' referred to Masvidal's \"philosophic lyrics\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratliff|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/02/arts/music/02buried.html|title=From Jazz-Rock Fusion to Progressive Metal, With a Virtuosic Accompaniment|date=2010-02-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> stating that he is \"a musician who can expand his own sense of calm into an aggressive, extravagant art\".\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAs an inventor, Masvidal filed a successful patent ([http://www.vidatak.com/index.html Vidatak] EZ Board US Patent No. 6,422,875) in 1999 (which was approved in 2002), involving a device to assist voice-disabled individuals. Masvidal's interest stems from his extensive volunteer work with AIDS patients, the terminally ill and the elderly in the Los Angeles area.\n\nIn May 2014, the [[Los Angeles Times]] did a front cover story on Masvidal's coming out as a homosexual along with fellow Cynic member [[Sean Reinert]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-c1-gay-heavy-metal-20140508-story.html|title=Great Read: Cynic's Paul Masvidal, Sean Reinert are out and ready to be loud|date=2014-05-08|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. For gay pride month June 2017, Masvidal talked to Billboard about his experiences as gay man in the rock and metal community<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/7842075/paul-masvidal-lgbtq-hard-rock-metal|title=Paul Masvidal on LGBTQ Acceptance In the Hard Rock/Metal Community|date=2017-06-29|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>:<blockquote>\"We were always outsiders as a metal band, not only sonically with our influences coming at it from a totally different direction, but we never wore the masculine badge as being tough guys or any of that. We oftentimes wore very colorful clothes, so we were just a little more eccentric and kind of outside the box...\" </blockquote>In an interview<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tricycle.org/trikedaily/buddhist-rocker/|title=The Heavy Metta of a Buddhist Rocker|last=Strahley|first=Erin|date=2018-11-07|website=Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> for [[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|Tricycle magazine]], Masvidal elaborated on the origins of Cynic's name, Buddhism and his creative process. \n\nMasvidal has been a [[vegetarian]] since 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/progmetal/comments/2gsxkr/greeting_this_is_paul_welcome_to_my_ama/|title=r/progmetal - Greeting this is Paul, welcome to my AMA!|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nMasvidal began work with his brother, [https://www.dancingshiva.com/about/our-founder Maheshananda], an established and influential teacher of Yoga and Ayurveda in 2018, offering Ayurvedic and [[Cannabidiol|CBD]]-based products with company ''[https://morelifemarket.com/ More Life Market]''.\n\nMasvidal has most recently entered into the creation of physical objects, developing [[Orgone|Orgonite]] related devices and [[Sacred geometry|sacred geometric]] amulets. His interest in [[Cosmology]], [[Consciousness]], [[Extra-terrestrials|Extra-Terrestrials]], [[Unidentified flying object|UFOs]], [[Crop circle|crop circles]] and their connection to his spiritual interests have become integral to his work as an artist.\n\n==Gear==\n[[File:Masvidalien Cosmo.png|thumb|152x152px|The Masvidalien Cosmo|alt=]]Masvidal has been playing [[Steinberger]] GM & GR headless 6-string guitars since his beginnings as a professional musician. Although he was seen by far the most with this instrument, he was also seen playing a Gibson SG with \u00c6on Spoke. Since Masvidal's association with the DTA (earlier called ''Death To All'') tours in 2013, a touring tribute to his former band [[Death (metal band)|Death]] and the songs of [[Chuck Schuldiner]], he has been playing his signature Strandberg ''Masvidalien'' headless 6-string guitar. He also had his recording debut with this new Strandberg guitar on Cynic's 2014 release, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]''.\nMasvidal lent his name to a line of signature instruments aptly named, ''Masvidalien Cosmo''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://strandbergguitars.com/artists/paul-masvidal/|title=Paul Masvidal|website=.strandberg* Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> produced by Sweden's award-winning '''[https://strandbergguitars.com/ .strandberg* Guitars]'''. \n\n<br /> \n==Discography==\n\n=== Cynic ===\n\n* ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' (1993)\n*''Focus'' 'Remastered Re-Issue with bonus tracks' (2004)\n* ''[[Traced in Air]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Portal Tapes]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'' (2014)\n*''Uroboric Forms - The Complete Demo Recordings'' (2017)\n*''Humanoid'' single release (2018)\n*''Traced In Air''\u00a0'Remixed' (2019)\n\n=== Solo ===\n\n* ''Mythical'' (2019)\n* ''Human'' (2019)\n* ''Vessel'' (2020) \n\n=== Other ===\n\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]] \u2212 ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]'' (1991)\n*[[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[Above the Buried Cry]]'' (2004)\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[\u00c6on Spoke (album)|\u00c6on Spoke]]'' (2007)\n\n=== Guest/Session ===\n\n*[[Master (American band)|Master]] \u2013 ''On The Seventh Day God Created... Master'' (1991) (guitars)\n*[[Terri Nunn|Terri Nunn (Berlin)]] (1997) - co-wrote songs for an unreleased solo album\n*[[Gordian Knot (band)|Gordian Knot]] \u2212 ''[[Emergent (album)|Emergent]]'' (2003)\n*[[Amy Correia]] - ''Lakeville'' (2004) (Guitar, Piano, keyboards)\n*[[Exivious]] \u2013 ''Exivious'' (2009) (guitar solo on \"Embrace The Unknown\")\n*[[Devin Townsend Project]] \u2013 ''[[Deconstruction (Devin Townsend Project album)|Deconstruction]]'' (2010) (vocals on \"Sumeria\")\n*[[Gene Ween|Aaron Freeman]] - ''Marvelous Clouds''\u00a0 (2012) (Acoustic guitar)\n*[[Chris Schlarb]] \u2013 ''Psychic Temple II'' (2013)\n* [[Persefone]] \u2013 ''AATHMA'' (2017) (vocals on ''Living Waves'')\n* [[Neil Grant]] - ''Location Persuader'' (2017) (Guitars & vocals on \"Throw me out there!\")\n* [[Contrarian]] \u2013 ''To Perceive Is to Suffer'' (2017) (vocals on \"At Fate's Hands\")\n*[https://stephanepigeon.com/ Dr. Stefane Pigeon] (2019) - ''Mythical Human Vessel'''s Isochronic Tones, Transdimensional Traveler 'Mynoise' player\n* BRVMAK - ''In Nomine Patris'' (2019) (vocals on \"Omnipotence\")  \n* Moon Destroys - ''Maiden Voyage'' (2020) (vocals on \"Stormbringer\")\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Cynic}}\n{{Death (band)}}\n{{\u00c6on Spoke}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masvidal, Paul}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Death metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Death (metal band) members]]\n[[Category:Progressive metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Cynic (band) members]]\n[[Category:\u00c6on Spoke members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Paul Masvidal\n| image            = Paul Masvidal 2020.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Photo by [http://darrinnoble.com/ Darrin Noble]\n| image_size       = 250\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Paul Albert Masvidal\n| alias            = \n| birth_place      = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1971|1|20}}\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Miami, Florida]], United States\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals\n* keyboards\n* [[guitar synthesizer]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Progressive rock]]}}\n* [[heavy metal music|metal]]\n* [[ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[experimental music|experimental]]\n* [[acoustic music|acoustic]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* Songwriter\n* Artist\n}}\n| years_active     = 1987\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n* [[Season of Mist]]\n* [[SPV GmbH|SPV]]\n* [[Warner Music]]\n* [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]\n* Portal\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]]\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]]\n* Onward With Love\n* Masvidal\n}}\n| website          = http://masvidalien.com/\n}}\n\n'''Paul Albert Masvidal''' (born 20 January 1971) is an American guitarist, songwriter and producer. He is the guitarist, singer, and a founding member of the progressive rock band, [[Cynic (band)|Cynic]]. He has remained a continual member for nearly three decades and has developed numerous other projects including [[\u00c6on Spoke]], Onward with Love, and recent his solo work. Masvidal was ranked in ''[[Loudwire]]''<nowiki/>'s Best 66 Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists Of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/top-hard-rock-metal-guitarists-of-all-time/|title=The 66 Best Hard Rock + Metal Guitarists of All Time|last=Staff|first=Loudwire|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and 50 Best Metal Songwriters Of All Time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/best-metal-songwriters/|title=50 Best Metal Songwriters of All Time|last=DiVita|first=Joe|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nPaul Masvidal was born in San Juan, Puerto Rico to Cuban-American civic and business leader Raul Masvidal. Masvidal's early years were spent in the Miami area where he studied classical guitar with [[Carlos Molina (guitarist)|Carlos Molina]], and in college, with jazz musician, Dave Weissbrot who inspired his love of jazz, [[Steinberger|Steinberger guitars]], and introduced him to [[Buddhist philosophy]]. Masvidal developed an interest in mysticism and esoteric topics from a young age, becoming an initiate to [[Kriya Yoga]] in his late teens and eventually a practitioner of [[Buddhist meditation]] by his late 20s. Masvidal met drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in 1984 at [[Gulliver Schools|Gulliver Academy]] In Miami, where the duo began making music the day they met, eventually forming the pre-Cynic groups, Crypha and Seaweed. Masvidal's eclectic musical tastes ranging from classical to rock, jazz, fusion, and metal along with a innate passion for mysticism came to inform much of his work with Cynic and other projects. Masvidal wrote in detail about early life experiences in his Mett\u0101 Mind Journal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metalsucks.net/2010/04/07/metta-mind-journal-with-cynics-paul-masvidal-the-bird-outside-my-window/|title=METTA MIND JOURNAL WITH CYNIC'S PAUL MASVIDAL: \"THE BIRD OUTSIDE MY WINDOW\"|date=2010-04-07|website=MetalSucks|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> series, which he published on the music blog [[MetalSucks]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nMasvidal co-founded Cynic with drummer [[Sean Reinert]] in the late 80\u2019s, having released four demos from 1988-1991 that circulated in the underground tape trading community. Masvidal developed a reputation in the South Florida music scene for his musicianship and attention began to grow quickly around the band. In 1989, while still in high school, Masvidal toured Mexico as a replacement guitarist for the band [[Death (metal band)|Death]], but declined an invitation to permanently join the band in order to remain committed to Cynic. This had many journalists curious at the time, since Death were emerging as an influential and popular act, but Masvidal persevered with Cynic. However, Masvidal returned to the Death fold replacing guitarist [[James Murphy (guitarist)|James Murphy]] for tour dates on the international ''[[Spiritual Healing (album)|Spiritual Healing]]'' tour in 1990. In 1991, Masvidal and fellow Cynic member Reinert were recruited by Death to record the \"groundbreaking\" ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]''. In 2017, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine placed the album as the 70th greatest metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/the-100-greatest-metal-albums-of-all-time-113614/|title=The 100 Greatest Metal Albums of All Time|last=Christe|first=Christopher R. Weingarten,Tom Beaujour,Hank Shteamer,Kim Kelly,Steve Smith,Brittany Spanos,Suzy Exposito,Richard Bienstock,Kory Grow,Dan Epstein,J D. Considine,Andy Greene,Rob Sheffield,Adrien Begrand,Ian|last2=Weingarten|first2=Christopher R.|date=2017-06-21|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15|last3=Beaujour|first3=Tom|last4=Shteamer|first4=Hank|last5=Kelly|first5=Kim|last6=Smith|first6=Steve|last7=Spanos|first7=Brittany|last8=Exposito|first8=Suzy|last9=Bienstock|first9=Richard}}</ref>. Masvidal toured extensively for ''Human'', in addition to appearing in the [[music video]] for ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7j8vUbMmOwM \"Lack of Comprehension\"]'', which debuted on MTV's [[Headbangers Ball]]. After fulfilling their obligations with Death, both Masvidal and Reinert returned to Cynic in 1992. In 2013, Masvidal joined forces with other original members of the Death ''Human'' line up and toured worldwide in honor of [[Chuck Schuldiner]]'s legacy with the group DTA (Death to All).\n[[File:Cynic, Focus (1993).jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Focus'' (1993)]]\n1993 saw the release of the \u201cprogressive landmark\u201d album, ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' on [[Roadrunner Records]]. ''Focus'' was listed in Rock Hard magazine's book as one of ''The 500 Greatest Rock & Metal Albums of All Time''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rensen|first=Michael|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/best-of-rock-metal-die-500-starksten-scheiben-aller-zeiten/oclc/62273803|title=Best of Rock & Metal: die 500 st\u00e4rksten Scheiben aller Zeiten|last2=Heine|first2=Uwe|last3=Stratmann|first3=Holger|last4=Villalonga|first4=Marc|date=2005|publisher=Heel|isbn=978-3-89880-517-9|location=K\u00f6nigswinter|language=German|oclc=62273803}}</ref>. ''[[Loudwire]]'' writer Graham Hartmann named Focus the ninth best debut metal album of all time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/cynic-focus-best-debut-metal-albums/|title=No. 9: Cynic, 'Focus' \u2013 Best Debut Metal Albums|last=Hartmann|first=Graham|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. Roadrunner released a reissue of Focus in 2004 as a special collector's edition due to high demand. Cynic took a 12 year hiatus in 1995 after recording \"''The Portal Tapes\"'' demos. Masvidal moved to Los Angeles in the fall of 1996, upon being offered a full scholarship at [[Musicians Institute]], where he also began work as a session musician and composer for network TV and film. \n\n[[File:Aeon Spoke Band.jpg|thumb|152x152px|[[\u00c6on Spoke]]|alt=]]During Cynic's hiatus, Masvidal founded [[\u00c6on Spoke]], whose ethereal indie rock was heralded as \"beautiful, exquisite [and] destined for greatness\" by Janice Long, BBC Radio. In 2004, the band received airplay on BBC Radio 2 and XFM for the single \"Silence\". The following year, the track \"Emmanuel\" appeared in the indie breakout film ''[[What the Bleep Do We Know!?]]'' \u00c6on Spoke songs have also appeared on the Warner Bros. television series ''[[Smallville]]'', ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' and the motion picture ''[[Cry Wolf (2005 film)|Cry Wolf]]''. \u00a0Their self-titled debut LP was released in 2007 on SPV Records.\n\n\n[[File:Cynic, Traced In Air (2008).jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Traced In Air'' (2008)]]\nCynic reunited in 2008 to record ''[[Traced in Air|Traced In Air]]'', their comeback opus. In his review<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=The New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/arts/music/01choi.html|title=New CDs|date=2008-11-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, ''New York Times'' music critic Ben Ratliff wrote that Cynic \"should be understood not so much alongside any metal bands but along with the radical harmonic progressives in the last 45 years of pop and jazz: composers like Milton Nascimento, the Beach Boys or Pat Metheny.\" [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] described it as \"A Modern Classic.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/a-modern-classic-cynics-e_b_190622|title=A Modern Classic: Cynic's Traced in Air , A Reunion Album As Good As the Classic Debut|last=Remington|first=Alex|last2=ContributorBlogger|date=2009-05-24|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 and 2011 Cynic released two conceptual records: ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010), featuring re-interpretations of several ''Traced in Air'' tracks, and ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011). ''Rolling Stone'' music critic Hank Shteamer raved in his review<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16034-carbon-based-anatomy-ep/|title=Cynic: Carbon-Based Anatomy EP|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> of ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'': \"The title track is a perfectly paced stunner...Cynic sounds fully liberated, not just from their metal past but from any aesthetic concern other than assembling a great song.\" The album's opening track ''\"Amidst The Coals\"'' features artist, [[Amy Correia]] singing an adaptation of an Amazonian [[Icaro]], inspired by Masvidal's work with the South American entheogenic brew, [[Ayahuasca]]. \u00a0  <gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Cynic, Re-Traced (2010).jpg|Cynic, ''Re-Traced'' (2010)\nFile:Cynic, Carbon-Based Anatomy (2011).jpg|Cynic, ''Carbon-Based Anatomy'' (2011)\n</gallery>\n[[File:Cynic, Kindly Bent to Free Us (2014).jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Cynic, ''Kindly Bent to Free Us'' (2014)]]\nCynic's third full-length album, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'', released in 2014, was hailed by [[Malcolm Dome|Malcome Dome]] of ''[[Prog (magazine)|Prog]]'' magazine as \"an album that transcends all the limitations of genre and era... There are few albums which can claim such a remarkable hold.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/cynic-kindly-bent-to-free-us|title=Cynic: Kindly Bent To Free Us|last=February 2014|first=Malcolm Dome 11|website=Prog Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The album rose to No. 4 on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Heatseekers chart in February 2014 and was No. 1 on CMJ's Loud Rock Chart the following month. \n<nowiki/><blockquote>\"Kindly Bent to Free Us [is] an album that, while most definitely in the realm of prog rock, has the kind of open, unpretentious air that makes Rush such an easy-to-love band.\" - [[AllMusic.com|allmusic.com]]</blockquote><blockquote>\"The alchemy of front man Paul Masvidal (vocals, guitars & keyboards) combined with rhythmaniac Sean Reinert (drums) and the technically divine Sean Malone (bass), make Cynic one of the finest Prog Rock bands to have ever of landed on Planet Earth\" - [https://burningfist.co.uk burningfist.co.uk]</blockquote>[[File:Onward with Love.jpg|left|thumb|150x150px|Onward with Love, 2015]]In 2015, Masvidal ventured into the performing-arts world with masked duo Onward with Love (OwL), a musical collaboration with acclaimed singer-songwriter [[Amy Correia]]. The pair's singular points of view make for an intriguing synthesis of Eastern-influenced philosophy, symbolist poetry, American blues, jazz and experimental rock. OwL has performed in concert venues, hospices and art galleries around greater Los Angeles. In 2015, OwL unveiled a video for the song ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHrg6W6gddY \"Kali In My Arms\"]'', which was featured in the HBO TV series and film, ''[[Looking (TV series)|Looking]]''. The duo officially released the song [https://distrokid.com/hyperfollow/onwardwithlove/kali-in-my-arms digitally] in 2019 have plans to release a full-length record by 2021.\n\nIn 2016, Masvidal, along with collaborator [[Amy Correia]], composed the musical score for the award-winning feature film ''[[The Tiger Hunter]]'', featuring lead actor [[Danny Pudi]]. The film was released in over 60 cities nationwide,won the grand jury prize for narrative feature at the Los Angeles Asian Pacific Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/los-angeles-asian-pacific-film-festival-the-tiger-hunter-hooligan-sparrow-win-1201768412/|title=\u2018Tiger Hunter\u2019 and \u2018Hooligan Sparrow\u2019 Win Big at L.A. Asian Pacific Film Festival|last=Cavassuto|first=Maria|last2=Cavassuto|first2=Maria|date=2016-05-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and garnered effusively positive reviews from The New York Times, Los Angeles Times, and more. In 2017, Correia and Masvidal scored the main title to CW Networks, game show \"Save To Win\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pilotonline.com/business/article_2428e2c3-f385-5b17-805a-58e61daa7316.html|title=Family Dollar launches &quot;Save to Win&quot; game show on The CW|last=Pierceall|first=Kimberly|website=pilotonline.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Creators Scott Weiner and Paul Reaney described the song as \"acid jazz meets 70's game show.\" Most recently the duo composed end title song for the feature film [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lKzGNIk4XBI&fbclid=IwAR2nbrqJe9IjfUrakvWKP7oR6KQIJyRg711IfBCckEqKdKsffbYMBsMmDkU ''The Deported''] which made the official selection at the prestigious New York Latin Film Festival and the [[Beverly Hills Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beverlyhillsfilmfestival.com/2019-official-selection-fri/|title=2019 Official Selection Fri {{!}} Beverly Hills Film Festival {{!}} Official Site|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.  \n\nMasvidal also writes and performs music for television and motion pictures. His credits include main title (composer credit) on an Emmy nominated NBC teen series show ''[[Operation Junkyard]]'', short films ''The Yellow Umbrella'', ''A Bride in Black'', assistant to [[Ben Vaughn]] and session musician for Carsey Warner network sitcoms ''[[That '70s Show]]'' and ''[[3rd Rock from the Sun]]''. In 2013 Masvidal founded composing collective [http://stillmotionmusic.com/ Still Motion Music] which scored music for numerous TV series on H2, National Geographic, Bravo, ABC and PBS. Masvidal also has a library songs regularly performed on network and cable television. Music writer Jeff Wagner, in his book ''[[Mean Deviation (book)|Mean Deviation]]:'' Four Decades of Progressive Heavy Metal, stated that \"any viewer of ''3rd Rock from the Sun'', ''That '70s Show'', ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'', ''[[Queer as Folk (2000 TV series)|Queer as Folk]]'', and any number of random television programs has probably stumbled across Cynic's core members without even knowing it.\" In 2015, Masvidal produced a children's album for actor [[Jim Carrey]] titled ''How Roland Rolls''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howrolandrolls.com/the-ep/|title=The EP {{!}} How Roland Rolls|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\n[[File:Cynic Humanoid.jpg|thumb|150x150px|Cynic - Humanoid (Single)|alt=]]In January 2018, Cynic released a digital single, titled ''\"Humanoid\"''. The song featured new drummer, Matt Lynch with longtime bassist and collaborator, [[Sean Malone]]. \"Humanoid\" marked the first new music from the progressive pioneers since the band's 2014 album ''Kindly Bent to Free Us''. The artwork features a detail from the painting \"Ayahuasca Dream\" by [[Robert Venosa]], Cynic's longtime collaborator and celebrated artist who passed away in 2011. <blockquote>\"Venosa and Masvidal recognized each other as fellow artists in the pursuit of authentic, spirit-based artistic expression in sound and imagery.\" - \u00a0[https://www.martinahoffmann.com/ Martina Hoffman], painter and Venosa's wife, from the book ...''And Justice for Art, Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers'' by Ramon Martos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://andjusticeforart.bigcartel.com/product/and-justice-for-art-stories-about-heavy-metal-album-covers-volume-2|title=...And Justice For Art: Stories About Heavy Metal Album Covers|last=Art|first=And Justice For|website=And Justice For Art|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 2019 and 2020 Masvidal ventured into releasing work as a solo artist under the name 'Masvidal' releasing three conceptual albums titled ''Mythical Human Vessel.'' The artwork for the three albums was designed by visual artists Igraine Grey and Jonatan Martinez aka [https://cargocollective.com/greymar/about Greymar]. <gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:MYTHICAL Album.jpg|MYTHICAL\nFile:HUMAN Album by Masvidal.jpg|HUMAN\nFile:VESSEL Album by Masvidal.jpg|VESSEL\n</gallery>Produced by three-time [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] winner Warren Riker (Lauryn Hill, Fugees, Santana). Drawing on influences from musicians [[John Lennon]], [[Brian Eno]], [[Chet Baker]], Russill Paul and [https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/artist/Elliott Elliott Smith] to visual artists - [[Mark Rothko]], [[Cai Guo-Qiang]], [[Hilma af Klint|Hilma af Klimt]], the songs embrace concise forms and catchy melodies in spite of their often painful subject matters of loss, depression, and heartache. In Masvidal's view, \"pain is not something to be feared but embraced as inevitable and, ultimately, a doorway.\" ''Billboard'' described the work\u00a0''Mythical Human Vessel'', finds Masvidal at his most vulnerable, often with just a guitar and vocals, while experimenting with brain entrainment, a series of pulsing sounds that are said to lead to enhanced neural perception and memory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8513968/paul-masvidal-interview-brain-experiment|title=Paul Masvidal's Solo Project Doubles as a Brain Entrainment Experiment|date=2019-05-31|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOther press related to MHV: Human<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8532688/paul-masvidal-interview-human-track-by-track-rundown|title=Paul Masvidal 'Human' Track-by-Track: Cynic Frontman Explains New EP|date=2019-10-10|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> / Vessel<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9324719/paul-masvidal-releases-final-installment-of-mythical-human-vessel-trilogy?fbclid=IwAR3AhHwixQ7LGFZjUtZ1hWW9-ErQ3yH2rH8LZ-k6OsLBmgOGJLyAy0MUqqs|title=Paul Masvidal&#39;s &#39;Mythical Human Vessel&#39; Finale|date=2020-03-06|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nBen Ratliff of the ''New York Times'' referred to Masvidal's \"philosophic lyrics\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratliff|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/02/arts/music/02buried.html|title=From Jazz-Rock Fusion to Progressive Metal, With a Virtuosic Accompaniment|date=2010-02-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> stating that he is \"a musician who can expand his own sense of calm into an aggressive, extravagant art\".\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAs an inventor, Masvidal filed a successful patent ([http://www.vidatak.com/index.html Vidatak] EZ Board US Patent No. 6,422,875) in 1999 (which was approved in 2002), involving a device to assist voice-disabled individuals. Masvidal's interest stems from his extensive volunteer work with AIDS patients, the terminally ill and the elderly in the Los Angeles area.\n\nIn May 2014, the [[Los Angeles Times]] did a front cover story on Masvidal's coming out as a homosexual along with fellow Cynic member [[Sean Reinert]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-c1-gay-heavy-metal-20140508-story.html|title=Great Read: Cynic's Paul Masvidal, Sean Reinert are out and ready to be loud|date=2014-05-08|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. For gay pride month June 2017, Masvidal talked to Billboard about his experiences as gay man in the rock and metal community<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/7842075/paul-masvidal-lgbtq-hard-rock-metal|title=Paul Masvidal on LGBTQ Acceptance In the Hard Rock/Metal Community|date=2017-06-29|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>:<blockquote>\"We were always outsiders as a metal band, not only sonically with our influences coming at it from a totally different direction, but we never wore the masculine badge as being tough guys or any of that. We oftentimes wore very colorful clothes, so we were just a little more eccentric and kind of outside the box...\" </blockquote>In an interview<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tricycle.org/trikedaily/buddhist-rocker/|title=The Heavy Metta of a Buddhist Rocker|last=Strahley|first=Erin|date=2018-11-07|website=Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> for [[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|Tricycle magazine]], Masvidal elaborated on the origins of Cynic's name, Buddhism and his creative process. \n\nMasvidal has been a [[vegetarian]] since 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/progmetal/comments/2gsxkr/greeting_this_is_paul_welcome_to_my_ama/|title=r/progmetal - Greeting this is Paul, welcome to my AMA!|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nMasvidal began work with his brother, [https://www.dancingshiva.com/about/our-founder Maheshananda], an established and influential teacher of Yoga and Ayurveda in 2018, offering Ayurvedic and [[Cannabidiol|CBD]]-based products with company ''[https://morelifemarket.com/ More Life Market]''.\n\nMasvidal has most recently entered into the creation of physical objects, developing [[Orgone|Orgonite]] related devices and [[Sacred geometry|sacred geometric]] amulets. His interest in [[Cosmology]], [[Consciousness]], [[Extra-terrestrials|Extra-Terrestrials]], [[Unidentified flying object|UFOs]], [[Crop circle|crop circles]] and their connection to his spiritual interests have become integral to his work as an artist.\n\n==Gear==\n[[File:Masvidalien Cosmo.png|thumb|152x152px|The Masvidalien Cosmo|alt=]]Masvidal has been playing [[Steinberger]] GM & GR headless 6-string guitars since his beginnings as a professional musician. Although he was seen by far the most with this instrument, he was also seen playing a Gibson SG with \u00c6on Spoke. Since Masvidal's association with the DTA (earlier called ''Death To All'') tours in 2013, a touring tribute to his former band [[Death (metal band)|Death]] and the songs of [[Chuck Schuldiner]], he has been playing his signature Strandberg ''Masvidalien'' headless 6-string guitar. He also had his recording debut with this new Strandberg guitar on Cynic's 2014 release, ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]''.\nMasvidal lent his name to a line of signature instruments aptly named, ''Masvidalien Cosmo''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://strandbergguitars.com/artists/paul-masvidal/|title=Paul Masvidal|website=.strandberg* Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> produced by Sweden's award-winning '''[https://strandbergguitars.com/ .strandberg* Guitars]'''. \n\n<br /> \n==Discography==\n\n=== Cynic ===\n\n* ''[[Focus (Cynic album)|Focus]]'' (1993)\n*''Focus'' 'Remastered Re-Issue with bonus tracks' (2004)\n* ''[[Traced in Air]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Re-Traced]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Carbon-Based Anatomy]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Portal Tapes]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Kindly Bent to Free Us]]'' (2014)\n*''Uroboric Forms - The Complete Demo Recordings'' (2017)\n*''Humanoid'' single release (2018)\n*''Traced In Air''\u00a0'Remixed' (2019)\n\n=== Solo ===\n\n* ''Mythical'' (2019)\n* ''Human'' (2019)\n* ''Vessel'' (2020) \n\n=== Other ===\n\n* [[Death (metal band)|Death]] \u2212 ''[[Human (Death album)|Human]]'' (1991)\n*[[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[Above the Buried Cry]]'' (2004)\n* [[\u00c6on Spoke]] \u2212 ''[[\u00c6on Spoke (album)|\u00c6on Spoke]]'' (2007)\n\n=== Guest/Session ===\n\n*[[Master (American band)|Master]] \u2013 ''On The Seventh Day God Created... Master'' (1991) (guitars)\n*[[Terri Nunn|Terri Nunn (Berlin)]] (1997) - co-wrote songs for an unreleased solo album\n*[[Gordian Knot (band)|Gordian Knot]] \u2212 ''[[Emergent (album)|Emergent]]'' (2003)\n*[[Amy Correia]] - ''Lakeville'' (2004) (Guitar, Piano, keyboards)\n*[[Exivious]] \u2013 ''Exivious'' (2009) (guitar solo on \"Embrace The Unknown\")\n*[[Devin Townsend Project]] \u2013 ''[[Deconstruction (Devin Townsend Project album)|Deconstruction]]'' (2010) (vocals on \"Sumeria\")\n*[[Gene Ween|Aaron Freeman]] - ''Marvelous Clouds''\u00a0 (2012) (Acoustic guitar)\n*[[Chris Schlarb]] \u2013 ''Psychic Temple II'' (2013)\n* [[Persefone]] \u2013 ''AATHMA'' (2017) (vocals on ''Living Waves'')\n* [[Neil Grant]] - ''Location Persuader'' (2017) (Guitars & vocals on \"Throw me out there!\")\n* [[Contrarian]] \u2013 ''To Perceive Is to Suffer'' (2017) (vocals on \"At Fate's Hands\")\n*[https://stephanepigeon.com/ Dr. Stefane Pigeon] (2019) - ''Mythical Human Vessel'''s Isochronic Tones, Transdimensional Traveler 'Mynoise' player\n* BRVMAK - ''In Nomine Patris'' (2019) (vocals on \"Omnipotence\")  \n* Moon Destroys - ''Maiden Voyage'' (2020) (vocals on \"Stormbringer\")\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Cynic}}\n{{Death (band)}}\n{{\u00c6on Spoke}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masvidal, Paul}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Death metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Death (metal band) members]]\n[[Category:Progressive metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Cynic (band) members]]\n[[Category:\u00c6on Spoke members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Abhaysingh1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated intro", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Masvidal"}
{"title_page": "Chugrum River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Chugrum River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth             = [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]]\n  | progression       = [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva]]\u2192 {{RVeslyana}}\n  | length            = {{convert|21|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n\n'''Chugrum''' ({{lang-ru|\u0427\u0443\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043c}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a right tributary of the [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Veslyana River]]. The river is about {{convert|21|km|mi}} long.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180024|script-title=ru:\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u0427\u0443\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043c|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Chugrum River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]]\n  | progression       = \n  | length            = {{convert|21|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n\n'''Chugrum''' ({{lang-ru|\u0427\u0443\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043c}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a right tributary of the [[Utva River (Perm Krai)|Utva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Veslyana River]]. The river is about {{convert|21|km|mi}} long.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180024|script-title=ru:\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u0427\u0443\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043c|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chugrum_River"}
{"title_page": "Offa's Dyke Path", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox hiking trail\n| name = Offa's Dyke Path\n| photo = Offa's Dyke Path signpost. - geograph.org.uk - 501938.jpg\n| caption = Offa's Dyke Path signpost in [[Denbighshire]]\n| location = [[England|English]]/[[Wales|Welsh]] border\n| designation = [[National Trail]]\n| length_mi = 177\n| trailheads = [[Sedbury]] {{coord|51.6324|-2.6482|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=Offa's Dyke Path, Sedbury trailhead}}<br>[[Prestatyn]] {{coord |53.3423|-3.4126|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=Offa's Dyke Path, Prestatyn trailhead}}\n| use = [[Hiking]]\n| lowest = \n| difficulty = \n| season = All year\n| sights = \n|elev_gain_and_loss={{Convert|9085|m|0}}|established=1971|highest_m=703|highest_name=[[Hatterrall Ridge]]|route_state=}}\n'''Offa's Dyke Path''' (Welsh: ''Llwybr Clawdd Offa'') is a [[long-distance footpath]] following closely the [[Wales\u2013England border]]. Opened in 1971, it is one of Britain's [[National Trail]]s and draws [[hillwalking|walkers]] from throughout the world. About {{convert|60|mi|km|adj=off|abbr=}} of the {{convert|177|mi|km|adj=on}} route either follows, or keeps close company with, the remnants of [[Offa's Dyke]], an [[Earthworks (engineering)|earthwork]], most of which was probably constructed in the late 8th century on the orders of [[Offa of Mercia|King Offa of Mercia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/|title=Long Distance Walkers Association|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ldwa.org.uk|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n== Walking trail ==\nTraveling south to north, starting by the [[Severn Estuary]] at [[Sedbury]], near [[Chepstow]], and finishing at [[Prestatyn]] on the north coast. The walk will take an average walker roughly 12 days to complete.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Mileages along the Path (South to North)|url=http://www.offasdyke.demon.co.uk/mileages.htm |publisher=Offa's Dyke Association |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref> Following a man-made border and the ancient monument of Offa's Dyke, rather than natural features, the dyke path crosses a variety of landscapes. The route crosses the [[Black Mountains, Wales|Black Mountains]], the [[Shropshire Hills]], including the many ups and downs of the 'Switchback', the [[Eglwyseg]] moors north of [[Llangollen]] and the [[Clwydian Range]]. \n\nThe route passes through the counties of [[Monmouthshire]], [[Gloucestershire]], [[Powys]], [[Herefordshire]], [[Shropshire]], [[Wrexham County Borough|Wrexham]], [[Denbighshire]] and [[Flintshire]]. The [[Welsh Marches]] (Marchia Wallie) is a term used to describe this border region between England and Wales, since it was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] in 1086.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Carter|first=Keith|title=Offa's Dyke Path|publisher=Trailblazer Publications|year=2011|isbn=978-1-905864-35-5|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ludlow.org.uk/historyofthemarches.html|title=A History of The Welsh Marches|website=www.ludlow.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n[[File:Knighton in Powys.jpg|thumb|Knighton in Powys]]\nIt passes through, or close to, the towns of [[Chepstow]], [[Monmouth]], [[Abergavenny]], [[Hay-on-Wye]], [[Kington, Herefordshire|Kington]], [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]], [[Montgomery, Wales|Montgomery]] and then in and around the [[North Wales]] towns and villages of [[Llangollen]], [[Llandegla]], Clwyd Gate, [[Bodfari]] and [[Dyserth]].\n\nThe half-way point of the path is marked by the Offa's Dyke Centre in [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]] ({{coord |52.3458|-3.0517|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title|name=Offa's Dyke Centre}}).<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=The Offa's Dyke Centre in Knighton, Powys|url=http://www.offasdyke.demon.co.uk/odc.htm | publisher=Offa's Dyke Association |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref>  There used to be around 600 [[stile]]s along the route, but many of these have now been replaced by [[kissing gate]]s.\n\n{{cquote|\na certain vigorous king called Offa......had a great dyke built between Wales and Mercia from sea to sea.||| [[Asser]]}}\n\n== Route ==\n[[File:Chepstow Castle from Offa's Dyke Path.jpg|thumb|Chepstow Castle from Offa's Path|alt=]]\nPlaces on the route and highlights on or near the trail: <ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Tintern Abbey from Offa's Dyke Path.jpg|thumb|Tintern Abbey from Offa's Path|alt=]]\n\n=== Chepstow to Monmouth ===\n\n*[[Sedbury]] Cliffs: [[Severn Estuary]], [[Severn Bridge]]\n*[[Chepstow]]: [[Chepstow Castle]], [[River Wye]]\n* View of [[Tintern Abbey]] from the [[Devil's Pulpit]]\n*[[Redbrook]]: Iron railway bridge\n*[[The Kymin]] naval temple\n\n[[File:Monnow Bridge over River Monnow at Monmouth.jpg|thumb|Monnow Bridge at Monmouth]]\n[[File:St Cadoc's Church at Llangattock Lingoed.jpg|thumb|St Cadoc's at Llangattock Lingoed]]\n\n=== Monmouth to Hay-on-Wye ===\n[[File:Black Mountain Top.jpg|thumb|The summit of the [[Black Mountain (hill)|Black Mountain]] crossed by the Offa's Dyke Path|alt=]]\n\n*[[Monmouth]]: [[Monnow Bridge]]\n*[[White Castle, Monmouthshire|White Castle]]\n*[[Llangattock Lingoed]]: [[St Cadoc's Church, Llangattock Lingoed|St Cadoc's church]]\n*[[Pandy, Monmouthshire|Pandy]]\n*[[Hatterrall Ridge|Hatterall Ridge]] is the highest point on the trail at {{convert|703|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Black Mountains, Wales|Black Mountains]]\n\n=== Hay-on-Wye to Knighton ===\n\n*[[Hay-on-Wye]]\n*[[Newchurch, Monmouthshire|Newchurch]]\n*[[Gladestry]]\n*[[Hergest Ridge]] with wild ponies, {{convert|425|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Kington, Herefordshire|Kington]]\n* Hawthorn Hill, {{convert|406|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n\n[[Image:Offa's Dyke near Clun.jpg|thumb|Dyke near Clun]]\n\n=== Knighton to Montgomery ===\n\n*[[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]]: Offa's Dyke visitor centre\n* Panpunton Hill, {{convert|374|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n* Cwm-Sanaham Hill {{convert|406|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n* Llanfair Hill, highest point of the dyke at {{convert|430|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n* Churchtown and Edenhope Hill\n\n=== Montgomery to Llanymynech ===\n\n*[[Montgomery, Powys|Montgomery]]\n*[[Long Mountain (Powys)|Beacon Ring]] [[Iron Age]] hill fort (Caer Digoll)\n*[[Buttington]]\n* Alongside [[Montgomery Canal]] and dyke beside [[River Severn]]\n*[[Four Crosses, Powys|Four Crosses]]\n\n[[File:Offa's Dyke Path through Racecourse Woods.jpg|thumb|Path through Racecourse Woods]]\n\n=== Llanymynech to Trevor ===\n[[File:Pontcysyllte Aqueduct carrying Llangollen Canal over RIver Dee.jpg|thumb|Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]]\n\n*[[Llanymynech]]\n* Moelydd, {{convert|285|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Trefonen]]\n* Oswestry old racecourse at Racecourse Common\n* Craignant\n*[[Chirk Castle]]\n*[[Llangollen Canal]]\n*[[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]] ([[World Heritage Site]]) over the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]]\n\n[[File:Eglwyseg Crags from Offa's Dyke Path.jpg|thumb|Eglwyseg Crags from the Path]]\n[[File:View from Jubilee Tower at Moel Famu summit.jpg|thumb|View from Jubilee Tower]]\n\n=== Trevor to Prestatyn ===\n\n*[[Trevor, Wrexham|Trevor]]\n*Llangollen Castle\n*[[Eglwyseg|Eglwyseg Crags]]\n*[[Llandegla Forest]] (with mountain bike trails)\n*[[Llandegla]]\n*[[Clwydian Range]] of hills:\n**Around Moel-Y-Plas, {{convert|440|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}, Moel Llanfair, {{convert|447|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}, [[Moel Gyw]], {{convert|467|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}} and [[Foel Fenlli]], {{convert|511|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n**[[Moel Famau|Moel Famu]], {{convert|555|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}} and [[Jubilee Tower]] at summit\n**Around Moel Dywyll, {{convert|472|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}, Moel Llys-Y-Coed, {{convert|465|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}} and [[Moel Arthur]], {{convert|455|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n**[[Penycloddiau|Pen-Y-Cloddiau]] hill fort at {{convert|440|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Bodfari]]\n*[[Rhuallt]]\n*[[Prestatyn]]: Offa's Dyke Monument on the beach\n\n==Promotion and media==\nVarious bodies on either side of the border are collaborating on a sustainable [[tourism]] partnership, a principal focus of which is ''Walking with Offa'', both on the trail but also in what has been dubbed [[Offa's Country]] i.e. in a corridor along the border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/wales/entries/2d59dab0-a1a5-3c80-9d0b-9517b9300704|title=Walking along an ancient border|date=2011-11-09|website=BBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe path was the focus of an episode of the [[Channel 4]] program ''[[Britain's Ancient Tracks with Tony Robinson]]''.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n*[http://www.offasdyke.demon.co.uk/ The Offa's Dyke Association]\n*[http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/offas-dyke-path Offa's Dyke Path on the National Trail website]\n*[https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Offa%27s+Dyke+Path+National+Trail Offa's Dyke Path National Trail - Long Distance Walkers Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080922031918/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/offasdyke.html Rambers' Association: Offa's Dyke Path National Trail]\n*[http://www.hikeview.co.uk/OffasDyke/OffasDykePage.html  Map of the Offa's Dyke Path in 2 mile sections]\n\n{{Long-distance footpaths in Wales}}\n{{UK Trails}}\n{{Transport in Powys}}\n\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recreational walks in Wales]]\n[[Category:Footpaths in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Footpaths in Herefordshire]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in Wales]]\n[[Category:Footpaths in Powys]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in England]]\n[[Category:England\u2013Wales border]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox hiking trail\n| name = Offa's Dyke Path\n| photo = Offa's Dyke Path signpost. - geograph.org.uk - 501938.jpg\n| caption = Offa's Dyke Path signpost in [[Denbighshire]]\n| location = [[England|English]]/[[Wales|Welsh]] border\n| designation = [[National Trail]]\n| length_mi = 177\n| trailheads = [[Sedbury]] {{coord|51.6324|-2.6482|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=Offa's Dyke Path, Sedbury trailhead}}<br>[[Prestatyn]] {{coord |53.3423|-3.4126|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=Offa's Dyke Path, Prestatyn trailhead}}\n| use = [[Hiking]]\n| lowest = \n| difficulty = \n| season = All year\n| sights = \n|elev_gain_and_loss={{Convert|9085|m|0}}|established=1971|highest_m=703|highest_name=[[Hatterrall Ridge]]|route_state=}}\n'''Offa's Dyke Path''' (Welsh: ''Llwybr Clawdd Offa'') is a [[long-distance footpath]] following closely the [[Wales\u2013England border]]. Opened in 1971, it is one of Britain's [[National Trail]]s and draws [[hillwalking|walkers]] from throughout the world. About {{convert|60|mi|km|adj=off|abbr=}} of the {{convert|177|mi|km|adj=on}} route either follows, or keeps close company with, the remnants of [[Offa's Dyke]], an [[Earthworks (engineering)|earthwork]], most of which was probably constructed in the late 8th century on the orders of [[Offa of Mercia|King Offa of Mercia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/|title=Long Distance Walkers Association|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ldwa.org.uk|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n== Walking trail ==\nTraveling south to north, starting by the [[Severn Estuary]] at [[Sedbury]], near [[Chepstow]], and finishing at [[Prestatyn]] on the north coast. The walk will take an average walker roughly 12 days to complete.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Mileages along the Path (South to North)|url=http://www.offasdyke.demon.co.uk/mileages.htm |publisher=Offa's Dyke Association |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref> Following a man-made border and the ancient monument of Offa's Dyke, rather than natural features, the dyke path crosses a variety of landscapes. The route crosses the [[Black Mountains, Wales|Black Mountains]], the [[Shropshire Hills]], including the many ups and downs of the 'Switchback', the [[Eglwyseg]] moors north of [[Llangollen]] and the [[Clwydian Range]]. \n\nThe route passes through the counties of [[Monmouthshire]], [[Gloucestershire]], [[Powys]], [[Herefordshire]], [[Shropshire]], [[Wrexham County Borough|Wrexham]], [[Denbighshire]] and [[Flintshire]]. The [[Welsh Marches]] (Marchia Wallie) is a term used to describe this border region between England and Wales, since it was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] in 1086.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Carter|first=Keith|title=Offa's Dyke Path|publisher=Trailblazer Publications|year=2011|isbn=978-1-905864-35-5|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ludlow.org.uk/historyofthemarches.html|title=A History of The Welsh Marches|website=www.ludlow.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIt passes through, or close to, the towns of [[Chepstow]], [[Monmouth]], [[Abergavenny]], [[Hay-on-Wye]], [[Kington, Herefordshire|Kington]], [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]], [[Montgomery, Wales|Montgomery]] and then in and around the [[North Wales]] towns and villages of [[Llangollen]], [[Llandegla]], Clwyd Gate, [[Bodfari]] and [[Dyserth]].\n\nThe half-way point of the path is marked by the Offa's Dyke Centre in [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]] ({{coord |52.3458|-3.0517|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title|name=Offa's Dyke Centre}}).<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=The Offa's Dyke Centre in Knighton, Powys|url=http://www.offasdyke.demon.co.uk/odc.htm | publisher=Offa's Dyke Association |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref>  There used to be around 600 [[stile]]s along the route, but many of these have now been replaced by [[kissing gate]]s.\n\n{{cquote|\na certain vigorous king called Offa......had a great dyke built between Wales and Mercia from sea to sea.||| [[Asser]]}}\n\n== Route ==\n[[File:Chepstow Castle from Offa's Dyke Path.jpg|thumb|Chepstow Castle from Offa's Path|alt=]]\nPlaces on the route and highlights on or near the trail: <ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Tintern Abbey from Offa's Dyke Path.jpg|thumb|Tintern Abbey from Offa's Path|alt=]]\n\n=== Chepstow to Monmouth ===\n\n*[[Sedbury]] Cliffs: [[Severn Estuary]], [[Severn Bridge]]\n*[[Chepstow]]: [[Chepstow Castle]], [[River Wye]]\n* View of [[Tintern Abbey]] from the [[Devil's Pulpit]]\n*[[Redbrook]]: Iron railway bridge\n*[[The Kymin]] naval temple\n\n[[File:Monnow Bridge over River Monnow at Monmouth.jpg|thumb|Monnow Bridge at Monmouth]]\n[[File:St Cadoc's Church at Llangattock Lingoed.jpg|thumb|St Cadoc's at Llangattock Lingoed]]\n\n=== Monmouth to Hay-on-Wye ===\n[[File:Black Mountain Top.jpg|thumb|The summit of the [[Black Mountain (hill)|Black Mountain]] crossed by the Offa's Dyke Path|alt=]]\n\n*[[Monmouth]]: [[Monnow Bridge]]\n*[[White Castle, Monmouthshire|White Castle]]\n*[[Llangattock Lingoed]]: [[St Cadoc's Church, Llangattock Lingoed|St Cadoc's church]]\n*[[Pandy, Monmouthshire|Pandy]]\n*[[Hatterrall Ridge|Hatterall Ridge]] is the highest point on the trail at {{convert|703|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Black Mountains, Wales|Black Mountains]]\n\n=== Hay-on-Wye to Knighton ===\n\n*[[Hay-on-Wye]]\n*[[Newchurch, Monmouthshire|Newchurch]]\n*[[Gladestry]]\n*[[Hergest Ridge]] with wild ponies, {{convert|425|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Kington, Herefordshire|Kington]]\n* Hawthorn Hill, {{convert|406|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n\n[[Image:Offa's Dyke near Clun.jpg|thumb|Dyke near Clun]]\n\n=== Knighton to Montgomery ===\n\n*[[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]]: Offa's Dyke visitor centre\n* Panpunton Hill, {{convert|374|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n* Cwm-Sanaham Hill {{convert|406|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n* Llanfair Hill, highest point of the dyke at {{convert|430|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n* Churchtown and Edenhope Hill\n\n=== Montgomery to Llanymynech ===\n\n*[[Montgomery, Powys|Montgomery]]\n*[[Long Mountain (Powys)|Beacon Ring]] [[Iron Age]] hill fort (Caer Digoll)\n*[[Buttington]]\n* Alongside [[Montgomery Canal]] and dyke beside [[River Severn]]\n*[[Four Crosses, Powys|Four Crosses]]\n\n[[File:Offa's Dyke Path through Racecourse Woods.jpg|thumb|Path through Racecourse Woods]]\n\n=== Llanymynech to Trevor ===\n[[File:Pontcysyllte Aqueduct carrying Llangollen Canal over RIver Dee.jpg|thumb|Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]]\n\n*[[Llanymynech]]\n* Moelydd, {{convert|285|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Trefonen]]\n* Oswestry old racecourse at Racecourse Common\n* Craignant\n*[[Chirk Castle]]\n*[[Llangollen Canal]]\n*[[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]] ([[World Heritage Site]]) over the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]]\n\n[[File:Eglwyseg Crags from Offa's Dyke Path.jpg|thumb|Eglwyseg Crags from the Path]]\n[[File:View from Jubilee Tower at Moel Famu summit.jpg|thumb|View from Jubilee Tower]]\n\n=== Trevor to Prestatyn ===\n\n*[[Trevor, Wrexham|Trevor]]\n*Llangollen Castle\n*[[Eglwyseg|Eglwyseg Crags]]\n*[[Llandegla Forest]] (with mountain bike trails)\n*[[Llandegla]]\n*[[Clwydian Range]] of hills:\n**Around Moel-Y-Plas, {{convert|440|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}, Moel Llanfair, {{convert|447|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}, [[Moel Gyw]], {{convert|467|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}} and [[Foel Fenlli]], {{convert|511|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n**[[Moel Famau|Moel Famu]], {{convert|555|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}} and [[Jubilee Tower]] at summit\n**Around Moel Dywyll, {{convert|472|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}, Moel Llys-Y-Coed, {{convert|465|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}} and [[Moel Arthur]], {{convert|455|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n**[[Penycloddiau|Pen-Y-Cloddiau]] hill fort at {{convert|440|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=}}\n*[[Bodfari]]\n*[[Rhuallt]]\n*[[Prestatyn]]: Offa's Dyke Monument on the beach\n\n==Promotion and media==\nVarious bodies on either side of the border are collaborating on a sustainable [[tourism]] partnership, a principal focus of which is ''Walking with Offa'', both on the trail but also in what has been dubbed [[Offa's Country]] i.e. in a corridor along the border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/wales/entries/2d59dab0-a1a5-3c80-9d0b-9517b9300704|title=Walking along an ancient border|date=2011-11-09|website=BBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe path was the focus of an episode of the [[Channel 4]] program ''[[Britain's Ancient Tracks with Tony Robinson]]''.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n*[http://www.offasdyke.demon.co.uk/ The Offa's Dyke Association]\n*[http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/offas-dyke-path Offa's Dyke Path on the National Trail website]\n*[https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Offa%27s+Dyke+Path+National+Trail Offa's Dyke Path National Trail - Long Distance Walkers Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080922031918/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/offasdyke.html Rambers' Association: Offa's Dyke Path National Trail]\n*[http://www.hikeview.co.uk/OffasDyke/OffasDykePage.html  Map of the Offa's Dyke Path in 2 mile sections]\n\n{{Long-distance footpaths in Wales}}\n{{UK Trails}}\n{{Transport in Powys}}\n\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recreational walks in Wales]]\n[[Category:Footpaths in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Footpaths in Herefordshire]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in Wales]]\n[[Category:Footpaths in Powys]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in England]]\n[[Category:England\u2013Wales border]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Photo added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offa%27s_Dyke_Path"}
